deck_excerpt: Zombies have come a long way
deck_description:
This deck was made with the June 8th banlist in mind.

It has been five months since I last made a zombies deck, and things have gotten out of control very quickly. Five months ago Deer Note wasn't even in Master Duel and Dante was in everyones ED to unbrick bad hands with Uni and E-Tele. Now? Zombies can mill a sixty card deck without grass, spam every lvl 8 and 10 synchro possible, they can scythe lock, have a floodgate field spell that can burden the best deck in the meta, and stops the second best deck, Floowandereeze, altogether. All this while no longer getting locked into zombies. Honestly this deck has become comparable to Adamancipators. Where Adamancipators still has less potential to brick an opening, the end board zombies can make deprecates on Adamacipators as a deck that utilizes a monster type rather than an archetype. You can do anything. Rarely have I not had all three mezuki in grave along with changshi, Chaos Ruler and Doomking. Put whatever you want in the Extra Deck, it doesn't matter, if it is generic and good (or not), zombies will make it. Accesscode, Apollousa, Underworld Goddess, Dweller, Bagooska, Baronne, Chengying, Elf; people are doing Stardust Dragon lines because they can. I know Tearlaments ARE the format, but I would still give zombies a try because they have never been so powerful.

With all that said, this is my deck! It could be 60 cards, and it could play more handtraps and it could even play branded. That is the point of zombies: pure creative liberty. My deck is built to mill; I can get through a turn and end with 6 cards in main and 4 in Extra. I don't play handtraps because I like to see how far I can take a deck with it's own power, and that means going first and praying they don't have hand traps, which in tear format means I have to watch out for an Imperm and a DD Crow which is more than doable.

I do not have enough monster zones, I often have to decide what would be the best end board I can make with only six monsters on it. Thanks to Elf, mezuki, and this decks amazing ability to spam lvl 8 monsters, Mad Mauler is the MVP. Make a lvl 10 synchro, bring back Chaos Ruler from the graveyard, bring back Mauler using elf, make another lvl 10 synchro, target one of those synchros with Mauler and summon Red-Eyes, to resummon that lvl 10 in the GY on your opponents turn. End Boards look like, Elf, Red-Eyes, Baronne, Chengying, Doomking, and Rulkallos. Sometimes I will hold off on the Red-Eyes effect to see what would be better, a Chengying, a Sycthe lock, or a second Doomking depending on how they respond to the first one. Sometimes you even have Superpoly or can send your Tears back with a shuffler only to mill again with Merrli and summon Dragostepelia. Anything, anything, anything you want do you can do with this deck, so start labbing because it has never been a better time to mill with zombies!

Hello I am back with another Mannadium deck profile post June 2023 banlist. The list has kinda changed since last time I posted the first draft but with some changes in the extra deck and and some changes to non-engine cards as well as the side deck. I took out droll and gamma for ash and bystials as well as I put D barrier in the side because they limited gamma, banned super heavy scarecrow, limited purely delicous. You can play droll if you want still if you feel you need it but I believe thats up to you for decide. I chose ash, bystials and D barrier because I am asumming more people will play Branded and Striker since Engane got semi limited and Multi role became unlimited. Ash hits Branded fusion of course and bystials hit the archetype in general which is why I added them in as well as Labrynth. Dimensional barrier is reall good agaisnt Branded and even Kash shutting them off of XYZ, though Kashtira will probably still be the best deck. However I have thought about playing Belle in either the main or side because in testing I rn into alot of bytsials that would banish Visas in GY which hurts alot sincehe is the heart and soul of the deck. I believe we are in a bystial format so be aware of that going forward so be prepared. Another card I thought about playing was destrudo which is another card to add off of Magnamut but I will test more with it and come back with an updated deck if it works. In the extra deck I added IP Masquerena and Underworld goddess. I found myslef having a hard time outing chaos angel going first so that is why I put Underworld goddess and IP was added as just a more easy way to make unicorn if needed. You can play Accesscode if you want which isnt a bad idea but I would need to test more with it and see if it works well.

deck_excerpt: Competitively viable Pure Sacred Beasts deck with synergistic consistency boosters.
deck_description:
INTRO

Greetings! First off, this is by no means a comprehensive guide as I can't get through everything here, so feel free to leave a comment below if you have any questions. I hope you will find this guide useful. If you're looking to learn more about this archetype, see the link below.

STRATEGY

This strategy revolves around summoning your Sacred Beasts (SB) by using the effects of Dark Summoning Beast (DSB) and Chaos Summoning Beast (CSB). You mainly want to use CSB for this, unless you don't care about not being able to attack on the turn you used DSB. To ensure consistency, we have cards like Dark Beckoning Beast (DBB) and Opening of the Spirit Gates (OSG), which I'll be reffering to as »searchers« in this guide. It's important to note, that we don't have any »one card combos« and need to draw our core pieces. This is why we play Piri Reis Map and Allure of Darkness, both excellent cards with their own purpose, but they also have synergy on their own, as Piri can generate fodder for Allure.

Ideally, you will be able to control either (or both) Hamon, Lord of Striking Thunder or Raviel, Lord of Phantasms along side Fallen Paradise to protect them and allowing you to draw 2 cards each turn. Having both of them on the field in addition to Awakening of the Sacred Beasts (ASB) is your ultimate goal. This is because ASB has a Skill Drain-like effect, which has amazing stun potential along side Cerulean Skyfire, which allows us to negate a Spell/Trap activation once per turn.

The Extra Deck doesn't really server any specific purpose, but fills the gaps in our Main Deck strategy instead. You might not always be able to or even want to use the ED. The Knightmare cards are important, because they offer us forms of removal. Salamangreat Almiraj is an essential part of the deck, however, as it can Link off any leftover searchers on the field. Same idea applies to Linkuriboh. Barricadeborg Blocker offers a form of protection and recursion for cards like Cerulean Skyfire, Fallen Paradise and Opening of the Spirit Gates (among other cards). Both Dharc the Dark Charmer, Gloomy and Aussa the Earth Charmer, Immovable are great form of extending plays and disrupting your opponents GY. I:P Masquerena is a great going first tool, if you're going to be able to trigger her effect and SS Apollousa, Bow of the Goddess on the enemy turn, allowing you to suddenly have free negates on your field. There are other generic ED monsters worth considering, but I feel like this is a good start to any pure Sacred Beast build.

OTHER CARDS & UPGRADES

You could always opt-in to run a variety of engines, but I'm not going to go over those options in this section. You can check the Discord link below, if you want to learn more about engines that synergize with Sacred Beasts. However, there are a couple option worth discussing here.

The side deck is pretty self explenatory. You need to run some form of Spell/Trap removal such as Cosmic Cyclone or Mystical Space Typhoon, as it's not always worth making Knightmares to deal with that. Raigeki can go hard, aspecially with Dark Ruler No More activated and I prefer this option to Lightning Storm, as you should always have cards on your field. Solemn Strike is optional, but it's great for going first. Radian, the Multidimensional Kaiju can be replaced with other "better" Kaijus, but his DARK typing synergizes with Allure of Darkness. Nibiru, the Primal Being can be swapped out, it's not always great, it depends entirely on your local scene (consider other options listen below).

When considering handtraps and other generic/staple cards, keep these options in your mind:Chaos Hunter, Crossout Designator, Droll & Lock Bird Effect Veiler (replace with Infinite Impermanence and add One for One if you prefer), Ghost Belle & Haunted Mansion, Ghost Ogre & Snow Rabbit and Appointer of the Red Lotus among other cards.

If you feel like spending more, consider adding cards like Forbidden Droplet, Triple Tactics Talent, Pot of Prosperity (replaces Allure, but it conflicts with Fallen Paradise draw effect) and Accesscode Talker among other cards.

THANK YOU

If you enjoyed this guide, please leave a comment and/or a reaction below. I post builds for less popular casual and non-meta builds semi-regularly, so feel free to follow me if you're interested in that sort of thing.

To learn more about this archetype, join the Sacred Beast Discord community: https://discord.gg/rYaeTZJAxr

Let me know if you've got any ideas to improve it.

Guide
Any "Rokket" --> Striker Dragon --> Summon 2nd "Rokket" (either through Boot Sector Launch or another method) --> Striker & new monster for Dillingerous Dragon --> Summon Guardragon Pisty underneath --> Link 3/4/5 (Don't use Pisty for this) --> Activate Pisty's effect, summon "Rokket" --> Activate Dillingerous on the "Rokket" summon --> Link 4/5

Tips
Sending Absorouter Dragon to GY is a good idea, either use it to get Rokket Synchron, Rokket Tracer or Silverrokket Dragon (Rokket Caliber would also work but I don't have one). If Abso has already been used or they're all in the GY, Galactic Spiral Dragon is a good option.
- Tracer can be used to destroy Boot Sector for combo extentions
- Galactic Spiral Dragon, Noctovision Dragon, Red-Eyes Darkness Metal Dragon, White Dragon Wyverburster and Black Dragon Collapserpent are in here for combo extentions.
    - Probably would switch these cards when using side deck
- Moon Mirror Shield is here because it can be (I just like the card)

deck_name: Barrel Dragon Coin Flip Luck Deck
deck_excerpt: Bandit Keith's Barrel Dragon has gotten an upgrade!!
deck_description:
This is not one of my best decks, but a fun one nevertheless. Using no meta cards, this deck relies entirely on the luck of a coin flip! If you call right, pop a card! If you call wrong, well, lets talk about that later!

Use the monstrous, mechanical dragons known as Desperado Barrel Dragon, Barrel Dragon and Blowback Dragon to blast your opponents cards off the board, but remember, you must believe in your coin to get you the best hits! Even if you do get a tripe Tails, you can use Proton Blast in the GY to make all your results Heads. It's not cheating if it's written on the card!

Other than the Barrel Dragons, you also have Arcana Force EX - The Dark Ruler, who will be a 4000 ATK beatstick once you get three monsters on the field, flip a coin and see what upgrade you can get on him! Alongside Arcana, you also have JINZO The Machine Menace, alongside his trusty sidekick Returner. Jinzo The Machine Menance will special summon himself as a 2400 ATK monster while a trap is in the GY or face up on the field (not a Quick Effect). He can whenever tribute himself to rid all traps on the field and summon Returner, who when destroyed will summon Machine Menace again from the GY, but only for a turn, so use him wisely!

You also have cards like BM-4 Spider who can destroy an opponents monster and inflict burn damage, along with the old Blast Sphere that can do similar work. The mini Twin-Barrel Dragon can pop a card if it tosses two Heads. Keeper and Prisma help to get your Gatling Dragon on the field, Keeper can also summon a Barrel Dragon or Blowback from the Deck, but only in facedown defence position, flip him back up the next turn to activate his effect! Fusion Deployment is a free Barrel or Blowback Dragon from the Deck. Heavy Metal Raiders will upgrade your Barrel Dragons considerably, protecting them and boosting their ATK, while also summoning more Dark Machines! Limiter Removal will double your Barrel Dragons up to 5600 ATK (not permanent). 

Mirror Force is a classic way of protecting your board, and Call of The Haunted is yet another classic that brings back anything from the GY!

This isn't a great deck, but it is fun and nostalgic. Good luck!

Pros:

-Bike = Baronne access

Cons:

-Benkei = Brick

Notes:

-All SHS can be Link material for Almiraj if normal summoned

-T3 Bike in hand, Baronne on field --> Recycle Baronne into Accel --> Normal/Pend summon Bike = New Baronne

-Alt line can XYZ Alembertian if needed

-30.21% Open Bike/No Benkei

Thoughts:

-Allows for an alternate line that is more resilient to bystials growing in popularity

-Circular limited means it offers another line if needed through free R4 Alembertian XYZ

-D-shifter increasingly devastating now that gamma is limited, which begs the question: if baronne wasn't being played even when gamma was available, why would SHS be better?

-Droll hurts even more since adding Wakaushi/Soulgaia can mean no superfactorial setup

-ED space doesn't feel too bad. No link spider for nibiru but baronne should theoretically absorb anyway.

deck_description:
I buy alot of structure decks and recently became interested in Skystrikers, though some of the cards are a bit more than I'm willing to pay (*cough* afterburners,area zero *cough* linkage *cough*), so I thought about meshing them with something else I had lying about.

Introducing....Crystal Strikers! Theory was, Crystal beasts also use a lot of spells, which help trigger the second effect of your sky strikers, they also have a lot of good trap cards for countering the opponent, and as well as, can be *crystalised* to empty your main monster zone, to use sky striker spells. Also, helps for making bagooska if needed, and , since you mainly use links...you see what I mean.

Flaws; You have to run the brick of rainbowdragon, which, if you watched the replay , you know. Salvations never really came up, despite running goods(both for dumping engage turn 1 or salvations) This deck isn't exactly the MOST EFFICIENT it could be, but I thought I would do some tests to see, what works and what dosen't.

I might try tune it to what I can actually build for a reasonable price, but I figured I'd push the idea out there to see if anyone else wants to adapt it.

Take the Concept, not the deck...unless you want to lose.

deck_name: A Beginner's Guide to Mannadium (June 2023 Post-CYAC)
deck_excerpt: "Mannadium Prime-Heart has a special defensive ability that stops your opponent from targeting it with card effects. No monsters facing..."
deck_description:
The Mannadium archetype released in Cyberstorm Access is the designated modern synchro successor to strategies like Adamancipator, Virtual World and the (now defunct RIP) Superheavy Samurai - these decks "play solitaire" for several minutes, burning through half of their deck to build an unbreakable board with a gazillion negates. The opposing player cannot play due to the negates. With their gamestate heavily limited, the following turn it is an easy OTK your opponent on the counterattack. On the draw going second, the amount of extenders Mannadium has gives it a decent amount of resilience to play through interruption, breaking boards naturally as it navigates it's combo lines to OTK. 
 
The first wave of Mannadium cards is merely a shell that summons generic boss monsters like Baronne De Fleur, Apollousa, Dis Pater and Chaos Angel. 

In honour of the inferior Mannadium Prime-Heart who will never be competitively viable (card designers what are you thinking?!), here is the infamous Mannadium copy-pasta: 

"Mannadium Prime-Heart has a special defensive ability that stops your opponent from targeting it with card effects. No monsters facing Mannadium Prime-Heart will be safe due to its multiple energy blades! Find this powerful card in Cyberstorm Access, releasing on May 5th!"

Want to see the deck in action? Scroll to the very bottom for the Youtube video!

 
ARCHETYPES AND DECKBUILDING
 
This build of Mannadium is played pure without any other archetypes mixed into it. Most combos require two cards to get started, requiring a Mannadium ball + Starfrost himself - so this deck is maxed out on finding these two cards as much as possible. With this current iteration of the deck, if this combination isn't present in your hand, boards will be suboptimal or non-existent (essentially you bricked). 
 
A small hero engine is included with 3 "A Hero Lives" and 2 "Elemental Hero Prisma." Prisma is extremely useful in this deck representing about two resources upon summon, being able to foolish burial Visas Starfrost (material for Astraloud) and act as Visas on-field, turning on your Mannadium monster's special summon. Since he is "Visas Starfrost" on-field,you can also link him off to summon Scareclaw Light-Heart, further enabling your plays. 
 
9 slots are saved for staple cards, and they are the most impactful handtraps of the meta, Ash Blossom (counters Branded and Labrynth), Droll (counters Mannadium and PUNK Gold Pride) and Impermanence is very versatile in every situation. These 9 slots can be exchanged with side deck cards, allowing your deck to be ready for different match-ups. 
 
This deck's limiting factor is consistency. It faces the problem that a similar older combo deck had, Virtual World. It needed combo pieces to be present in hand or else you've straight up bricked. There aren't any "one card starters" in this deck like Branded Fusion, Mathmech Circular or Weclome Labrynth - you'll need at least two combo pieces, and three is optimal. This problem will soon be fixed (I think) with the upcoming DUNE support. However with CYAC, this deck suffers consistency issues, leaving it prone to bricking and having less room in-deck for staple cards. 
 
COMBOS AND GAMEPLAN
 
The strategy for Mannadium is straightforward (summon level 10 synchros + 3 mat Apollousa) while combos are linear, despite hands being different. Any combination of cards generally leads to the same end board. Here is the main combo for Mannadium: 
 
Riumheart + Mannadium Ball (for this example, we're using Meek) + Calarium = Dis Pater (Negate OR Destroy) + Baronne De Fleur (omni-negate/destroy) + Gymir Aegirine/Chengying (Protection/Banish) + 3 Mat Apollousa (3 monster negates) + Set Reframing (omni-negate) + draw 2. 
  1. Normal summon Riumheart to search for Abscission. 
  2. Activate Calarium, searching for Visas Starfrost. 
  3. Special summon Meek. Activate Abscission targeting and destroying Meek, adding Reframing from deck. 
  4. CL1 Meek to summon another Meek from deck increasing it's level by two, CL2 Calarium to summon Meek from GY. 
  5. Synchro summon Accel Synchro Dragon using level 4 Meek + Riumheart. On summon, Accel Synchro summons Meek from GY.
  6. Synchro Summon Dis Pater using Accel Synchro Dragon +  Meek. (Summon it to the middle, left-most or right-most column so that Cross-Sheep points to it in the future). 
  7. Special summon Visas Starfrost targeting and destroying Meek. Meek's effect upon destruction summons a 3rd Meek from deck and increases its level by 2. 
  8. Link summon Light-Heart using Visas Starfrost (be sure the zone below your Light-Heart is empty). Light-Heart searches for Primitive Planet Reichphobia. 
  9. Activate Reichphobia to search for Reichheart. Reichheart special summons from hand to the zone below Light-Heart. On-summon, Reichheart searches for Scareclaw Arrival and draws you an additional card. 
  10. Link summon Cross-Sheep using Light-Heart + Reichheart. (Summon it to the EMZ so that it's pointing to Dis Pater, while leaving the other column empty for the future summon of Astraloud). 
  11. Special summon from GY Reichheart using Scarelaw Arrival. 
  12. Synchro summon Charge Warrior using Reichheart + level 2 Meek. Draw 1 card. 
  13. Synchro summon Baronne De Fleur using Charge Warrior + level 4 Meek. 
  14. "Contact" Fusion summon Astraloud banishing Visas Starfrost + Riumheart in GY to a zone Cross-Sheep points to. 
  15. Cross-Sheep trigger effect boosts all monster's attack by 700 while simultaneously summoning Meek from GY. 
  16. Synchro summon Gymir Aegirine using Astraloud + Meek. (If you're not using Meek, you can summon Chengying instead). 
  17. Activate Bystial Dis Pater's effect to summon Visas Starfrost from banished pile. Summon Light-Heart from GY.
  18. Link summon Apollousa with 3 materials using Cross-Sheep + Light-Heart + Visas Starfrost. 
  19. Set Reframing and any other cards. 
Left unchecked, this Mannadium's main combo ends on 2 omni-negates, 3 monster negates, 1 banish, fieldwide protection and draw 2. You also have materials in GY next turn to create a Astraloud and if Dis Pater survives until next turn, he can summon Riumheart from banished pile to as follow-up to get more resources from deck. What makes this board extra special  is that it can withstand a Dark Ruler no More/Forbidden Droplet since Reframing is a backrow omni-negate. 
 
The optimal deck's endboard is an extremely potent powerhouse that all decks would be hard-pressed to deal with. Depending on the cards in-hand and whatever interruptions your opponent has, your resulting endboard from this combo vary in power, depending on how much you bricked and how many times you've been interrupted. 
 
This deck can also sustain being hit by several handtraps and keep on comboing, since it offers many extenders and different lines of play. 
 
Going second, this deck naturally breaks boards with Primitive Planet Reichphobia, Astraloud, Baronne and Chaos Angel removing cards. However, as it combos, the strategy is vulnerable to interruption, preferring to go first. The good news is that the Mannadium "ball" combo pieces float (not once per turn btw) when they are destroyed, so you can keep on going if your opponent opts to destroy them. 
 
Mannadium can easily churn out over 9000ATK on board with at least 4 removals requiring minimal investment. When you've baited out all their interruptions going for the regular combo, you can pivot your strategy for the Astraloud + Accesscode OTK. First Link two monsters for Cross-Sheep on board. Contact fuse Visas Starfrost + Visas Clone in GY for Astraloud (1 pop) to a zone Cross-Sheep is pointing to so you can summon another monster from the GY. Link Cross-Sheep + another monster for Knightmare Unicorn (1 spin). Link Knightmare Unicorn + monster for Accesscode Talker (2 pops). And there we have it, 4 removals and over 9000ATK on board for OTK!
 
 
GENERAL TIPS
 
  • As you combo, be aware of the zones you're summoning in, or else you may stop your combo in it's tracks! For Light-Heart, keep the monster zone below it empty, so you can summon Reichheart below it. For Cross-Sheep, make sure to leave space for both a synchro and fusion monster to summon underneath it so you can get an ATK boost and a monster reborn. 
  • High impact handtraps like Dimension Shifter, Droll & Lockbird, Nibiru and Artifact Lancea all stop this deck in it's tracks and severely limit it's play. While it is possible to play through these cards if your starting hand is strong, your board will be weaker. An option to use for this is 3 Crossout Designator + 1 of each handtrap to stop them.
  • An interesting variant of the deck is True King version, where level 9s summon themselves from hand by destroying your Mannadium "balls," triggering both of their effects! They simultaneously act as extenders, starters and board breakers, making them immensely valuable. Both archetypes hold immense synergy with each other, so I may begin testing the True King variant for their viability.  
  • Is your combo stopped by a pesky floodgate? No problem! One of your combo pieces, Primal Planet Reichphobia, destroys 1 card on the field! All it needs are at least 3 monsters on the field in defense position, which is an easy feat for this deck. 

Want to see the deck in action? Scroll to the very bottom for the Youtube video!

CONCLUDING REMARKS
 
So far, I honestly don't find Mannadium particularly interesting as a playstyle and aesthetic. The playstyle is a straightforward combo with little variance. I find that there is no uniqueness with this deck, since its only used as an engine to turbo out generic boss monsters, (Baronne, Apollousa, Dis Pater, etc.) rather than something in-archetype. Even their iconic level 10 boss synchro, Mannadium Prime-Heart is abandoned in favour of more competitive level 10s! With my complaints being said, I believe the next wave of support from DUNE will give this deck an actual personality and identity with "Visas Amritara." When that buster blade wielding badass is released, Mannadium will be more thematic, rather than merely being a shell to summon generic boss monsters. This deck is only getting stronger with future support! 
 
In honour of the inferior Mannadium Prime-Heart who will never be competitively viable (card designers what are you thinking?!), here is the infamous Mannadium copy-pasta, ran through the "OwOifier:"
 
"Mannadium Pwime-Heawt has a speciaw defensive abiwity thawt stops youw opponent fwom tawgeting iwt with cawd effects. No monstews facing Mannadium Pwime-Heawt wiww be safe due tuwu its muwtipwe enewgy bwades! find thiws powewfuw cawd in Cybewstowm Access, weweasing own May 5th!" (sorry for this)
 
GLHF Duelists!

deck_excerpt: The right way to use Dinosaur with Transcendrake's new supports
deck_description:
I decided to make this deck profile to demonstrate the simple, consistent and effective way to use the new Dinosaur supports.

Most of the content there is on the new Transcendrake cards make unnecessary combos using horrible bricks that are normal monsters, lose to all hand traps in the game and use an extra deck worsened with cross-sheep among other unnecessary cards mainly several Synchro monsters in one deck whose forte has always been making XYZ RANK-4.

 

That's why I bring here a decklist that uses the best that the new set brought to the deck: only the excellent Ground Xeno spell and the new Tuner lv6 Xeno Meteorus. These cards have the main advantages: they greatly increase the consistency of the deck and you can access Baronne de Fleur easily. The third big application is that you have more ways to play after opponent interactions which is a weakness of Dinosaur because the deck has a lot of normal summons and few hand extenders and Xeno Meteors is an exceptional extender to keep playing.

 

My intention when playing Dinosaur after the Miscellaneousaurus limitation has always been to continue playing second because his cards are not good against hand traps going first and when necessary to go first I can make the same end board that the deck alone has always been able to to do which is Evolzar Dolkka as the first extra deck monster protecting the rest of your turn and then Tyranno + Omega to return Miscellaneousaurus to the GY as a follow up which is the exact opposite of what most people do in the deck which is fill up the deck of unnecessary bricks to make an end board that when it passes it makes 5 to 6 negates and without any follow up which means that if you take Dark Ruler No More and the opponent clears the field with AA-Zeus for example you automatically lose the game on the way back.

If you intend to play with a Dice Roll deck with no space for tech cards, which uses a lot of horrible brick, it makes a combo that loses to all the hand traps in the game, which lock you into specific monsters in the extra deck that make your options scarce and bad when you go second and there's no follow up so that's what you'll find and get frustrated trying to play and lose.

 

So if you want a deck with consistency, versatility and power then this is the version of Dinosaur that I recommend using because now the deck has so much consistency that your starting hands are very redundant if the deck has 40 cards besides you have no room for tech cards like hand traps. So it's best to increase to 60 cards and use Small World to increase starting hand combinations and always choose to go second so you can get the best combinations of blind second cards as well.

 

The extra deck is standard for what I consider to be the right way to play Dinosaur which is to focus on Xyz. The only big change you can do is to test it and remove the Psyframe engine from the main deck and Lambda because after the banlist in a mediocre way limits Gamma it is a card that can be cut without difficulties from the decklist.

 

////////////////////////////////////

Below I'll leave some very basic combos in the right and simple way to play with the new cards that Baronne de Fleur has access to:

Remember that Oviraptor + Baby = Oviraptor + Miscellaneousaurus = Miscellaneousaurus + Baby = Archosaur + Baby

 

https://www.duelingbook.com/replay?id=813757-50167039

COMBO 1: Oviraptor + Babycerasaurus (Play Around Hand Traps)

Gamestate: Tyranno + Dolkka + Omega + Lambda

 

https://www.duelingbook.com/replay?id=813757-50167148

COMBO 2: Ground Xeno + Babycerasaurus

Gamestate: Tyranno + Baronne de Fleur + Omega + Lambda

 

https://www.duelingbook.com/replay?id=813757-50167479

COMBO 3: Lost World + Ground Xeno + Babycerasaurus (Full Combo Play Around Nibiru)

Gamestate: Tyranno + Dolkka + Baronne de Fleur + Omega + Lambda

 

I had even made a version with Ogdoadic that also talks about the right and detailed way to use this new engine. The version with Ogdoadic is more for fun but it was created with the aim of solving Dinosaur's biggest problem: how sensitive the deck is to hand traps when it goes first. In this version you have more ways to continue playing after taking hand traps and the follow ups are the best possible so I leave below the link of this version for those who are interested in knowing:

https://ygoprodeck.com/deck/scrap-dino-transcendrake-apr23-format-323446

 

////////////////////////////////////////////

The next "evolution" of the Dinosaur deck will be Kaitoptera with Horned Saurus. These cards basically replace Giant Rex in the deck and allow you to access Lost World every turn plus you have Polymerization available either to make Guardian Chimera or to be a discard of Link Knightmare. Until then, this is the best way to use Dinosaur.

 

Disregard the side deck because, like the tech cards I use in the main deck, you can adapt to the reality of the competitive format or where you play.

////////////////////////////////////////////

deck_excerpt: Deck can also be used with the skill Dragon Force
deck_description: Decklist is taken from the setlist of Speed Duel GX Duelists of Shadows.
Deck hecho para ser Fun, considero que tiene bastante reciclaje de recursos, también tiene un par de monstruos fuertes y potenciales OTK

MM SHS

Pros:

-Final Sigma Tower/OTK

Cons:

-Small 'brickage'? (see notes)

-Apollo/Final Sigma conflict

Notes:

-5 card package (3 main, 2 extra)

-Circular limits to one attack but with Final sigma play you can keep summoning non-cyberse if interrupted

-Circular is unnecessary for Final Sigma if you have a spare body (and allows final sigma + other monsters to attack) [Alembertian tribute spare body esp link such as AGB or QG into nabla, nabla tribute alembertian into multiplication, synch into FS]

-Nabla/Multiplication are soft bricks but are still Lvl4 so can be normal/pen summoned (or revived by alembertian) to continue plays

-Nabla/Multiplication also are a tuner/non-tuner pair which can also modulate level and so can be used to help make alternate synchro plays e.g. Muliplication+bike = baronne, Nabla+Multi = Borreload etc.

-Final sigma needs to be in EM zone to gain effects (unaffected/double dmg/double atk/attack monsters twice) which usually conflicts with apollo (it is possible to summon apollo to a linked zone, tribute the other link with alembertian effect and go into final sigma but rarely seems appropriate or necessary)

-Final sigma attacking into Jizukiru deals 5400 damage if its the only monster the opp controls

-AGB can pop pendulum scale to reduce a monster to 0 Atk --> Final Sigma double damage = 6000 unboosted, 12000 boosted. Consider AGB -> QG -> Tunneler Shuffle -> AGB -> Atk Reduce

-Stealthy can steal a spell/trap from opp's GY, then AGB can pop it to reduce

-Sauge de Fleur targetting FS will special then destroy only your opp's card

-Accesscode line was tested but seems more difficult and limiting (often locked into cyberse from ED for rest of the turn)

Thoughts:

-Still struggles under D-shifter/Arise

-Book of moon/Eclipse prevalent make OTK difficult

-Is a small package and easily sided in/out

-May be a case of 'Win more'

deck_excerpt: Yep, there's Winda in 2023. And other spice
deck_description:
A kinda Budget build for Branded Despia

I have Quem, but if you don't have it's not essential to play. If you have Cartesia you definitely want to switch Ecclesia for her. 

We play Winda, cause it's really easy to do with Lubellion and the only Shaddoll target that's in the deck isn't useless cause you can have a draw by discarding it (Branded Opening, Lubellion's cost, Branded Fusion...).

The main line of play to use in a good way Winda is to have Branded Fusion and Branded In Red. We send from deck Albaz and Shaddoll Beast and we summon Lubellion with this. Discard for Lubellion's cost (chain 1). Then you chain Branded In Red (chain 2) taking Albaz from GY and you have to make Mirrorjade by using Albaz from hand and Lubellion from Field. And then Lubellion is going to shuffle itself and Beast into the deck to make Winda. With this we will end with Mirrorjade and Winda (Notes: that's not the main line of play for the deck, but surely it's a good one. Other thing, this combo is possible to do even under Shifter)

The Shaddoll name it's for sure a brick if drawn in first hand or by top deck, but we have plenty of ways to use it as a cost for cards to use his effect to draw or as a fusion material, considering that Winda only requests a Dark Monster other than the Shaddoll one, and our deck is mostly composed by Dark Monsters

But maybe there's another question: why Ecclesia tho? I chose to play Ecclesia cause she can cheat out Albaz from deck during the opponent's turn, and you'll able to do his effect by stealing a opponent's monster.

The best way we want to use Ecclesia it's by using Branded Opening in the opponent's Standby Phase, and summon Quem with that. With Quem you can send Ecclesia from deck to GY, and with her second effect you'll summon Ecclesia too, that will send herself to GY and Special Summon Albaz (that's more easy if you actually try that instead of reading the explanation lol)

(Note: this combo isn't possible to do under Shifter)

Edge Imp Engine: I personally love to play it for the fact that is a way to play after an Ash on BraFu and let you plus

Allure Of Darkness: we like to have a good amount of cards in hand to do our stuff, and the synergy with Mercurier and Tragedy it's fantastic

Other spice, the Borreload fusion (I refuse to write the whole name). It's a good target for Albaz's effect, Branded in Red or Lubellion. And he pops an opponent card. Remember you can dodge the destruction of out Fusions by Branded Opening effect in the GY

Side is pretty standard, I thought about playing Dimension Shifter,but I have to find some space. Maybe you can cut the Dark Ruler No More, but we have to see how the meta will go. You can even play Enemy Controller or Forbidden Chalice in the side deck, is all about what you like to play and how the format goes. Advice a second copy of Masquerade for winning at the time. But I repeat, that's a personal choice

We don't play the new Albion that locks with the Gimmick Puppet for two reasons: Albion it's a pricey card (even Quem is pricey, but you can take her out from the deck. Instead Albion is the only way to do the lock) and I really don't like the lock, and Winda it's a good way to lock too

Last thing I swear: if you have Cartesia play her, but I'm broke. Same discourse with Super Polymerization (you can play three Spoly by cutting Ash and another card)

Much love, hope I explained in a decent way. Ask if you need, I'll try to answer

This deck is a combination of floodgating, board-breaking (some in the main, most in the side), and hand control via Yata Garasu. In my main, I love versatile cards that work well 1st or 2nd. Examples of these are Jowgen and Moon Mirror Shield. When side decking, I only run a couple of additional "going 1st" floodgate options, Summon Limit and TCBOO. I used to run 2-3 copies of Dark Bribe to protect my board, but I've recently dropped the card in lieu of running more "going 2nd" cards in the side. All of my "going 2nd" cards are board-breakers. No hand traps whatsoever. I feel like hand traps are terrible in Stun. Most meta players can play around 1 or 2 hand traps, and you, as the Stun player have now depleted your hand of 1 to 2 cards just for the sake of mildly slowing them down. I prefer to let them over-extend, build a big board, and break it.

Oh, and Yata Garasu ends up being the MVP pretty frequently. One of my biggest fears as a Stun player is my opponent drawing "the out". However....you can't draw "the out" if you can't draw at all....

The idea behind this deck is to mill as much as possible with grass/P.U.N.K./Tearlaments, and then use snow to build a board with the Thunder and Ghoti cards that you hopefully milled. I used to run it without maxx c and superpoly, but I found that it struggled going second so I added them. 

The Starving Venome, Predaplant and Mudragon are for the superpoly, but can be made using Tear fusion (except the Starving which can only be made using superpoly).

An ideal combo would be milling 9 cards using the PUNK engine, which activates the Tear engine to mill another 8. If you mill the Ishizu cards thats a further 10 mill so that's 26 cards milled in total without grass.

Check out the YT video for gameplay and the ideal first turn board.

Hope you like it.

deck_name: Evil Eye Abyss Actors ; I write Abyss Scripts not Evil Eye Defeats
deck_excerpt: What a shame the poor groom's bride is a Dark-Attribute Fiend-Type monster
deck_description:
Yeah

So this deck has some good stuff but also is another basis of Evil Eye good stuff.

I'm basically calling it that now, there is a lot you can accomplish by popping cards on the field.

This is in agreement with how the Abyss Actors like to play, so why not let them convene a bit and take things up a notch.

Good things come out of two engines which can draw a lot of cards, but unfortunately *Droll is a weakness of this deck.

Think that would be obvious, but Morganite is here to help you outperform your opponent in the best way possible, so that's why it's at 3.

This is an UNO deck (no handtraps) but it isn't meant to be ultra-competitve, just a fun build for a fun price.

Hands:

The point of this deck is setting up one side or the other on turn one, or if you're lucky doing both. With Evil Eye and Abyss Actors in your deck, you can summon Towers, amass materials for special summons, set scales which can summon any monster before specific restrictions (madonna, extras, wild hope, dress rehearsal), reset resource recursion, and with Fantastic Theater, provide a unique counter to hard-to-out monsters like Nibiru, when there is a set Abyss Script. 

Abyss Scripts being set also benefit your Evil Eye opens as well, because some of the best backrow-removal cards like HFD and Lightning Storm, are not specific in their destruction effect; you can reap benefits and turn the plot onto the opponent by surprise!

If you want to start Evil Eye: usually you want Evil Eye Serziel or Resurrection or Paradoleia in your opening hand.  Basilius + any Evil Eye card also works.

If you want to start Abyss Actors: usually you want Dress Rehearsal, Dramatic Story, Extras, Curtain Raiser, or Madonna in your hands.

Generally, if you want to learn how to open with abyss actors, a rule of thumb is this line:  summon extras, extras effect, set scale to the field (curtain raiser), curtain raiser effect, special summon from pendulum zone. curtain raiser effect, drop an abyss script from deck to grave & collect extras from ED, set scale extras from hand.  make hyper director with curtain raiser, director effect target extras, summon extras from penulum zone, set scale madonna from deck.  use Dramatic Story from hand, summon Superstar or wild hope. you want to pop wild hope somehow (preferably set up super producer for this purpose). then go on from there.

Evil eye is serziel + resurrection / paradoleia + resurreciton.  you can also access it with basilius + another evil eye in hand.  essentially, get Resurrection with your first hand somehow, use its effect and send gorgoneio + basiltrice/catoblepas as cost, add selene.  thru some variable 5 or 6 directions after this step, you can get serziel equipped with selene, protected from destruction by catle's effect, then have machinex or ashura king on the side, with a retribution set.

This is a fun deck which i haven't finished exploring, so there may be some alternate decklists this could be a template for.

I think Rivalry of the Warlords could be good here, given the main deck is filled with Dark Fiends, but I usually don't have room for it on-field or in-deck, unless you were to dismantle parts of one of the engines.

The best cards to have in your hand on your first turn are Unexpected Die and Rikka Petal. With those two cards you can potentially full combo both the Rikka and Sunavalon cards. After that Unexpected Dai will likely be a brick since you can't be controlling monsters to use it.

Also when using Sunavalon Dryas, first you should special summon Sunseed Twins with Sunvine Sowing, and make sure you never put it in the zone right under your Dryas. This blocks the Dryas effect as you cannot special summon another Sunvine link from your Extra Deck since the zone Dryas is pointing to is blocked.

My Savage Red Eyes Dark Armed Borreload Dragon of Annihilation Deck! (Burn deck/OTK) for Master Duel

Insane combinations: (summon these all in one turn!)
3 Red Eyes Flare Metal Dragons (for 1500 burn damage everytime opponent activates an effect)
A Borreload Savage Dragon to negate opponents card effects.
Dark Armed Dragon of Annihilation to destroy your opponents cards on the field.

And if that doesn't work you still can:
Summon Accesscode Talker with the Darkness Metal, Dragon of Dark Steel for 6300 Attack and destroy your opponents cards on the field.
OR
If your opponents field is full of monsters, summon Borrelend Dragon to clear the board.
OR
If that doesn't work you still have the option to Fusion summon Meteor Black Comet Dragon as a last resort.

Including the Red Eyes Black Dragon Sword for a 12k attack monster on the board and the Queen Dragun Djinn, Return of the Dragon Lords and Meteor Red Eyes Dragon Impact to save your monsters on the field from being destroyed.

deck_excerpt: The best version of tearlements You'll ever play
deck_description:
The Deck I'm about to describe is highly technical and requires skillful play. When piloting this deck, there are two key factors you must always keep in mind: cost and effect. Every hand you draw should have playability, meaning you should be able to make meaningful moves regardless of the initial cards you receive.

For your side deck, it's essential to include cards like "Ghost Reaper & Winter Cherries" to counter your biggest threats, such as "Abyss Dweller" and other similar cards. Additionally, "Chaos Hunter" is an unfortunate but necessary inclusion to combat certain banish strategies that may pose a challenge. It's worth noting that "Chaos Hunter" can be brought back to the field using "Muckraker," providing additional utility.

Regarding the Fiend lock, it shouldn't be a significant issue since both "Kaleido Heart" and "Grapha" are Fiends themselves. This synergy allows for strong plays and interactions within the deck.

 

The Fiend lock shouldn't be problematic since both 'Kaleido Heart' and 'Grapha' are Fiends themselves, enabling strong synergy and interactions within the deck.

When side decking, consider removing 1 'Eldlich,' 1 'Bear,' and 1 'Big Welcome' to optimize your strategy."

deck_excerpt: Been playing Pure Sams since 2015. Built the deck to play against meta, rouge, or casual.
deck_description:
PURE SIX SAMURAI DECK DECONSTRUCTION (any and all questions welcome)

MAIN DECK

(1)Great Shogun Shien: Easy summoning requirements, link fodder, powerful floodgate, can flow into Borreload Savage if needed.

(1)Grandmaster of the Six Samurai: Easy summoning requirement, link fodder, floating effect (do not run more than 1, is easily searchable and you can only have 1 on the board anyways).

(2)Secret Six Samurai - Kizaru: When Special Summoned (preferably with Kageki or Dojo) you can add a Sam with a different attribute from every monster you control (in most cases you will want to add Legendary Secret of the Six Samurai).

(3)Legendary Six Samurai - Kizan: 2nd best card in the entire archetype, easily splashable. Can asceticism into Grandmaster with ATK/DEF boosted from his second effect.

(1)Legendary Secret of the Six Samurai: Searchable with Kizaru, free summon when you put Fuma or Hatsume on board (hard once per turn).

(1)Secret Six Samurai - Hatsume: Excellent extender into Link summon or Synchro, asceticism target into Mizuho.

(2)Legendary Six Samurai - Mizuho: Easily splashable with Shinai, asceticism target into Hatsume, can pop 1 card (soft once per turn).

(2)Legendary Six Samurai - Shinai: Easily splashable with Mizuho, preferred target for Mizuho effect.

(3)Legendary Six Samurai - Kageki: Your Normal Summon 100% of the time if he is in your hand. Easy extender, asceticism target into Fuma.

(3)Secret Six Samurai - Fuma: Essential Tuner of the deck, asceticism target into Kageki,  floating effect, easy to bring out with Isolde or Dojo.

(1)Gateway of the Six: Best card in the entire archetype, 100% necessary for the deck to come online. Searchable with Battle Shogun (remember to always accumulate counters on OTHER cards and remove them from other cards before Gateway).

(3)Shien's Dojo: Easy Bushido Counter accumulation for Gateway, incredible Summon effect for any of your Sams (preferably Fuma, since he is level 1 you will only need 1 counter).

(3)Six Samurai United: Additional Bushido Counter accumulation for Gateway & in-archetype draw power.

(1)Broken Bamboo Sword: Allows you to activate Golden (Pot of Greed).

(3)Cursed Bamboo Sword: Allows you to activate Golden, also searches for Golden and Broken when sent to the GY (easily done with Isolde's effect).

(3)Golden Bamboo Sword: Literally Pot of Greed.

(1)Monster Reborn: Extender.

(1)Pot of Avarice: Recycles main and extra deck monsters with a +1. Better for longer duels when all resources are spent.

(1)Reinforcement of the Army: This is a Warrior Deck, this card searches for Warriors.

(3)Shien's Smoke Signal: In-archetype searcher.

(1)World Legacy Succession: Essentially another Monster Reborn, hard once per turn that needs a Link Monster, but still a Monster Reborn.

(3)Ascetisism of Six Samurai: Non-once per turn extender spell card, incredibly powerful. Plenty of targets, and the downside of this card is negligible.

EXTRA DECK

(1)Trishula, Dragon of the Ice Barrier: Easy to Summon by splashing Kizan. Excellent card removal.

(1)Borreload Savage Dragon: Powerful Beatstick with Omni-negate. Easy to make with splashable level 3 and 4 monsters.

(2)Legendary Six Samurai - Shi En: In-archetype "boss" monster. Easy to summon, negates Spell and Trap cards for no cost (which is also a SOFT once per turn). Can sacrifice other Sams to protect himself as well.

(1)Herald of the Arc Light: You can make this card easy with Hatsume’s effect by reviving Fuma. Powerful floodgate AND Omni-negate.

(1)Time Thief Redoer: Incredibly versatile generic Rank 4. Can steal opponent's card from their top deck, tag himself out, draw a card, AND/OR Spin 1 face-up card.  

(1)Castel, the Skyblaster Musketeer: Generic Rank 4. Removes problematic cards without destroying them (still targets sadly).

(1)Abyss Dweller: Powerful generic Rank 4 (especially in today's meta). Turns off the opponent's GY.

(1)Number 60: Dugares the Timeless: Deceptively powerful and versatile generic Rank 4. Can allow you to go +1 in hand, revive and extend plays, or go push for game with a huge ATK boost on a monster.

(1)Saryuja Skull Dread: Very powerful and versatile Link 4. Small stat boost, extender, and draw power.

(1)Accesscode Talker: Incredibly strong and generic Link 4. Turns into a beatstick that can pop multiple cards, your opponent cannot respond to this card's effects.

(1)Isolde, Two Tales of the Noble Knights: Superb extender. Adds 1 Warrior on Summon, Summons 1 Warrior by sending equip spells to the GY (always Cursed Bamboo Sword for the GY effect). 

(2)Battle Shogun of the Six Samurai: Essential in-archetype Link monster. Searches for Gateway of the Six as well as Dojo or United. He also accumulates Bushido Counters himself that give him an ATK boost. 

(1)Apollousa, Bow of the Goddess: Powerful monster effect negation. Can negate more than 1 monster effect per turn.

SIDE DECK

(3)Nibiru, the Primal Being: Counterplay to other combo heavy decks, since this deck plays no hand traps in main.

(3)Fire Flint Lady: Tech option for more Link/Synchro plays. Easy to summon, with an extender effect (would be in the main deck if it was searchable and not a hard once per turn).

(1)Number 39: Utopia & S39 Utopia the Lightning: Generic Rank 4 that can rank up into Lightning. Just a 5000 ATK beatstick if needed.

(1)Tornado Dragon: Excellent backrow removal in a generic Rank 4. If Shi En and Savage aren't enough anti-backrow, this card is more than enough.

(1)Number 101: Silent Honor ARK: Problematic card removal, similar purpose to Castel. Generic Rank 4.

(1)Leviair the Sea Dragon: Rank 3 extender. Revive any of your Secret Six Samurai monsters (that banish themselves from the GY as protection) or whoever you banished with Hatsume effect.

(1)Called by the Grave: This is your only hope against Ash or Droll if you don't have any omni- negates on board. Stuns hurt this deck badly.

(3)Musakani Magatama: 100% tech card/side deck option. If your opponent keeps focusing on destroying Gateway (which they should if they have a brain) this card can protect it. 

NOTES

On average this deck should end on a board consisting of Accesscode/Apollousa, Savage, 1 or 2 Shi En, 1 or 2 generic Rank 4 monsters, and either Herald (if you have enough resources) or Grandmaster (for his floating effect and to protect Shi En).

Also for clarification I have been playing pure sams since 2015 and I've been playing this variation of the deck since Link format was released. Suffice to say I am fairly confident in this deck and build decisions. But any and all questions are welcome. I am happy to discuss anything Six Samurai related.

deck_description:
Category: Tournament Meta Deck

Tournament Meta Decks are current-level Meta Decks that are capable of going up against the best of the best. These are curated lists that cannot be uploaded by regular users.

Creator: Francesco Sabatini

Tournament: Italy National Championship - June 3rd 2023

Placement: Top 16

Anime Deck based on Mako Tsunami's Duelist Kingdom Deck. Contains all cards that Mako used in the anime in that season.

Duelist Kingdom has different rules than the current ones (those would only take place in Battle City), so duelists are able to summon high level monsters for no tributes. This deck was made for fun and wasn't meant for being competitive (there was, however, an attempt to do it considering their decks and rules of that arc and their universe).

 

Not much is known about his first deck, but I believe it didn't change much from his Battle City one.

But it is clear that, this early on, "Kairiyu-Shin" (Leviathan) was his ace card.

Mako probably also had Legendary Fisherman and Fortress Whale around this time, they just weren't shown. His Tornado Wall strategy would probably be too much during this era, so let's just give him that in Battle City.

Notice that, some of the monster choices, are there because of Fortress Whale's materials on the games (I went for that approach for Duelist Kingdom Decks). They also heavily implied that he has a Raigeki in the deck, especially in the games (which I also checked and used to build this deck - I'm looking at you Duel Monsters 1).

 

His tactic against Yugi (on his first duel) was mostly just hiding his monsters underwater for a surprise Sea Stealth Attack (but for a supposed fair duelist, he wasn't doing much differently than Panik, so why wasn't he called out?).

And for those saying that the "Attack the Moon!" was bs in this Duel, you might also try to remember how Yugi's Equip Spell indirectly raised the tides (that was one weird backfire, but alright). Yugi finished the Duel with Curse of Dragon AND Burning Land, which destroys all Field Spell cards - getting rid of Umi, so it wasn't totally out-of-nowhere, right? Well I'd like to believe that but we already know how Duelist Kingdom rules were something else...

I added those 2 newer cards to the Side Deck in nod to his Duel with Yugi. They were made to refference it and I think they're honestly really cool.

deck_excerpt: Mokuba Kaiba - Reptile Plant Fusion Deck
deck_description:
Anime Deck based on the Deck Mokuba Kaiba STOLE during Duelist Kingdom. We saw a whopping 2 cards, but that shouldn't stop us! If anything we have more room to do whatever we want (as long as it makes sense).

Duelist Kingdom has different rules than the current ones (those would only take place in Battle City), so duelists are able to summon high level monsters for no tributes. This deck was made for fun and wasn't meant for being competitive (there were NO attempts at making this deck any good, really - in some games Mokuba was even the worst duelist and only appeared WHEN YOU LOSE WAY TOO MUCH).

 

So what was the Duelist (that Mokuba stole the deck) thinking exactly? Who would use cards like "Man-Eating Plant"? Well, perphaps, they were using a Plant Deck!

To make usage of Fairy King Truesdale's and Wodan's effect, I assume.

Oh seems viable enough for Duelist Kingdom Decks- but hey what's that? "Krokodilus"? I mean if some higher-up duelists can use cards weak as that, perphaps some other duelists could use too.

Millenium Duels gave Mokuba a "Reptile Plant Deck", and since we didn't see the other cards in the anime, that'll do.

I just tweaked it all a bit to make more sense in this era. Added some Fusions too, since there's a few Plant monsters that have neat Fusions. For Reptiles, we surely have the Trap card "Snake Fang"! Let's make it a bit more special in this Deck, I dare say.

 

Couldn't Pegasus have 40 duelists that were actually good? Was the game that early on back then? We're not really sure how they obtain the cards there but I guess the really good ones are just that scarce. Or perphaps, much like just copy-pasting someone else's Deck, Mokuba just didn't know how to use it properly.

 

Mokuba, please, next time adjust the Deck before using it, alright? Your brother is rich and has some neat cards to help you.

The Side Deck is full of cards that Mokuba is usually seen using in the games (they're pretty neat and much better options).

"Snatch Steal" isn't a card he is usually seen using, but you can kinda see where this is going.

 

Was hella fun building this trash Deck.

Anime Deck based on Bonz' Duelist Kingdom Deck. Contains all cards that Bonz used in the anime in that season.

Duelist Kingdom has different rules than the current ones (those would only take place in Battle City), so duelists are able to summon high level monsters for no tributes. This deck was made for fun and wasn't meant for being competitive (there was, however, an attempt to do it considering their decks and rules of that arc and their universe).

 

Bonz, while known to use a Zombie Deck, used some sort of regular monsters with a catch - he revives them back up again as Zombies.

But "Call of the Haunted" was given to him by Bandith Keith, so it kinda leaves us thinking... what was he using before that? A bunch of ghost monsters? The Deck he runs in WC2004 is pretty funny because he just runs something else entirely, so it's fun to think about it.

For the sake of being a bit more close to the anime (and his first duel), I gave him 3 "Call of the Haunted".

In the Side Deck you can find the first Ritual monster (which is also a Zombie) "Dokuroraider". Decided to give him that because, in Duelist Kingdom, Rituals were used quite a few times. I'm also going for the Forbidden Memories Rules and didn't put it in the Main Deck (we don't really see them have the Ritual monsters in hand anyway, the rules for Rituals were still pretty hazy back then).

The 3 iconic Low-Level 0 Defense Normal monsters should be put in the Side Deck, as they were more like transformations than actual cards. The ones they were originally (Crawling Dragon, Zanki and Dream Clown) are all in the Main Deck, however.

Any weak Normal monsters could be part of his previous Deck (the Ghost Deck), as they're on theme. No wonder Keith didn't like it.

Anime Deck based on PaniK's Duelist Kingdom Deck. Contains all cards that PaniK used in the anime in that season.

Duelist Kingdom has different rules than the current ones (those would only take place in Battle City), so duelists are able to summon high level monsters for no tributes. This deck was made for fun and wasn't meant for being competitive (there was, however, an attempt to do it considering their decks and rules of that arc and their universe).

 

I think most of us remember this guy because of his monsters' weird statlines. Let's hope that we can get retrains of such cards now that the Illusionist type has finally been announced.

There always seems to be something weird with his Deck, as he runs the most useless monsters ever.

And then Castle of Dark Illusions had its effect changed to Zombies??? What a disservice.

You can battle him on Legacy of Duelist and Nightmare Troubadour (he was pretty menacing here, with a Shadow Game and all) but his Decks were always trash, I can't believe he beat Mai.

 

Anyways, added a few monsters that are Fusion Materials for his Fusion monsters and added a few Rituals (seems like everyone almost goes to a consensus that he'd run 1 or more of such Ritual monsters).

"Dust Barrier" is really similar to one of the effects of the "Castle of Dark Illusions" in the anime and "Swords of Concealing Light" is a good rival for "Swords of Revealing Light", that Yugi used to reveal his monsters ("Dark Mirror Force" also has this logic behind it).

In the Side Deck, there's the Ritual Monsters (since Ritual Summoning in the anime didn't really show the Ritual monster in the Hand, so they're probably like Forbidden Memories) and some burn cards (representing his attempt to burn Yugi alive after losing). "Ultimate Obedient Fiend" just looks like a card he'd definitely use, but I'm not sure how that would go in the anime, since he has more ATK power than Blue-Eyes and wasn't even meantioned once (a missed opportunity I'd say).

deck_excerpt: Maximillion Pegasus - (Toon World!) Future Visions Deck
deck_description:
Anime Deck based on Pegasus' Duelist Kingdom Deck. Contains most cards that Pegasus used in the anime in that season (since there's a lot of anime-only cards).

Duelist Kingdom has different rules than the current ones (those would only take place in Battle City), so duelists are able to summon high level monsters for no tributes. This deck was made for fun and wasn't meant for being competitive (there was, however, an attempt to do it considering their decks and rules of that arc and their universe). I'll be treating Ritual monsters as the ones from Forbidden Memories too (and not having them as Main Deck cards).

 

The Final Boss of Duelist Kingdom and very memorable villain.

There's a few of cards that Pegasus owns that don't exist at the time of writing this. I substituted the following cards:

- Mermaid's Tear -> Spellbinding Circle

- Eye of Deception -> Change of Heart

- Magic Neutralizing Force -> Imperial Order

- Negative Energy -> (deppending on the situation, Megamorph or Reverse Trap)

- Prophecy -> Confiscation (Pegasus can see the opponent's hand anyway)

- Trap Displacement -> (One of the Mirror trap cards)

 

If the Deck seems a bit too different than usual, that's because "Toon World" was different in the anime and it could turn other monsters into Toons (not something that already exists). There's a few cards that are not known in his Deck, but due to them having Toon versions, we could imagine that he also has them in the Deck ("Toon Masked Sorcerer" and "Toon Cannon Soldier").

I also added those 3 Side Deck cards for flexing (you know which ones I'm talking about), he is the creator of the game, afterall.

Strange deck indeed, it's not what is usually seen for him, but I tried to make it more like Duelist Kingdom this time. And Pegasus is strange, so it fits in my opinion. For a proper playable deck for him and more in touch with what he usually uses in the games, perhaps I'll do it for later seasons...

This was all really fun to make, but it sure took a lot of time.

I'll be doing more in a near future perhaps :))

deck_excerpt: The Best Version of Tearlaments you'll ever play.
deck_description:
The Deck I'm about to describe is highly technical and requires skillful play. When piloting this deck, there are two key factors you must always keep in mind: cost and effect. Every hand you draw should have playability, meaning you should be able to make meaningful moves regardless of the initial cards you receive.

For your side deck, it's essential to include cards like "Ghost Reaper & Winter Cherries" to counter your biggest threats, such as "Abyss Dweller" and other similar cards. Additionally, "Chaos Hunter" is an unfortunate but necessary inclusion to combat certain banish strategies that may pose a challenge. It's worth noting that "Chaos Hunter" can be brought back to the field using "Muckraker," providing additional utility.

Regarding the Fiend lock, it shouldn't be a significant issue since both "Kaleido Heart" and "Grapha" are Fiends themselves. This synergy allows for strong plays and interactions within the deck.

In your side deck, include cards like 'Ghost Reaper & Winter Cherries' to counter major threats such as 'Abyss Dweller.' Additionally, 'Chaos Hunter' is vital against banish strategies, despite its drawbacks. 'Chaos Hunter' can be revived using 'Muckraker,' adding versatility to your plays.

The Fiend lock shouldn't be problematic since both 'Kaleido Heart' and 'Grapha' are Fiends themselves, enabling strong synergy and interactions within the deck.

When side decking, consider removing 1 'Eldlich,' 1 'Bear,' and 1 'Big Welcome' to optimize your strategy."

update: This is my TCG version of the deck I previously mentioned, which operates identically to the OCG version with a few key differences. In the OCG, there's a card called 'New World Formation' that adds recursion, providing an advantage not yet available in the TCG. However, the TCG version has access to better options like 'Gura Wings' and 'Toadally Awesome,' which can enhance your plays. As newer cards are released, I will update the deck list accordingly. If you have the extra funds to spare, you could consider adding a 'Kashira Fenrir' package instead of 'Chaos Hunter.' However, I decided to stick with 'Chaos Hunter' due to the prevalence of 'Bystials' in the current meta. I welcome any suggestions or ideas you may have, so please feel free to leave a comment. Enjoy exploring the possibilities of this deck

Update: Main deck primeval plant perlino 3-1 kashtira fenier 0-2, extra deck Kashtira shangira 0-1, Side deck chaos hunter 3-0, kaijus 0-3, sprind 0-1, burning abyss 0-1, dracossack 0-1.

deck_excerpt: First attempt at Branded Bystial Dragonmaids
deck_description:
Dragonmaids got a solid powerboost in the Bystials, alongside the obvious Branded synergy. This was made the morning the new pack released, so definitely suboptimal in a lot of ways. Regardless, I do believe this is the best type of Dragonmaid deck you can make. The Bystial package just has a lot of useful synergies with Dragonmaid that I believe are worth exploring. Without any further ado, let's get into it.

Branded:

  • 3x Albaz to make sure Branded Fusion is online at basically all times.
  • 3x Branded Fusion to make said BraFu targets.
  • 1x Springans Kitt for a Rindbrumm target and a BraFu searcher.
  • 1x Branded Retribution to dump with Saronir, might consider replacing if I can find a better thing to dump after Bystial Lubellion is put into the GY.
  • 1x Cartesia, because I don't want to spend the UR dust on extra copies right now. Really good card, walking Polymerization that adds herself back to the hand from grave if you dumped a Fusion in the grave that turn.

Bystial:

  • 1x Magnumhut because he's limited. Run as many copies as legally allowed, this guy is by far the best Bystial for this strategy.
  • 2x Saronir and 2x Baldrake, since I need a decent amount of Bystials for this strategy in general. Both have useful effects, though I haven't procced Baldrake in a duel yet.
  • 1x Druiswurm because it's limited. I'd probably run a ratio of something like 3x Magnumhut, 2x Druiswurm, 1x each of Saronir and Baldrake if it were up to me, but I sadly don't control the banlist.
  • 1x Lubellion. More are worth considering, he replaces himself with a usable Bystial if you draw him, but I don't want to spend the UR dust on the extra copies yet.
  • 1x Branded Regained and 1x Branded Beast as targets for Lubellion. Regained gives a lot of resource accumulation, and Beast gives proactive disruption.

Dragonmaid:

  • 3x Chamber, because she's literally the best Dragonmaid gameplay-wise (cutest is Laundry, but she really doesn't fit into this specific deck).
  • 2x Parlor because I wanted a few extra Dragonmaids to access Sheou better. I... might end up cutting her, as I have been bricking on Parlor a lot. That said, definitely the next best option to use after Chamber.
  • 1x Changeover to make Sheou, but can also be used to make the fusion Lubellion and any other Dragon fusion monster in the deck.
  • 1x Hospitality mostly because. Another card I might cut, as it just doesn't do enough TBH. We're not nearly as NS reliant in this build as regular Dragonmaid, since we have so many different playmakers between the Bystial and Branded engines.
  • 2x Tidying. Just a generally good trap in Dragon decks, both disruption and a way to get another body onto the field.

Rest of the Main Deck is just various staples and generic cards, not really an interesting discussion there. Fusion Deployment can be run at however many copies you desire, it summons Cartesia or Albaz straight from deck for basically no cost beyond a Fusion lock for the turn.

Extra Deck:

  • Lubellion, Albion, Mirrorjade are basically standard for any deck using the Branded engine, so I won't bother reiterating the most basic combo of the archetype.
  • Alba-lenatus is a hate crime against Dragon Link, so of course I run it. Also good to summon off Lubellion if you have a bunch of dragons in grave you'd rather have in your deck, though this ain't really the deck for that. Usually just the second thing you'd use as Mirrorjade ammo after Albion though.
  • Rindbrumm is an Albaz target to finally kill Floo, and also your other thing to summon off BraFu. It also gives Branded a negate, which is really appreciated even if I wish it was a Spell/Trap negate.
  • 1x Sheou and 2x House for Dragonmaid stuff. Gives you an omni, you can use the Bystials as material for Sheou, you probably know how this works if you've ever played Dragonmaid.
  • Garura, Starving Venom, and Mudragon are Super Poly targets. I'd argue Starving Venom is possibly the most important one to keep around, as sometimes you run into a big 4K+ monster you can't beat over otherwise, but all of them are replacable if you don't want to use Super Poly.
  • Granguinol to summon off Cartesia and dump a Level 6+ LIGHT/DARK. Garura can be dumped for a draw, if we had Chamber's dragon form we'd probably dump that, and Saronir can be used to dump a Branded Spell/Trap. Quaeritis is there as our Despia ED target, I'm replacing it with Luluwalilith once she comes out.
  • Hieratic Seal of the Heavenly Spheres to give us a thing to end on if we have spare bodies, and Underworld Goddess to out Towers and the like. Spheres can be probably be replaced, Verte Anaconda would be a good immediate option if you're not sure.

And that's the deck as I have it built! Feel free to ask any questions, I'm going to get back to bricking with this stupid thing.

Original Deck- Scareclaw Dinomorphia (June 2023)

Iv'e Just created the spicyest deck! 

@copyright reserved to me

A fun take on spright that adds both the Melffy and Ghoti engines to create a poweful synchro climbing combo that both bounces and banishes a monster on the field.

Standard Combo:
Any two level 2's goes into Spright Sprind, send nimble angler to go into two Nimble Beavers. Nimble Beaver + sprind summons Spright Giant and then Spright Giant summons Shif, Fairy of the Ghoti from the deck. Giant + Shif goes into Elf and then Elf brings back Nimble Angler, banish Shif targeting Angler since its a fish and then XYZ into Melffy of the Forest using Angler and remaining Nimble Beaver and add Melffy Catty to complete the combo.

Followup turn 3 if you used Askaan and banished Shif to summon it back the previous turn when Shif activates its effect to return to the field you can immediately summon Minairuka which you searched off of Arionpos and then go into Baronne de Fleur using Askaan and Shif. Summon Back the Shif using Elf to go into Virtual World Beast Jiu Jiu, giving you two removals (Jiu Jiu + Baronne), incidentally Jiu Jiu can trigger Askaan giving you 8100 total damage on board (Jiu Jiu + Askaan + Barrone De Fleur).

You can interchange some non-engine handtraps with boardbreakers if you are concerned about losing the coin flip and want to reset the gamestate with Downered + Zeus.


Overall its a fun twist on Spright Melffy that deviates towards interrupting the opponent by synchroing on the opponents turn as opposed the traditional methods of interrupting the opponent by link summoning on the opponent's turn.

deck_excerpt: All Naturia monsters come from the forest
deck_description: All naturia monsters where all based on nature and natures elements

Here's a short guide to the deck's base combo

 

synchro into junk speeder

special summon jet, assault, revolution, stardust and wheel synchrons with speeder's effect

stardust synchron effect to add arrive in light

synchro speeder, jet, assault and stardust for supernova

activate arrive in light, placing converging wills on top

synchro summon using revolution and wheel (it can be treated as a non-tuner and therefore carries the deck) for stardust dragon

arrive in light effect to draw into converging wills

converging wills effects to special summon it and Wurm from deck

revolution effect in GY, pitch top card of deck to special summon as level 1

synchro into star shaman

star shaman effect (if you want)

either synchro celestial and stardust into shooting star then with converging wills, shooting majestic star, or shooting majestic star using stardust, converging wills, stardust and the monster summoned with shaman's effect.

 

that's the base combo

Everything from card choices flexibility of the extra deck is gone over in the video. Let me know what you think in the comments!

I will expand a bit more here though. I'm only on 2 Maxx C simply because I couldn't find another slot for number 3 and I, personally, kept bricking by opening multiple. Thunder Dragon can be inconsistent so I never want to open a full house of Maxx C and OG Thunder Dragon. 

Speaking of the Level 2 Earth Insect. This deck plays well under it. If you see it you only have to special summon once or twice to get to SUS or Titan. 

Your ideal end board is Branded Beast, Lubellion, Sus + a link 2 of either Verte to make Titan on top or I:P. 

Sitting on Sus + a pop with some Bystials is good enough to take a lot of games and to win on the crack back and you're fine to play second - which I did regularly - with this list as you can see from the replays in the video.

deck_description:
Category: Tournament Meta Deck

Hi, Grayewick the Fusionist here, with a Synchro Deck... YEP

Presenting Ghoti. Why? Because it's just like Crystrons fr fr but with fishes and easier maths. Anyway, there's really nothing much to talk about this list since it's for the most part a standard Ghoti deck with standard Ghoti ratios, but with a few notable exceptions.

Main Deck, except "Ghoti" cards

• x3 Supay, Duskwalker  + x1 Supay - It's a free Arionpos, Serpent of the Ghoti engine. Yep.
• x3 Minairuka - It's a free negate that Special Summons itself when the effect of a WATER monster is activated... which majority of your monsters are.
• x3 Lifeless Leaffish - Just an Armageddon Knight  for Fishes. Best Normal Summon because of how unassuming its effect is.
• x3 Beautunaful Princess - Second best Normal Summon because of how it dodges targeting negations. You're going with Lifeless Leaffish or Paces, Light of the Ghoti with this card anyway so, you know... yeah.
• x3 Hop Ear Squadron - One of the enablers of funny Synchros.

The rest is just a bunch of staples.

Extra Deck

• x2 Ghoti of the Deep Beyond - I play 2 because sometimes I need the extra copy.
• x2 Askaan, the Bicorned Ghoti - I play 2 because you play 2 in Ghotis.
• x2 Arionpos, Serpent of the Ghoti - I play 2 because you don't need 3 of it. You could, though, if you have it and and extra space.
• x1 Guoglim, Spear of the Ghoti - I only play this because I have the slot for it, and because it's a D.D. Warrior Lady. You don't need it, but can have it.
• x1 Assault Blackwing - Onimaru the Divine Thunder - I just have him here because I don't have a Geomathmech Final Sigma, which could also take this place for a generic Synchro 12. Onimaru can swing for 6k though, which is funnier.
• x1 Swordsoul Supreme Sovereign - Chengying, Baronne de Fleur, Icejade Gymir Aegirine - Just a bunch of generic Synchro 10s you can Summon during your opponent's turn.
• x1 Adamancipator Risen - Dragite - It's a free Spell/Trap negate. You'll never run out of WATER monsters in your GY.
• x1 PSY-Framelord Omega - Funny card to Summon during your opponent's turn.
• x1 White Aura Whale - A Raigeki that can keep your set up going.
• x1 Desert Locusts - Another funny card that can be Summoned alongside your aforementioned PSY-Framelord Omega.

Honorable mentions

• Ruddy Rose Dragon - It reads "nuke your opponent's board and GY while setting up your banish pile during their turn".
• Crystron Quariongandrax - Another funny card that can be Summoned during your opponent's turn.
• Angel of Zera - Funny beatstick.
• Buster Dragon - Funny floodgate for monster Types.
• Hyper Psychic Riser - Literally just Skill Drain.
• Cyber Slash Harpie Lady - Just a free bounce each turn.
• Vulcan the Divine - Same thing with the aforementioned card.
• Metaphys Horus - A free permanent negate for a face-up card.

Final thoughts, uhhh... YEP Joel. Goodluck with the upcoming Synchro Festival, again, to y'all, I suppose. As per usual, if you have any questions or thoughts, feel free to express them down in the comments and I'll respond to them as soon as I possibly can.
