deck_excerpt: [insert something about fighting games and rocks]
deck_description:
Still on copium after losing Block Dragon, even if it's been, y'know, years? Just trying to find a deck to play this format with a bunch of Spright and Adamancipator cards just sitting around somewhere? Well, my friend, you've come to the right place! Introducing Vanquish Soul Adamancipator Spright, a combination of decks that sounds ridiculous but actually works really well.

Now these three decks on their own are absolutely amazing. Spright can build a board of interactions and negates, Adamancipator... does basically the same thing, and Vanquish Soul can easily disrupt your opponent's plays at Quick Effect speed. So, really nice, huh? So how do they all work together?

Well, quite simple, really... Vanquish Soul monsters have effects that require them to reveal certain monsters with certain Attributes from the hand, which are DARK, EARTH, and FIRE. These 3 Attributes are necessary in order to activate certain effects, like Vanquish Soul Heavy Borger providing draw power (and maybe burning for time) and Vanquish Soul Caesar Valius and Vanquish Soul Razen can easily pop cards on the field. The amount of power here is amazing, and Rock of the Vanquisher is just an amazing card that can quickly help bring out more Vanquish Soul monsters. Better yet, the other monsters in the Deck only help Vanquish Soul even further. The Adamancipator and Koa'ki Meiru monsters are EARTH (except for Dragite), Spright Blue is a DARK, and the Spright negates + Ash + Dogoran are FIRE.

But what if you don't draw your Vanquish Souls? Well, that's not much of an issue. All of the Adamancipator monsters can easily set up Synchro plays for even Levels, allowing you to go into either a Level 6, 8, or 10. Often, you'll be Synchro Summoning Raptite and then using it and one of your Level 2 Tuners to make Dragite or Borreload Savage Dragon (if you have a Link in grave). Plus, if you have Level 2 monsters on the field, you can go into Spright plays with Gigantic Spright, giving you access to more interactions by spamming more bodies for I:P Masquerena, yet another interaction which can spin a card on your opponent's turn with Knightmare Unicorn.

The deck is incredibly easy to pick up and understand, but pretty expensive. However, once you have the cards, please try and test it out - I want to see how good this deck really is (if I've just made a meta threat then uh... you can blame me)

Other Options

This is just one decklist, but there are a bunch of other cards you can play that I strongly recommend.

  • Number 41: Bagooska the Terribly Tired Tapir - Out of options? Get 2 monsters on the field, and hope you live.
  • Crystal Wing Synchro Dragon - Any Level 2 Tuner + Raptite/Leonite = Crystal Wing. A nice monster negate.
  • Swordsoul Supreme Sovereign - Chengying - Just another great generic Level 10. Can't afford Baronne? That's fine, just play Chengying!
  • Lava Golem - Okay this option sounds good, but, just one problem... it takes away your Normal Summon... something this deck kinda needs to get to cooking. Plus, if you draw Cartorhyn in the same hand, uh... enjoy having dead cards.
  • Kurikara Divincarnate - Still nice and a smidge better than Lava Golem, but I'd prefer this as a side deck option.
  • Apollousa, Bow of the Goddess - Another I:P target, and a good one at that too!
  • Dimension Shifter - This one's... actually not too bad. Most of these cards rarely care about the GY, so you can take a D-Shifter. Note that you will actually be going against this card sometimes in certain strategies like pure Vanquish Soul, so don't worry.

That's all!

If you have any thoughts on the deck, please comment - feedback is appreciated, and I'd like to know how the deck can be further improved.

deck_excerpt: An Evil Eye deck built to go second and break your opponent's board while making your own.
deck_description:
This is my take on Evil Eye, with many additions to make this deck strong going second in the current format. To clarify, the Evil Eye GY monsters are Catoblepas, Familiar of the Evil Eye and Basiltrice, Familiar of the Evil Eye.

These are explanations of some of the non-engine cards:

- Super Polymerization is compatible with discarding your Evil Eye GY monsters and takes down many decks that put at least 2 quick effect/negate monsters on the end board, but unfortunately is weak to different atrributes like Swordsoul. In this deck, it can make either Mudragon of the Swamp, which gives your field targeting protection, Garura, Wings of Resonant Life, which can give you an extra draw or help you otk, or Predaplant Dragostapelia, which can out fusion boards or work if you have 2 Super Polys in hand and give an on-field monster negate.

- Kashtira Fenrir is also a solid board breaker, which can trick opponents into thinking you are playing Kashtira and can bait out negates with the search. It also banishes your opponent's cards when it attacks or your opponent activates a monster effect.

- Triple Tactics Thrust can typically get you access to your Terraforming in order to start your combos, as well as your combo pieces (Evil Eyes Unleashed, Evil Eye Awakening,) Triple Tactics Talent, Pot of Prosperity, or Infinite Impermanence if your opponent doesn't have a monster on field or you already have your combo.

- Ash Blossom & Joyous Spring, Droll & Lock Bird, and Infinite Impermanence are all strong going first and second cards that stop your opponent's plays.

Some Important things to know when playing (or against) this deck are:

- Droll & Lock Bird, Dimension Shifter, Necrovalley, Abyss Dweller, and similar cards, such as cards that stop GY effects, are strong outs to this deck and its combos.

- This deck typically requires an Evil Eye monster on field to activate most of its effects, so if your Serziel, Watcher of the Evil Eye gets destroyed before you can equip it with Evil Eye of Selene, your combo will either be lackluster or simply stopped.

- My version of the deck runs little main deck monsters and lots of searchers/non-engine, so if you find yourself not drawing your engine much, you can add in more Evil Eye monsters.

Here are some example lines that I use with this deck:

- You always want to start your combo by having access to Serziel, Watcher of the Evil Eye, summoning it and adding Evil Eyes Unleashed to your hand, using Unleashed to send an Evil Eye GY monster and Evil Eye of Gorgoneio to the GY and add Evil Eye of Selene to your hand, and equipping Selene to your Serziel. Depending on what you draw, you can extend further using Gorgoneio and make/break different end boards.

- You can extend with more summons by summoning Basilius, Familiar of the Evil Eye from the Deck with Evil Eye Awakening, using it and an Evil Eye GY monster to Xyz summon The Phantom Knights of Break Sword, using the effect by detaching Basilius to destroy your field spell (Evil Eye Domain - Pareidolia) and an opponent's card, using the destruction effect of the field spell to add Basilius back to your hand, and summoning Basilius from your hand. This can allow you to make multiple Xyz monsters if you can't otk your opponent, such as a potential Divine Arsenal AA-ZEUS - Sky Thunder using the The Phantom Knights of Break Sword and D/D/D Deviser King Deus Machinex by overlaying on top of a D/D/D Stone King Darius.

- You can create more inturruptions on your opponent's turn using the GY effect of Basiltrice, Familiar of the Evil Eye. If you leave Serziel, Watcher of the Evil Eye on the field equipped with Evil Eye of Selene, (which is standard in the Evil Combo as you can destroy an opponent's special summoned monster during their turn,) you can use Basiltrice on your opponent's turn AFTER YOU USE SERZIEL TO DESTROY A SPECIAL SUMMONED MONSTER to make either Gorgon, Empress of the Evil Eyed and negate an on-field monster effect or Zerrziel, Ruler of the Evil Eyed and destroy an opponent's card and attack twice on your turn. You can then use the GY effect of Evil Eyes Unleashed in order to equip Evil Eye of Selene to that monster.

These are some potential siding/maining options if you don't like the current list or want to add to it (some are already in deck but you can add more copies):

deck_name: Slifer Dark Magician Power Draw Deck
deck_description: Draw 6x

My approach on what I believe to be a fun competent control deck going first and second.

With the addition of Dogmatikamatrix, the deck has gained an extremely powerful tool for going first and second allowing you to +2 or even +3 depending on the scenario at hand. Compared to other lists, I have decided to cut Diviner for deck space and opted to play triple Ultimate Slayer instead.

Ultimate Slayer allows you to not only get rid of your opponent's pesky monsters (like Rulkallos and whatnot) as well as give you the opportunity to opt into a multitude of plays with your extra deck monsters and its unfounded "Once per Turn" clause allows you to capitalize off Maxx C by utilizing it multiple times, whereas Diviner would simply be rotting in your hand.

The main downside to not playing Diviner would be your innability to go for the Maxiimus line easily with Almiraj and Secura Gardna, however since your normal summon is not spent on Diviner, you may make use of Cartesia which allows you to go into Granguignol during yours or your opponent's Main Phase. And although not optimal, normal summoning Ecclesia is also a choice.

Since this deck does not have a high need for the Extra Deck, playing triple Super Polymerization feels only natural and with the arrival of Garura, the -1 required to activate it will feel trivial. The Bystials are obviously strong monsters specially in a meta dominated by Tearlaments and the synergy this deck has with Regained may allow you to get the follow-up much needed for this "ritual" deck. Also use Alba Zoa's effect at your own discretion, unless you are sure of what your opponent is playing activating his effect may end up losing you the game.

this deck is a powerful deck that can beat the top 8 meta deck of 2023, and also it's cute. hope someone will have fun with this deck (because is a non-meta deck so you can also upgrade this deck to a meta deck )

deck_excerpt: Branded Labrynth / Halifax WCQ Regional Top 4
deck_description:
Category: Tournament Meta Deck

Tournament Meta Decks are current-level Meta Decks that are capable of going up against the best of the best. These are curated lists that cannot be uploaded by regular users.

Creator: Angus M.

Tournament: Halifax WCQ Regional- June 10th 2023

Placement: Top 4

Well, they killed off Cyber-Stein, so there goes my other FTK (probably necessary though, when has Cyber-Stein done anything fair?). I highly doubt the FTK players are going to stop though, so if you really want another (and goofier) FTK, here you go!

Main Combo

First on the agenda is bringing out Lifeless Leaffish + any Level 4 monster OR any 2 Level 4 monsters + Superancient Deepsea King Coelacanth in your GY. This can easily be achieved with Beautunaful Princess, Silent Angler, Kagetokage, and many other options we have to make a Rank 4 Xyz monster. 

Once you've got that done, the combo starts:

  1. Overlay your 2 Level 4s into Number 60: Dugares the Timeless. 
  2. Detach 2 materials from Dugares, skipping your next (nonexistent if you do this properly) Main Phase 1 and Special Summoning Coelacanth from your GY.
  3. Activate Coelacanth's effect to Special Summon 4 Fish monsters from your Deck, including one Oyster Meister and Royal Swamp Eel (I personally like to use 7 Colored Fish because... it's funny, but if you do bring it out, make sure to Link it off first in step 4.)
  4. Link Summon Shinobi Insect Hagakuremino using Dugares and anything except Oyster Meister and Royal Swamp Eel, and do this in the right EMZ.
  5. Link Summon Codebreaker Virus Swordsman using any 2 Fish monsters other than Oyster Meister and Royal Swamp Eel, then Special Summon Codebreaker Zero Day to the zone Hagakuremino points to.
  6. Synchro Summon White Aura Monoceros, then, on Synchro Summon, Special Summon Coelacanth back to the field (Oyster Meister will also Special Summon a Token, which is mandatory).
  7. Link Summon Triple Burst Dragon using Codebreaker Virus Swordsman and Shinobi Insect Hagakuremino.
  8. Link Summon Reprodocus using Triple Burst and the Token.
  9. Use Coelacanth's effect to Special Summon Royal Swamp Eel, any Level 4 Fish monster, and Oyster Meister (make sure to shuffle any in your GY back into the Deck with Lifeless Leaffish if necessary, we need to recycle resources). Put Royal Swamp Eel in a Zone that Reprodocus points to.
  10. Xyz Summon Red-Eyes Flare Metal Dragon using Coelacanth and White Aura Monoceros in your rightmost zone.
  11. Use Reprodocus's effect to change Royal Swamp Eel to a DARK monster.
  12. Link Summon Geonator Transverser using Oyster Meister and Reprodocus, and make sure that it is in the Left EMZ.
  13. Synchro Summon Beelze of the Diabolic Dragons using Royal Swamp Eel and your Level 4 Fish monster in the zone Geonator points to. Geonator should point to both Beelze and Zero Day now.
  14. Switch control of Beelze and Zero Day, and put Zero Day in a zone that Geonator doesn't point to.
  15. Use the Oyster Token Oyster Meister should've summoned earlier to make Link Spider (or Linkuriboh, your choice).
  16. Link Summon Agave Dragon using your Link-1, Link-2 Geonator, and Zero Day.

Now that that is done, you've already won the game. Agave Dragon's effect on Link Summon allows you to inflict 100 damage to your opponent. Beelze's effect will then activate, increasing its ATK. Red-Eyes Flare Metal Dragon will then also inflict 500 damage since your opponent activated an effect. Beelze's effect will then activate again, increasing its ATK. REFMD will then inflict again, and Beelze's effect will activate. This will keep looping until your opponent runs out of LP - it doesn't even matter how many they have, as the loop can inflict any amount of LP necessary.

Emergency Options

You might have to resort to Crooked Cook Exodia stall if necessary. But, if not, you can just play your FTK as usual. Otherwise, you can banish the 3 Rank 4s I put in there for Pot of Prosperity (or literally any other cards, doesn't have to be those 3 specifically).

That's all!

Enjoy this deck, and if you do, call it Ghoti to trick others ;)

Any thoughts or potential improvements I could make to the deck? Please comment, as all feedback's appreciated. Thanks! ^-^

Creator: Todd "Rogue Forever" Tolbart

Tournament: Halifax WCQ Regional- June 10th 2023

Placement: Top 4

Karakuri, Scrap and Watt have all been released around the end of the 5DS era and from those 3 Karakuri proofed to be the best of them. Today we look at Karakuri in all of it's detail and find out what makes these mindless Machines so strong: 

 

Help me I'm a Karakuri!

The gimmick of this Deck revolves around changing the Battle Position of your Monsters and sometimes the opponents Monsters too. Every Maindeck Karakuri has to attack if possible and will change it's Battle Position when targeted for an attack. Some Karakuri only change to Defense Position once and some always change their Battle Position when attacked, even back to Attack position. 

The bigger goal of Karakuri is to summon their 3 Synchro Shogun Bosses which are not forced to attack and do not change their Battle Position when attacked. Instead they always summon another Karakuri on synchro summon and have a unique effect on top of that. 

With many good interruption Cards and a lot of advantage this Deck proofs to be very unique and formidable and we will look at everything more closely now: 

 

Assembling the Karakuri Arsenal

We look at all Karakuri Monsters and their purpose sorted into 3 Categories. The Beta Models which always change their Battle Position when attacked and have to attack if possible. The Advanced Models which only change to Defense Position when attacked and also have to attack if possible and the Final Synchro Shogun Models which always summon another Karakuri Monster from the Deck when they are Synchro summoned and have no other downsides. Let's start with the Beta Models: 

Karakuri Gama mdl 4624 "Shirokunishi": A small L1 Karakuri Tuner which can banish itself from the GY as a Quick effect to change the Battle Position of a Karakuri Monster. He enables Synchro Climbing with your big Karakuri bosses and interruption plays during the opponents turn which makes him 100% essencial to be played at 3 copies at all times. He's a Garnet which you don't wanna see in your Hand if possible, but he's just to good to be ignored for your Strategy. 

Karakuri Komachi mdl 224 "Ninishi": She has 1900 DEF and is a L3 tuner which is nice and enables an additional Normal summon for an Karakuri Monster which is great to have. She's your 2nd best Starter to go into your Synchro Climb line with Karakuri Gama mdl 4624 "Shirokunishi" and can extend your lines further to end on up to 2 of your L9 Boss Shoguns Karakuri Super Shogun mdl 00N "Bureibu".

Karakuri Watchdog mdl 313 "Saizan": He's a L4 Tuner which can't be destroyed by Battle while in attack Position and has 1800 DEF. When you receive Damage from a Battle with this card you increase the ATK/DEF of all Karakuri Monsters by 800 until the end of this turn. In Theory this effect can trigger multiple times if the opponent attacks into him multiple times. The best application for him is to run into an opponents Monster to strengthen all your Karakuri Monsters by an hefty amount. 

Karakuri Ninja mdl 919 "Kuick": A L4 non tuner with 1700 ATK which revives a L4 or lower Karakuri from the GY to Defense Position when he destroys an opponents Monster by Battle. He can sometimes help to get your Synchro Line back online especially if cards like Karakuri Watchdog mdl 313 "Saizan" make him a 2500 ATK Beater before that. Fun Fact: He's one of 3 "Ninja" Monsters which are part of this Archetype. You can Build a whole Ninja Karakuri Strategy around him and the other 2 Karakuri Ninja^^

Karakuri Bonze mdl 9763 "Kunamzan": A L5 non tuner with 2000 ATK which can be special summoned by changing the Battle Position of one Karakuri you control. He will be treated as a L5 Tuner then and lock into Earth Machine Extra Deck summons. With Karakuri Merchant mdl 177 "Inashichi" together he forms a One Card Combo into your full Combo setup which makes him very much essencial. He can also be an easy L9 Synchro summon if combined with any other L4 non Tuner Karakuri making him the 3rd best Starter on top of all that. 

Karakuri Ninja mdl 7749 "Nanashick": A L5 non tuner with 2200 ATK who's also a "Ninja". He's the strongest Main Deck Monster and forms an perfect OTK when combined with Karakuri Steel Shogun mdl 00X "Bureido" and Karakuri Super Shogun mdl 00N "Bureibu" to deal exactly 8000 damage. If you tribute summon him you can draw Cards up to the Number of Karakuri Monsters in Defense Position. In theory that's up to 6 cards! In reality maybe 2 to 3 Cards are a bit more realistic. 

Let's continue with the advanced models which only change to Defense Position below: 

Karakuri Barrel mdl 96 "Shinkuro": A L2 Tuner which can't be destroyed by Battle Once per Turn. With him you can jump from your L7 Boss directly to the L9 Boss which is great to have. Almost only with this card you can end on 2 copies of Karakuri Super Shogun mdl 00N "Bureibu" during your initial turn. Just like Karakuri Gama mdl 4624 "Shirokunishi" he's a Garnet you don't wanna draw. 

Karakuri Merchant mdl 177 "Inashichi": When Normal Summoned he searches any Karakuri Card from your Deck. Easily your best Starter which forms the earlier mentioned 1 Card Full Combo Setup with Karakuri Bonze mdl 9763 "Kunamzan". You can search for every card in your Deck not limited to anything which makes him 100% essencial to the Strategy. 

Karakuri Strategist mdl 248 "Nishipachi": A L3 Tuner which on Normal or Special Summon targets any Monster on the field and changes it's Battle Position. He can be used to get over an difficult Monster from the opponent or as an Combo finisher to trigger the Banish effect from Karakuri Super Shogun mdl 00N "Bureibu" or the Draw effect from Karakuri Steel Shogun mdl 00X "Bureido".

Karakuri Ninja mdl 339 "Sazank": The only L3 non Tuner in the Deck and the third and Final "Ninja" Monster of the Archetype. When he's flipped face up he targets and sends one Monster on the field to the GY. During that turn he can attack directly with his 1200 ATK Statline. Since he's the only L3 non Tuner he enables a L7 line with Karakuri Watchdog mdl 313 "Saizan" and a L4 line into Armory Arm with Karakuri Gama mdl 4624 "Shirokunishi".

Karakuri Soldier mdl 236 "Nisamu": A L4 non tuner which is basically Giant Rat but for L4 or lower Karakuri Monsters. He's nice to crash into an opponents Monster multiple times to strengthen Karakuri Bushi mdl 6318 "Muzanichiha". This card could suddenly be a 3800 ATK Threat if combined with Karakuri Watchdog mdl 313 "Saizan". He's also good to thin out the Deck or to just be a L4 non Tuner for Synchro setups. 

Karakuri Muso mdl 818 "Haipa": HAIPA HAIPA! A L4 non Tuner with 2100 ATK which is changed to defense Position at the End of the Battle Phase if he attacked. This effect will trigger your Boss Monsters and setup your Counter Trap. He's pretty basic but useful in many Situations. 

Karakuri Bushi mdl 6318 "Muzanichiha": A L4 non Tuner with 1800 ATK which gains an additional 400 ATK whenever a Karakuri Monster is destroyed. He can get pretty chonky when combined with Karakuri Soldier mdl 236 "Nisamu" and is yet another important L4 non Tuner to get a easy L7 Synchro access with Karakuri Komachi mdl 224 "Ninishi".

Now we can look at the final 3 Karakuri Shogun models which are Synchro Bosses in the Extra Deck. They always summon any other Karakuri Monster from the Deck when they are Synchro summoned to the field: 

Karakuri Shogun mdl 00 "Burei": The L7 with 2600/1900 Statline. Once per Turn he can target any Monster on the field and Change it's Battle Position. He will help you to get over big problems from the opponent and help trigger the effects of the other 2 Shogun bosses. 

Karakuri Steel Shogun mdl 00X "Bureido": The L8 with 2800/1700 Statline. Once per Turn when a Karakuri Monster changes it's Battle Position you Draw 1 Card. Since this is not hard once per turn you can easily get multiple Draws with him and find everything you need from your Deck. 

Karakuri Super Shogun mdl 00N "Bureibu": The L9 with 3000/1500 Statline. Once per turn if the Battle Position of a Karakuri Monster is changed you can target 1 card from the opponent and Banish it. Furthermore Karakuri Monsters in defense Position cannot be destroyed by Battle. He's the culmination of everything your Deck could ever need. Easy Disruption during the opponents turn with cards like Karakuri Gama mdl 4624 "Shirokunishi" and protection for all Karakuri Monsters on top of that. 

 

The Big Karakuri Trickbox 

We finally went through all the Monsters but guess what, there's good backrow too! Let's take a look at it: 

Karakuri Showdown Castle: When a Karakuri Monster attacks you can change the Battle Position of the opponents Monster. When this card is destroyed you can target a L4 or higher Karakuri Monster in your GY and special summon it. Not the most broken Field Spell but also not bad. I always like to play the Field Spell if the Archetype has one so it's a one of option here. It is non targeting Battle Position changing which is very nice to have. 

Karakuri Cash Cache: Target a Karakuri and change it's Battle Position to search any L4 or lower Karakuri from your Deck. Pretty useful to get Karakuri Merchant mdl 177 "Inashichi" or a L4 non Tuner that is missing while Karakuri Komachi mdl 224 "Ninishi" is already on the field. I like to play this card rather then Karakuri Anatomy which is a Draw 2 which let's you draw Karakuri Gama mdl 4624 "Shirokunishi" more often then you want to. 

Karakuri Gama Oil: A equip which targets a Karakuri in the GY and revives it back to the field. Once per turn if the Battle Position of a Karakuri Monster is changed the equipped Monster gains a permanent 500 ATK/DEF Boost even if this card leaves the field. This card is a better Premature Burial in every way. Even if Karakuri Gama Oil leaves the field the revived monster won't leave the field. Also it's a mandatory effect which can create an easy chainblock with Karakuri Steel Shogun mdl 00X "Bureido" combined to get safe draws. 

Karakuri Trick House: When the Battle Position of a Karakuri is changed you can target 1 Card on the field and destroy it. A simple yet effective removal Trap and a nice addition to the interruption lineup. You could potentially use it to destroy your own field spell Karakuri Showdown Castle and get a reborn effect triggered in the process. 

Karakuri Cash Inn: Target a Karakuri and a opponents Monster. Change the Battle Position of your Monster and negate the effects from the opponents Monster until the end of this turn. You can banish this card from the GY, if a Karakuri is on the field, to target any Monster on the field and change it's Battle Position. This card has versatility written all over it and is very useful in many Situations. You don't have to fear Called by the Grave thanks to this card. 

Karakuri Cash Shed: A Counter Trap that negates the activation of a Spell/Trap and destroys it if you control a Karakuri Monster in defense Position. A Simple effect which is very easy to activate and has no other restrictions. Branded Fusion is ready to be negated thanks to this card:) 

 

Further thoughts on the Archetype

In the Extra Deck you see quite a few options besides the Karakuri Shogun Monsters. These can be changed around to your liking but I chose to play a few more unknown contenders in these slots. For Master Duel Divine Arsenal AA-ZEUS - Sky Thunder and Underworld Goddess of the Closed World are usually always great additions. 

As for the Archetype itself I chose to play this Deck as a going first Deck with lots of interruption. If you wanna play it going second you gotta include Karakuri Gold Dust to the mix which is a great OTK tool. 

Runaway Karakuri is also quite nice for going second builds and Limiter Removal should be a no brainer. Golden Gearbox just doesn't cut it for me but feel free to experiment if you wanna use a going 2nd OTK Build. 

 

Karakuri fail to follow Orders

These mindless Karakuri machines have a few obvious disadvantages to them. Being forced to attack can really bite you if you don't play carefully. Karakuri Komachi mdl 224 "Ninishi" has 0 ATK and could easily fall into an enemys Trap. 

Also there's only Battle Protection so you better prepare your Counter Trap in an Raigeki emergency case. Them being machines is a general disadvantage too. The vs. Cyber Dragon Matchup doesn't work in your favor. 

Finally Ash Blossom & Joyous Spring is an enemy for your Karakuri Merchant mdl 177 "Inashichi" and can stop you easily. Karakuri Komachi mdl 224 "Ninishi" is the more safe starter in that regard but even then they could use Infinite Impermanence or wait until the first Shogun is summoned and use Ash Blossom & Joyous Spring then. 

Thanks to strong backrow and usable Maindeck Monsters you do have a Chance for a Comeback from bad positions, so it's not all darkness if your initial play is prevented. 

 

The Final Order 

Karakuri is a pretty strong Deck especially going first. You can easily negate and banish multiple cards while gaining massive Draw advantage. Being able to manipulate Battle Positions and avoid taking damage is very nice to have too. 

Almost every turn you have access to a full Combo setup and can easily OTK the opponent after getting rid of all his ressources. Karakuri are a lot of fun and easy to learn. I'm always amazed if I manage to beat full Combo Branded because of all the interruption you have easily ready. 

If you like Machines or like Decks like Morphtronic, Karakuri is the Deck for you^^ 

 

Final Rating: 

OTK Potential

Defensive Tools

Control Options

Removal Options

Recovery/Recycling

Card Advantage

Overall Rating:   33/42

 

 

The Karakuri Ruling Trickhouse 

There's a few rulings you should know about before getting started with this Deck: 

Karakuri Merchant mdl 177 "Inashichi": His search is mandatory. 

Karakuri Strategist mdl 248 "Nishipachi": His effect is mandatory. 

Karakuri Komachi mdl 224 "Ninishi": You can only use the additional normal summon once per turn.

Karakuri Watchdog mdl 313 "Saizan": His effect is mandatory. 

Karakuri Ninja mdl 919 "Kuick": His effect is mandatory. 

Karakuri Ninja mdl 339 "Sazank": His effect is mandatory. 

Karakuri Bushi mdl 6318 "Muzanichiha": His effect is mandatory. 

Karakuri Muso mdl 818 "Haipa": His effect is mandatory. 

Karakuri Steel Shogun mdl 00X "Bureido": His effect is mandatory. 

Karakuri Showdown Castle: The 2nd effect can miss timing. 

Karakuri Gama Oil: The ATK increase is Mandatory.

deck_excerpt: Blind Second Sky Striker, but using the latest 2023 June banlist!
deck_description:
Want to see the deck in action? Scroll to the very bottom for the Youtube video!


Who is gonna win? Hordes of Demons, Superpowerful Dragons, Masters of Arcane Arts,

Or a single girl (with friends) in a mech suit? My money is on Raye, since she is more powerful than ever with not one, BUT TWO COPIES OF ENGAGE, THE MOST BUSTED CARD IN YUGIOH!

The philosophy with blind second Sky Strikers is to destroy most if not all of your opponent's resources that they slap down on the board going first, and then close out the match with Sky Striker's unparalleled grind game. This deck has cards specifically picked out for the June 2023 meta, like Triple Tactics Talent (super good since everyone uses Branded, Flundereeze, and handtraps, etc).

The current meta allows for Evenly Matched and Raigeki to obliterate most duelist's boards this format since they spend all their resources building their "unbreakable" board only to fall to 1-2 cards.


When your opponent forces you to go 1st thinking all you do is spam "Raigeki" and "Evenly Matched," metagame them by siding in devastating floodgates like TCBOO and Grave of the Superancient Organism!

If your weakened opponent hasn't surrendered yet due to the sheer resource advantage and offensive pressure this deck generates, you can clear the board with a plethora of cards including Linkage, allowing Raye to OTK all by herself!

If you have any questions about this deck, feel free to ask me in the comments below!

Want to see the deck in action? Scroll to the very bottom for the Youtube video!

deck_excerpt: Cyberdark end dragon consistent combo and broken end board
deck_description:
Very consistent combo to get out a Cyberdark End Dragon with a Dragon Buster Sword Equipped.

route: Cyber Dragon Core + 1 cyber or cyberdark + 1 spell or trap

normal cyber dragon core Board: cyber dragon core

search cyberdark realm

play cyberdark realm Board: cyber dragon core cyberdark realm

search cyberdark claw

activate cyberdark claw hand effect : discard and search cybernetic horizon

play cybernetic horizon

discard additional cyber or cyberdark monster as well as another from deck send cyber end dragon to grave add cyberdark cannon

activate cannon hand effect discard add cyberdark chimeratech

activate cyberdark realm second effect normal summon cyberdark chimera  Board: cyber dragon core, cyberdark chimera, cyberdark realm

activate cyberdark chimera discard spell/trap add powerbond to hand

link cyber dragon core, cyberdark chimera into union carrier Board: union carrier, cyberdark realm

activate cyberdark chimera grave effect discard an additional cyberdark from deck

activate powerbond to summon cyberdarkness dragon using chimera effect (materials: claw, cannon, chimera, horizon mill, chimera mill)

equip cyberdarkness with cyber end dragon

summon cyberdark end dragon equip with monster of choosing

activate union carrier equip cyberdark end with Dragon Buster Sword,   Board: union carrier, cyberdark end equipped with cyber end or cyberdarkness and dragon buster sword, cyberdark realm.

End board 6000 atk uneffected cyberdark end with 2 attacks + opponent cannot summon from extra deck. stupidly hard to beat over.

some combo of a spell or trap you can discard as well as a cyber or cyberdark you can discard + a normal summon monster + realm into claw into horizon into cannon into chimera into powerbond into darkness into cyberdarkness end dragon.

Mess around with the deck and it is very consistent. Can also get out 6400+ atk chimeratech overdragon with 4+ attacks or 5600 cybertwin very easily.

~Cyberdark Win~

This deck focuses on the summon and sustain of your cyberdark monsters. Some of the information below may seem obvious but gives an in depth look into how and why each card is used.

~Big 3~ ( The bread and butter ) Basics

Cyberdark Edge, Horn, Keel : 1) Big beefy beat sticks while "C.D. Cannon" or "C.D. Claw" is equiped.  ( ATK2400/DEF800 )  

                                                 2) "C.D. Cannon" & "C.D. Claw" are always priority for attachment "C.D. Chimera" is not used as equip material unless                                                           no other option is available.

                                                 3) "Cyberdark Invasion" Allows for extra material to be attached to your "Big 3" boosting damage. ( ATK3400/DEF800 ) 

                                                     This also allows a counter method to grave heavy decks with both graves accessable for material attachment.

                                                 4) "Cyberdark Invasion" Also lets you remove an attached material to destroy any 1 card on your opponents field.    

                                                      Typically you will discard your "C.D" attatchment then requip later with "C.D. Invasion".

 

Cyberdark Cannon : 1) Discard to pull your "Big 3" to your hand. Can also be used to bring "C.D. Claw" to hand.

                                  2) Used to send "Cyber D. Core" or "Cyber D. Herz" to grave for chain.

Cyberdark Claw :      1) Discard to pull your "C.D. Spell/Trap" to your hand. Used first to bring "C.D. Inferno" to hand giving protection to your "Big 3"

                                      If you draw into "C.D. Inferno" then "C.D. Realm" or "C.D Invasion" will be your next choices based on your first hand.

                                  2) After battle, while equiped send your "Cyber End Dragon" from your extra deck  to grave to set it up as an attach material.

Cyberdark Chimera: 1) Discard 1 Spell to bring "Power Bond" to your hand then allows graveyard monsters to be used for the first fusion summon

                                      of that turn.

                                  2) Once sent to the graveyard you will be allowed to send any cyberdark monster from your deck to the graveyard allowing it 

                                      to be used as an attached material either by the effect of the "Big 3" or "C.D Invasion". Alternatively you can load your grave

                                      with the remaining  "Big 3" to summon out "Cyberdark Dragon" or "Cyber Darkness Dragon" w/ cards like "Overload fusion"

                                      "Power Bond" paired with "C.D. Chimera" effect. Just be sure to have used your "C.D. Claw" to send "Cyber End Dragon" to

                                       the grave to make youre "Cyber Darkness Dragon" a massive ( ATK6000/DEF2000 ). The "Cyberdark End Dragon" route is 

                                       typicaly situational with the "Cyber Darkness Dragon" route being far more usefull in the current meta.

 

~Cyberdark Spells/Traps~

Now that we have a basic understanding of how our Cyberdark monsters function lets take a look at some of the spells and traps.

Cyberdark Inferno : 1) "Cyberdark" "Effect Monsters you control that are equipped with an Equip Card cannot be destroyed by your opponent's card

                                       effects, also your opponent cannot target them with card effects." This is a massivly important to keep your field safe paired 

                                       with the effect of "Cyber Darkness Dragon" When your opponent activates a card or effect (Quick Effect): You can send 1 Equip

                                       Card you control to the GY; negate the activation, and if you do, destroy that card. Your field will be very hard to work around .

                                  2) If this card in its owner's control is destroyed by an opponent's card effect: You can add 1 "Polymerization" Spell or "Fusion"

                                      Spell from your Deck to your hand. This will allow you to bring your "Overload Fusion" or "Cyberload Fusion" quickly to your

                                      hand in the event that it is destroyed insuring additional protection. 2 copies are mandatory and "Terraforming" is not required

                                      due to "C.D. Claw's" effect to search for it.

Cyberdark Invasion : 1) Target 1 "Cyberdark" Effect Monster you control; equip 1 Dragon or Machine monster from either GY to it as an Equip Spell that

                                     gives it 1000 ATK.  Remember that Massive "Cyber Darkness Dragon" well yes it got bigger. With the more recent popularity 

                                     towards branded decks. You can snag away those pesky fusion grave monsters but keep in mind only dragons and machines can 

                                     be attached.

                                   2) Yes if "Cyber Darkness Dragons" effect was not enough you can also "Send 1 Equip Card you control equipped to a Machine 

                                       monster to the GY; destroy 1 card your opponent controls." 2 Copies of this card is also a must and is as well searchable with

                                       "C.D. Claw's" effect.

Cyberdark Realm :     1) Allows you to bring other cyber dark monsters you dont already have into your hand and immediatly summon that card or 1 

                                       other monster from your hand.

                                   2) Allows you to use your opponents grave for material to equip much like other cards in the cyberdark arsenal.

 

You now hopefully have a better understanding of how this engine works and how to get some beefy boys on the field. This guide only covers the cyber dark engine but rest assured with this knowledge you can incorporate all the listed cards below and pull out some very satisfying wins! Thank you for viewing and if you have any comments or sugestions for the deck im always looking for new info !!!

deck_description: Here's a deck I made for a thing
yuh
hooray

A deck I once tried way back before Alba Zoa even released, now made a functional strategy with Climax of the Showdown! Dogmatika Ritual was once pretty bad, with being bricky and not even having great payoffs for the Rituals on their own.

That era, is no longer. Alba Zoa and Dogmatikamatrix have ushered in a new era of anti-ED dueling, and while not meta this deck packs a significant punch and can play with the big boys with the right tech (and a good hand). Let's start with the main engine:

  • 3x Ecclesia, as we need to search all the useful Dogmatika engine somehow. She herself can be searched via Nadir Servant, and the second search of Dogmatikamatrix can do so as well.
  • 1x of the original main deck bosses of Dogmatika, Fleurdelis and Maximus. They're still good cards, but Maximus only bolsters good boards and Fleurdelis' negate only activates if you have a second Dogmatika on the board so we don't want to just draw into them on their own. Cut Maximus if you want to.
  • 3x Dogmatikamatrix. Searches a Dogmatika Ritual, whether a monster or spell, and if your opponent has a monster on field you get to search any Dogmatika card. Also lets you scout your opponent's extra if you control a Dogmatika Ritual, giving you the ability to comfortably decide whether you want to use Alba Zoa's effect, or you can just dump something from your extra to proc useful effects.
  • 3x Dogmatikalamity, our primary Ritual spell. It can use a Fusion/Synchro monster from the Extra Deck as material for your Ritual, meaning the inherent minus of Ritual Spells is now closer to even (or even a plus, depending on what you're sending and how you can benefit from it). Make sure you have at least one Level 12 for Alba Zoa.
  • 1x Dogmatikamacabre, our secondary Ritual spell. This is usually used to summon White Relic, since you'll typically have a Level 4 in grave to banish and you'd have probably spent your use of Dogmatikalamity for the turn.
  • 1x Branded in Central Dogmatika, enables you to further benefit from Ritual summons by dumping an ED monster of your choice from either players ED. Can be cut, it's only good for further bolstering good hands.
  • 3x Dogmatika Punishment. One of the best Trap cards ever printed in general, so of course we run it in its namesake deck.
  • 1x Dogmatika Alba Zoa. Alba Zoa, the corrupted form of Maximus, is a crazy powerful boss monster... with a few asterisks attached. For starters, his protection only applies to Extra Deck monsters, and only to activated effects. Which means he is unable to do anything about Spell/Traps, main deck monsters, or lingering effects (like, say, Mirrorjade's field wipe effect). However, if you can get it onto the field, you'll be able to force your opponent to dump 7 cards from their Extra, discard from their hand, or if they have no Extra Deck left shuffle all their ED monsters back. Combine that with his tremendous 4k/4k statline, and some decks just plain don't have an out to him.
  • 1x White Relic of Dogmatika. Aside from being cute, she's Alba Zoa's biggest supporter by removing one of his weaknesses (being destroyed by things bigger than him) and our OTK enabler. She also dumps a monster of your choice from your opponent's ED if your opponent summons from it, making things harder for your opponent. Her main role though, is to buff herself to 4.5k with Alba Zoa and beat your opponent to death with him.
  • 1x Nadir Servant. Not technically a Dogmatika card by name, but important for the archetype. I run one due to economics, run as many copies as you can. Searching literally any Dogmatika while dumping a monster from the ED is just good (note that the only monster with over 4k we have is Five-Headed Dragon, who is our only target for summon Alba Zoa with Dogmatikalamity, so just be careful with how you do your combo).
  • I don't run White Knight as I don't want to brick on Rituals any more than I already do and I find I'm never going for it over Alba Zoa or White Relic, but it is a strong card that is more proactive with playing on your opponent's turn.

For side engine stuff, we run Bystials to deal with other LIGHT/DARK decks, Diviner of the Herald as a NS to send Arc Light, and Shaddoll Schism to summon Winda. Everything else is just tech cards from the basic MD handtrap suite to boardbreakers, which can be switched as you desire to suit the meta.

The ED:

  • 3x Herald of the Arc Light. We're playing a Ritual deck that dumps cards from ED to grave, of course we're playing this. It's technically possible to summon this under an extremely narrow circumstance (having both Diviner and Maxx C on field), but realisitically speaking you won't be summoning this.
  • 1x Elder Entity N'tss. We're playing a deck that dumps ED cards, of course we run one of the best Dogmatika Punishment targets. More copies are a good idea, I only own one so I just run one.
  • 1x Fossil Warrior Skull Knight, Fossil Machine Skull Wagon, Mereologic Aggregator, Garura Wings of Resonant Life, Tri-Brigade Ferrijit the Barren Blossom, Granguignol the the Dusk Dragon, other things to dump. There's plenty of other targets you can pick to dump, these are just the ones I went with.
  • 1x of Apkallone and Winda, our method of using the Schism engine. Dump Apkallone, grab Schism and discard, make Winda next turn and floodgate your opponent.
  • 1x Five-Headed Dragon as a Dogmatikalamity target to summon Alba Zoa. Can be replaced by any Level 12, but a DARK one is preferred for the Bystial and Schism engines. Despian Lulawalilith would probably be the best option, but not in MD yet.
  • 1x Barrone de Fleur just because we have a tuner and could occasionally summon it. Entirely replacable.
  • 1x Linguriboh as my out to Iblee, as otherwise this deck would simply keel over on the spot if Iblee is summoned. Also replacable, we're not in an Iblee meta right now so it doesn't matter that much, but I had the space and noticed the weakness so I corrected.

And that's the list. As always, feel free to ask questions, I'll try to answer to the best of my ability. Goal is generally to just turbo out Alba Zoa as quickly as possible and then do other shit from there with the rest of your hand hoping that your opponent doesn't have an immediate out to Alba Zoa.

deck_excerpt: Too poor to play the optimal Branded build? Try Slifer
deck_description:
This is a take on a Branded deck that holds true to the basic combos, but focuses on preventing your opponent building a board on their turn in lieu of more expensive combo pieces like Quem, Cartesia, etc. Some basic ideas of the deck are below.

Going First:

- Slifer the Sky Dragon is a main card used to attempt to shut your opponent's board down, but only if you see The Revived Sky God or Trap Trick in hand. The main sequence to first set one of the aforementioned traps, then to utilize Branded Fusion to dump Fallen of Albaz and Slifer the Sky Dragon to fuse into Brigrand the Glory Dragon. This unfortunately does kill the normal line of fusion summons in a Branded deck profile. However, once you pass turn, you can activate either The Revived Sky God or Trap Trick to utilize the Revived Sky God's effect, summoning Slifer from grave, restoring card advantage to hand, and putting a 6000ATK Slifer on the field that auto-kills any monster summoned with less than 2000ATK. Brigrand also protect Slifer from opponent card effects. Ideally, you activate the trap as soon as possible in order to have your opponent draw as few cards as possible. The main downside of this combo is that Slifer must be destroyed in the End Phase since it was special summoned.

- Instant Fusion is meant to summon Millennium-Eyes Restrict, essentially acting as a second copy of Called by the Grave. As with Slifer, it is destroyed in the End Phase so use wisely.

Going Second:

The entire aforementioned Slifer engine, Monster Reborn, Harpie's Feather Duster, Allure of Darkness, and Branded Retribution are meant to be swapped out for the entire side deck to grant maximum interruption without much change to regular branded combos. Allure of Darkness is the only card that may be dangerous to swap out since draw power would be sacrificed.

- Albion the Sanctifire Dragon can only be played going second since Effect Veiler is the only Light Spellcaster available in the deck. This can be changed if you can afford more expensive cards like Blazing Cartesia, the Virtuous

- Fusion Deployment is an excellent way to break your opponent's board, easily using Fallen of Albaz effect to get into an easy Mirrorjade the Iceblade Dragon 

 

Other deviatons:

- Allure of Darkness grants some extra draw power, ideally banishing Despian Tragedy to search other Despia monsters, especially Aluber the Jester of Despia in a pinch. Allure works generally well because, with exception of Slifer, all monsters are Dark attribute. If you can afford Quem, Cartesia, or perhaps the more budget friendly Incredible Ecclesia, the Virtuous, Allure can easily be removed in favor of these cards.

- Red-Eyes Dark Dragoon is easily included because Dragoon is the G.O.A.T.

deck_excerpt: Good deck, gets rid of all monster zones.
deck_description: Yippeee!!!!
Ancient Warriors N/R for fun!

My most "Budget" (under 60$/Euros) Ghoti deck using 1 or more engine/s, Supay, (Lifeless Leaffish, and Beautunaful Princess), and 2 tech cards, Icejade Ran Aegirine and Hop Ear Squadron.

Not a very competitive deck or meta, can die often to handtraps. Pretty consistent, but needs more trials to see if it really works that well. Tried to stay under 60$/Euros by all means by the current shown prices, even if we lose some power/consistency.

 

A number of Ghoti MONSTERS:

2x Snopios, Shade of the Ghoti , using a 3rd one might brick more often,

2x Ixeep, Omen of the Ghoti , using a 3rd would brobably brick, and may be unnecessary,

1x Zep, Ruby of the Ghoti , because I found that it is not that useful in hand or field, can add one though,

3x Shif, Fairy of the Ghoti , the main way to synchro but if done on opponent's turn after returning from banishmet you can only summon FISH,

3x Paces, Light of the Ghoti , the main way to synchro but if done on opponent's turn after returning from banishmet you can only summon FISH.

3x Lifeless Leaffish  and 3x Beautunaful Princess : I found them very useful, basically you can begin your combos.

On the other hand, 3x Minairuka , 2x Silent Angler , can't say that I like them because their effects are a bit restraining (i.e. Minairuka negates opponent's effects ONLY on OUR TURN and is not a Quick Effect, and Silent can special itself if we control another water monster BUT we can't special from our hand for the rest of the turn which on one instance bricked me)... However they are pretty cheap and might be useful in other ways.

3x Supay, Duskwalker  and 1x Supay : The main engine outside of Ghoti. 1 Supay because it isn't useful, alone in hand, without Duskwalker, and 3 Duskwalkers because they are pretty good, require a discard (most of the times I discard Shif if in hand). Maybe they can be cut to 2 because you only have 1 Supay and once in grave, you can't get it back.

I tried 2 techs:

1) 3x Icejade Aegirine : I was impressed by it's usefulness: Discard 1 Water monster, special summon it (lvl 7 Tuner) and activate to summon a lvl 3 Token. After that you can synchro to your level 10s, basically Supreme Chengying and if I remember correctly in general level 10s. Can be done turn 1 too!

2) 3x Hop Ear Squadron : On opoonent's turn, target 1 monster you control, special the card and then immediately synchro. Basically levels 6, 8 or 10 will be at your service if the correct numbers are on field! Ghoti of the Deep will still activate and banish!

SPELLS: 1x The Most Distant, Deepest Depths (can add another copy but not sooo useful a spell), 1x Gold Sarcophagus (ummm, idk, with a good hand it can banish a Shif or Paces and then return) it is supposed to boost consistency as well as 2x Pot of Desires (can get you out of trouble, banish 10 cards. Chenying can boost its ATK by 1000 I THINK), 1x Terraforming (to search for field spell), 1x Called by the Grave .

TRAPS: 1x Dimensional Barrier (might be useful once you know opponent's strategy) and 1x Ghoti Chain (can also save you a material or Ghoti monster).

 

EXTRA DECK:

2x Ghoti of the Deep Beyond lvl 10, pretty big monster on turn 2 or 4 since you need materials in banishment to gain massive ATK (3500+), weak to destruction,

2x Askaan, the Bicorned Ghoti lvl 8, most useful,

2x Arionpos, Serpent of the Ghoti lvl 6, main tech - synchro,

1x Guoglim, Spear of the Ghoti lvl 8, never used him, can be cut too and add another 6 or 8 of the others,

1x Icejade Gymir Aegirine lvl 10, strong, can be useful if opponent starts destroying/banishing,

1x Swordsoul Supreme Sovereign - Chengying lvl 10, strong, but weak to banishments,

1x Adamancipator Risen - Dragite lvl 8, negate and destroy spell/trap if a Water monster in your GY,

1x Ruddy Rose Dragon lvl 10, can banish all cards on both GY once summoned, very cool for Ghoti and Chen,

1x Satellite Warrior lvl 10, target cards your opponent controls, up to the number of Synchro Monsters in your GY; destroy them, gains 1000 ATK for each card destroyed (if 3 then 5500 ATK),

1x Metaphys Horus lvl 6, *Effect Monster: you can target 1 other face-up card on the field; negate that target's effects permanetly,

1x Crystal Wing Synchro Dragon lvl 8, basically can become a pretty big ATK dragon and negates effects,

1x Brionac, Dragon of the Ice Barrier lvl 6, discard any number of cards to the GY, target the same number of cards your opponent controls; return those cards to the hand (ummm I think that might be useful at times).

 

In my opinion, ANYTHING BELOW Ruddy Rose can be changed if you want and add more copies or monsters, according to budget. **Note that Paces' and Shif's effects, summon FISH monsters and anything else needs to be summoned on your own turn.

Cards not used because of their cost and thought that synergy was not affected without them in this version: (1) Abyss Shark engine and (2) Number 4: Stealth Kragen, (3) White Aura Whale (12 euros is too much for a card for me, and being on budget below 60 is the only option to cut it, since it needs to be the first thing in a Chain to be summoned and can be easily "missed on timing"). Ash, Psy-Gamma, Infinite, Solemn, Evenly, Crossout D, Baronne, Accel Stardust, Stardust Dragon, Psychic End Punisher, Link monsters can all be implemented and cut some other cards. It will boost its consistency and competitiveness!


Tell me your thoughts and oppinions on how we can push this to more power on low budget! *Forgive me if I messed some things up, I'm pretty new to Yu-Gi-Oh, coming from Master Duel...*

 

*Credits to Rogue Tier (https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=dM8dcKnBQ-A&t=455s&ab_channel=RogueTier) and Deepsea Darew (https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=aHhKqeUi1G8&ab_channel=DeepseaDarew) for the ideas!

deck_excerpt: A.K.A. Lady of Lament Visas (I guess...)
deck_description:
Loka Samsara is a new card coming out in AGOV and with it being able to Summon a Visas counterpart from your Extra Deck, it gives you a lot of utility considering the monsters you can summon off of it. Tearlaments Kaleido-Heart shuffles a card your opponent controls into the Deck, Kashtira Arise-Heart is just Macro Cosmos, and Scareclaw Tri-Heart changes all monsters to Defense and is unaffected by Defense Position monsters (let's pretend that Prime-Heart doesn't exist). However, the catch is that you need to banish a Visas Starfrost you control to activate it. My first idea to use the card is in Lady of Lament to easily search it while summoning Visas off of Fusion Deployment because you rarely go into the Extra Deck turn 1 and since the DARK Fiends allow you to hard summon Visas from hand also. 

For monsters we have 3 Lord of the Heavenly Prison, 1 Darkest Diabolos, Lord of the Lair, 1 Visas Starfrost, 2 Tour Guide from the Underworld, 3 Lilith, Lady of Lament, 3 Alice, Lady of Lament, and 1 Sangan. To supplement the fact that all of the Visas counterparts in the Extra Deck are DARK monsters, we are playing Virus Traps to get more value off of them before they are eventually banished face-down during the End Phase from Loka Samsara. This is also why we are playing Darkest Diabolos to have a large, recurring, untargetable body on the field. I'm choosing Sangan over Doomdog Octhros because we are running triple Fusion Deployment and we can also choose to Fusion Deployment revealing Sanwitch for Sangan to search follow-up.

For Spell/Traps: 3 Fusion Deployment, 3 Pot of Prosperity, 3 Ties of the Brethren. Only 2 Loka Samsara since it needs to banish a face-up Visas Starfrost you control to activate. This means that if you draw multiple copies of this card with no ways to access Visas, you have a literal dead card in  your hand. Also, because it can add itself back to hand from GY when your opponent summons from the Extra Deck, you really do not need 3 of it in Deck unless you want to reliably search it off of Lilith. However, you still need Visas on field to do anything with it. 2 Eradicator Epidemic Virus and 3 Deck Devastation Virus since all of the Visas Extra Deck monsters are DARK, so they make for good Virus fodder before they eventually banish themselves face-down during the End Phase. 1 Trap Trick, 3 Infinite Impermanence, 3 Archfiend's Ghastly Glitch, and 3 Anti-Spell Fragrance. 

Extra Deck: 1 Vicious Astraloud, 2 Tearlaments Kaleido-Heart, 1 Kashtira Arise-Heart, 2 Scareclaw Tri-Heart, 1 Sanwitch, 1 Elder Entity N'tss, 1 Divine Arsenal AA-ZEUS - Sky Thunder, 1 D/D/D Deviser King Deus Machinex, 1 Mereologic Aggregator, 1 D/D/D Stone King Darius, 1 EvilTwin's Trouble Sunny, 1 Dharc the Darck Charmer, Gloomy, and 1 Salamangreat Almiraj. 

Side Deck is mainly going second stuff along with Dimensional Barriers and  Destructive Daruma Karma Cannon. Looking at Loka Samsara, it is definitely an interesting card, but you cannot get much out of it due to the fact that you need to banish a Visas you control to activate it. Dedicated Trap Decks can play if they run something like Fusion Deployment of some other way to get Visas on the field, but it is still clunky unless you build your whole deck around it. I really doubt that a Mannadium deck would even play it either as you get so much more out of its standard combo already.

deck_excerpt: "Suffering-laden cycle of life, death, and rebirth, without beginning or end"
deck_description:
Check the older Deck profile for in-depth explanation on the Deck, in this follow-up list I will explain some of my thoughts on the new cards and the changes done to the Decklist.

Changes:

  • Reduced the number of Reichheart, Reichnophobia and Arrival, cause you won't be able to full combo again in case your board gets destroyed and sometimes you would open/draw a card that just ain't gonna do much.
  • Removed Mannadium Fearless, Torid/Trid is a way better card since it tutors Meek which is full combo with Mannadium Riumheart. Fearless only use would be making Naturia Beast but that is too hard to pull off.
  • Removed Merlli cause the Dragostapelia/Sprind line was pretty inconsistent. 
  • Removed Adamancipator Risen Dragite and replaced it with Borreload which will equip Light Heart or Cross-Sheep.
  • Added in More Handtraps.

Thoughts on the New support:

  • Trilosukda is all the Deck needed, would have been crazy if she wasnt a tuner... Would allow any Deck that can make a Level 6 to go into Accel to then go into Dis Pater or Baronne, she helps Synchro Climb into Visas Amritara or Prime=Heart for the lol's.
  • Samsara would have been interesting in the Deck but unfortunately he is unsearcheable. 
  • Veda has some synergy with the Deck but I feel like there are too many deviations from the main combo to pull his turn skip effect off, since if you dont draw Elegy you will have to climb into Amritara to search it and then pop 4 cards.
  • Sarv Sarga is the only other one I want to mention and it would have been funny to Arise=Heart jumpscare but the restriction causes it to be not that good.

deck_excerpt: Vice-Madame turbo featuring Blazing Cartesia, the Virtuous
deck_description:
I was playing Branded with the new support and I got struck by a realisation:
Blazing Cartesia, the Virtuous , a spellcaster monster who fusion summons as a quick effect? This girl is a Witchcrafter monster.

The aim of  this deck is to find Cartesia with Fusion Deployment or Branded in High Spirits along with any witchcrafter to make Witchcrafter Vice-Madame  and combo off, usually ending with her + Witchcrafter Madame Verre , Witchcrafter Bystreet  and a pile of spells in hand. I've also put in a Tearlament package because we can summon Tearlaments Reinoheart  from deck with Fusion Deployment and mill a bunch of useful witchcrafter spells, then end on Tearlaments Rulkallos .

This deck is really bad going second. Sorry. Forbidden Droplet helps, but there's only so much we can do.

Here are some notes on specific cards I've chosen to include:


Albion the Shrouded Dragon is basically upstart goblin if we draw it, and if we open with a cartesia available we can use Branded in High Spirits to search him and dump another high spirits to draw one card. Deck thinning! Also if we mill/discard him, we get to special summon Cartesia from hand every turn.

Branded in High Spirits Most of the time we will reveal any spellcaster to send it + Granguignol the Dusk Dragon to GY and add Blazing Cartesia, the Virtuous to hand. But as mentioned above, we can also search albion in a pinch. But if we get lucky and open a tearlament girl we can instead send Tearlaments Rulkallos to fetch cartesia, because rulk is a level 8 fusion monster with 2500 def. Neat. And high spirits discards for effect, so the tear girl we discard will be able to immediately fuse into either Tearlaments Kitkallos or Predaplant Dragostapelia .

Tearlaments. The usual combo after succesfully making Vice-Madame is: Summon reino with Fusion Deployment , send havnis, make kitkalos, add merrli, send kit to gy to summon merrli, mill 8 feel great, then use vice-madame to destroy merrli and summon rulk when our witchcrafter spells or cartesia trigger in end phase.

Spright Sprind is the reason Witchcrafter Potterie is in the deck. We can summon her from deck with vice-madame and make sprind, then send merrli to GY in order to fuse into either a tear fusion or Predaplant Dragostapelia  or Granguignol the Dusk Dragon . I experimented with elf as well but very rarely found it useful compared to sprind.

Despian Proskenion is optional, but I like having it because it's just free off a grang in grave.

Accesscode Talker If we have the right materials we can pretty easily climb into him from two monsters via a charmer and Selene, Queen of the Master Magicians . Notably, accesscode + vice-madame together deal exactly 8000 damage.

Don't just use Selene, Queen of the Master Magicians to climb into accesscode though because we have a ton of amazing spellcaster monsters we want to summon from hand/GY.

Guardian Chimera NOTE: The on-summon effect only triggers if summoned by a spell card, so if you make it with cartesia you don't get to draw/destroy. Sometimes worth it anyway for the high attack. You could swap it out for Quintet Magician I suppose, if you feel spicy.

 

Feel free to tweak the witchcrafter spell ratios to your liking, but 3 Witchcrafter Creation is essential. I'm not running many handtraps because we need to keep the monster count down, and also it sucks if they get milled instead of something useful. It's probably better to cut the 2 effect veilers for one maxx c, but i only own 2 copies and i hate the card and so I never end up crafting the 3rd one. That said, effect veiler has additional utility in this deck, as it can be used as material for our spellcaster fusion monsters, or discarded with high spirits to find cartesia.

deck_excerpt: To think we could've gone somewhere this banlist...
deck_description: Hello frens, it's been awhile. It seems that not much has changed since the last time I appeared but it's fine. Just like this deck there really doesn't to fixate on anything drastic; simply because we aren't getting any new support for neither Tenyi or Swordsoul anytime soon that is game changing or groundbreaking. However what I did notice was that a prominent Synchro Monster just got released from the banlist after half a decade on it. "Denglong, First of the Yang Zing" was a very impactful synchro monster for it's time: being that it can not only manipulate it's level with whatever monster you mill to the GY, which in case can be any monster that can benefit from being in the GY or have GY effects (such as the Tenyi monsters if a normal monster is on the field). The result of this allows easier access to synchro monsters you normally wouldn't be able to access under the typical Swordsoul-Tenyi playstyle (such as "Virtual World Kyubi - Shenshen" and "Psychic End Punisher").

deck_excerpt: Best Cyberdragon Deck Layout so far - Diamond 4 in Master Duel.
deck_description: Best Cyberdragon Deck Layout so far - Diamond 4 in Master Duel.

Check the older Deck profile for in-depth explanation on the Deck, in this follow-up list I will explain some of my thoughts on the new cards and the changes done to the Decklist.

Changes: 

  • Complete removal of the Mikanko and Impcantation engines in favor of the newer cards are more flex spots, the Deck is not as frail as it used to be and Voici la Carte (Today's Menu) replaces Impcantations while Poissoniere de Nouvelles and Concours de Cuisine (Confectionery Contest) outright replaces the Mikanko engine. 
  • Running Buerillabaisse de Nouvelles as a target for Voici la Carte (Today's Menu) and ways to get to your Fishgal.
  • Running 1 Field which I post Voice was already playing at 2, just now it feels better at 1, since you have more ways to getting to Balam.
  • More Ben10s
  • Playing Sakitama which can be searched by Ben10 to make Baronne de Fleur or Chaos Angel using Diviner

Thoughts on the new Support:

  • Poissoniere is CRAZY, can be summoned off Diviner of the Herald being tributed, good normal summon and comes with an E-teli. Pre-Prep on legs or cheats out a ritual. Making her a pendulum is genial since now you have a way to target your Nouvs every turn for their effects which is great and helps you deal with people putting cards in the defense I suppose.
  • Contest ties in with an unexpected card, Patissciel Couverture, putting her in the opponent's field and then summoning your Poiss, meaning you get free tributes and allows you to go crazy with your effects turn 1. The GY effect also targets which is great!

deck_name: Vanquish Soul post Age of Overlord
deck_excerpt: THE WHEEL OF FATE IS TURNING! Rebel 1 ACTION!
deck_description:
Check the older Deck profile for in-depth explanation on the Deck, in this follow-up list I will explain some of my thoughts on the new cards and the changes done to the Decklist.

Changes:

  • Added the Kashtira Fenrir and Kashtira Riseheart package into the Deck for exta Earth and Fire names, one of the best innovations coming from the TCG for this Deck! Fenrir helps mitigate the lack of Earths since your first search with Razen will be either Borger or Madlove.
  • Playing Kumongous, the Sticky String Kaiju on main, interchangeable with Dogoran, the Mad Flame Kaiju if you want more Fires or Radian, the Multidimensional Kaiju for Darks. Retaliating "C", Dinowrestler Pankratops, Kurikara Divincarnate, Dimension Shifter and Bystial Magnamhut with 1 Bystial Druiswurm also work great for the Deck! ( Maxx "C" if you play OCG )

Thoughts on the new support:

  • Vanquish Soul Jiaolong is GREAT! But i'd still run 1-2 of him Max, I am not too keen on removing Vanquish Soul - Pluton HG cause its another Fire for Jiao and allows for Turn 0 plays... Jiao and Razen is full Combo (will explain later), being able to search any VS card makes it incredible + its effect to summon itself, meaning you can use your Razen, reveal Jiao and then Jiao will summon himself.
  • Vanquish Soul Snow Devil is what you will search if you don't open Dust Devil, so DDevil > SDevil > Cont. It pushes for time/winning via burn, but special summoning a VS, giving them effect protection and nuking the field is crazy, its a better disruption than Trinity Burst. 

Combo: 

Vanquish Soul Razen + Vanquish Soul Jiaolong 

Razen NS > Add Pluton HG > Reveal Fire in hand > Jiaolong special summons itself > Link Razen into Rock of the Vanquisher which will add to your hand Razen > Jiaolong reveal 2 fires > Add Snow Devil or Dust Devil. Next turn this gives you full set-up Rock will summon Razen which will search Vanquish Soul Caesar Valius which will make the trap live, trap summons Madlove which adds Continue/Dust Devil and then you can bounce her with Valius.

deck_excerpt: Branded is even stronger than ever before... And now on top of it's new support it has the ridiculously unfair Expulsion Lock!
deck_description:
Want to see the deck in action? Scroll to the very bottom for the Youtube video!

Branded is even stronger than ever before... And now on top of it's new support it has the ridiculously unfair Expulsion Lock! Grab free wins on ladder with this abusive strategy!

The "Expulsion Lock" summons Gimmick Puppet Nightmare to your opponent's side of the field so they can only special summon that archetype for the rest of the turn!

Here is a short step-by-step guide on the combo:

1. Summon Aluber to search for Branded Fusion.

2. Activate Branded Fusion to summon Lubellion by sending Albaz + Gimmick Puppet Nightmare to the GY.

3. Lubellion fusion summons Mirrorjade by shuffling Albaz + Lubellion back into the deck.

4. Activate Mirrorjade's effect to banish Aluber by sending Albion to the GY.

5. During the endphase, activate Albion's effect to set Branded Expulsion from deck.

6. During your opponent's turn (preferably the draw phase) activate Branded Expulsion tributing Mirrorjade. Summon from banished pile Aluber to your field. Summon from GY Gimmick Puppet Nightmare to your opponent's field.

7. On summon, Aluber searches for your Branded card of choice. Gimmick Puppet Nightmare then activates to lock your opponent out of special summoning except for Gimmick Puppets.

This particularly nasty combo basically ends your opponent's turn. All they can pretty much do is set backrow and normal summon a monster. Next turn, you should have more than enough follow-up to finish off your opponent!

This build has been granting me quick, straightforward and easy freewins on Masterduel ladder. Hope you have as much success as I do!

GLHF Duelists!

Fun Ancient Gear deck, simple play; fusion summon big gears, special gears, inflict big damage and win.

A combination of Vaylantz and Solfachord. Vaylantz provide the materials, Solfachord provides the high scale and one of the boss monsters, GranSolfachord Coolia.

Pros:

- Vaylantz and Solfachord cards are both super cheap.

- Vaylantz field spells can turn off cards like Infinite Impermanence, Evenly Matched, Lightning Storm, etc. In fact, opening a field spell isn't that bad, because you can immediately turn off Infinite Impermanence. (try to put Koing Wissen on your field, in case you have to pop it, the opponent is still left with Shinra Bansho on their field).

- ReSolfachord Dreamia acts as the high scale and allows GranSolfachord Coolia's negate to be live. Dreamia can be searched by Cutia, be set in scale by Elegance (plays around Ash/Veiler, etc), and searched by Beyond the Pendulum (BTP). Ideally, you would have Dreamia before making BTP, so you can search for another Vaylantz monster with BTP.

- Coolia provides a much needed spell/trap negate (it can negate any card or effect), but it also provides negation protection to your pendulum monsters it points to. It would be best to save Shinonome's effects until she can be protected by Coolia.

- This deck can pend summon basically whenever it wants, in fact with the right hand it is beneficial to pend summon early to get Coolia out ASAP and then use it to protect your Vaylantz monsters from being negated by ash, gamma, etc.

- Can probably play Time-Tearing Morganite, if you're into that.

- Pretty easy to make another BTP if the first one can't resolve (ash, veiler, etc). The restriction only applies if it resolves, and only the second effect is a HOPT.

Cons:

- Dies to Anti-Spell Fragrance.

- Dies to any spell speed 2 or higher spell/trap removal. Using MST, Cosmic Cyclone, Twin Twisters, Solemn Judgement, etc on the field spells, scales, etc. are super effective.

- Vaylantz can be a little complicated already, but having to leave ReSolfachord Dreamia in the scale so Coolia's negate can be used makes things more complicated (you lose a scale to summon your Vaylantz).

- Cutia cannot be pend summoned (because the deck plays no 0 scales), can only be normal summoned.

- Leaving Koning Wissen on the field can be annoying. A tip, however, is that it requires the person using it to have a monster in the same column as the monster they are targeting. So, if you have Arktos XII and weren't able to destroy Konig Wissen in time, you can destroy the opponent's monster before they can activate Konig Wissen (or just destroy Koing Wissen).

Notes:

- It is possible to get Coolia's negate live in time for Nibiru, but it can't be used the second you Vaylantz lock yourself. Only useful if your opponent shotguns Nibiru, or they don't understand the interactions between Vaylantz and Solfachord.

- Genesis Grand Duke is there for situations in which you need an extra material to make Arktos XII (use Voltage Viscount and Shinra Bansho).

deck_excerpt: A Traptrix deck made to combat meta
deck_description:
Focused around traps and going first, I wanted to make a mostly pure Traptrix deck. I've played this for over two years in meta now, so it's refined to the best of my ability.

Well it's focused around heading first, I have different ways to combat and win certain circumstances! Feel free to comment and add suggestions.

Tactics:

You're ideal hand will have "Mantis", "Parallel eXceed", "Heavenly Prison's, and three hole cards.

Sera needs to be out first turn, along with some defense using hole cards. If you get "Rafflesia" out with Sera you're golden.

"Sera" let's you flood both the field with both hole and Traptrix monsters, well "Rafflesia" makes sure your Traptrix monsters are not destroyed by battle, card effects, or directly attacked.

"Heavenly Prison" makes set cards not be destroy my card effects, perfect to counter brack row breaking spells and traps such as "Lightning Storm". He also acts as good 3000 beatstick. To get him in your hand easier, special summon "Gallant Granite" with 2 level 4 monsters. As all Traptrix monsters are level 4 and Sera floods the field with them, this is easy.

Summoning "Sera" with "Parallel eXceed" allows "Rafflesia" to be summoned first turn, as she only needs 2 level 4 monsters.

For this reason, "The Phantom Knights of Shade Brigandine" also counts as a level four monster. If you get this, summon "Sera" before using "Brigandine", as activating it's effect will also get you a free Traptrix monster summon.

As Traptrix isn't very good at high damage, "Dogmatika Ecclesia" can summon "Dogmatika Fleurdelis" to add some extra power. That, and "Fleurdelis" nullify a monsters effect as if "Ecclesia" is on the field when summoned. "Fleurdelis" can be summoned on either turns Main Phase from your hand if either player special summons from the extra deck.

If all else fails, you can use "Dionaea" to summon a Traptrix Monster from your graveyard, giving you option. You can link into a "Knightmare" monster, or summon "Allomerus". "Number 80" is there to buff "Allomerus" if she needs it, but her purpose is to bring out "ZEUS". Most games you won't be summoning her if you don't neex "ZEUS"

deck_excerpt: Yea... this deck is still good
deck_description:
Man I love this deck. Even through 8 limits and a ban, this deck in my opinion is still an incredibly powerful option and can stand up to the best of the best. 

Some quick explainations:

This deck wants to mill a lot. For consistency I wanted to balance the deck between cards that are good to draw, and cards that are good to mill. E.g. the tear names are very good to mill, and OK to draw. Danger Nessie is quite good to draw or mill. Diviner is incredible to draw, but not great to mill. This deck tries to find the balance in that and use as many GY effects as possible to go nuts on your first turn. Jet synchron and destrudo are very useful to make Baronne and Dragite. As long as you mill enough cards you should usually put up an insane board that is very hard to push through.

I personally love this archetype, not only because the card art is majestic, but also because it's pretty fun to play. This deck isn't intended to be used competitively since it could definitely use some polishing. I am posting this because I personally believe that this deck is the perfect deck for begginers. It is a really simple deck to learn how to play and, if you remove triple tactics and make small ajustments in the extra deck since not all the monsters are needed, this is a perfect budget deck to pick up the game for the first time. Have fun with this and feel free to suggest modifications

Cards that can be removed to make this deck cheaper:

Garden Rose Maiden (although I recommned just getting a PSA 7 or something since they come really cheap)

Triple Tactics Talent (completely unnecessary, I just included it for new players to get used to chains but can be removed obviously

Queen of Thorns (just not really needed for the deck to work)

 

 

NOTE: please keep in mind that I designed this deck as a budget deck and a beginner friendly deck INTENTIONALLY, so some obvious cards that would make this deck way better have been removed. Thanks for reading
