deck_excerpt: The new Horus cards are an unbelievable insane Rank 8 package
deck_description:
I made a deck focused around summoning Galaxy-Eyes Cipher Dragon to work with the new Cipher support at the time such as Galaxy-Eyes Cipher X Dragon, Double Exposure, and Cipher Biplane. (Link to Deck) However, the biggest issue the Deck had at the time was actually consistently drawing enough Cipher names in order to make your Rank 8 Cipher Dragons. Pot of Prosperity, while it would fix most of that issue, would cut your damage in half for the turn which is not what you want for a going-second deck. The new Horus cards, with each of them being an inherent summon from GY if you control Pharaonic Sarcophagus, are an incredible Rank 8 engine with their cards being able to easily send all 4 names to GY for enough material for 2 Rank 8 monsters without using your Normal Summon. This deck aims at going second in order to make Galaxy-Eyes Cipher Dragon and its compatriots to steal your opponent's monsters and overlay them into Cipher X Dragons to hopefully deal near-lethal damage to your opponent or prevent them from retaining resources on field and/or in GY. 

For our monster handtraps, we have 2 Nibiru, the Primal Being, 3 Ash Blossom & Joyous Spring, and 3 Ghost Ogre & Snow Rabbit. For our Horus monsters, we have 3 Imsety, Glory of Horus, and 1 each of the rest: 1 Hapy, Vanguard of Horus, 1 Qebehsenuef, Aegis of Horus, and 1 Duamutef, Blessing of Horus. Functionally, we are only using them for a Rank 8 package, so their individual effects are irrelevant for the most part other than Imsety who can send itself and a card from hand to search Pharaonic Sarcophagus to get everything started. You will brick on Horus monsters if you play more than 1 of the other names. For Ciphers, we are playing 3 Cipher Biplane, 3 Cipher Twin Raptor, 1 Cipher Mirror Knight, and 3 Cipher Etranger. Biplane summons itself if another Cipher is Summoned and it can make 2 Ciphers become Level 8. Raptor is a free summon if your opponent controls a monster summoned from the Extra Deck, and it can discard 1 to summon a Cipher, preferrably Biplane, from Deck. Mirror Knight is just here as discard fodder since it searches a Cipher card during the End Phase of the turn it was sent to the GY. The same goes for Etranger, but it immediately searches a Cipher Spell/Trap when sent to the GY and it can attach itself from hand or GY to a Cipher Xyz Monster. 

For Spell/Traps, we have 3 Pharaonic Sarcophagus which allows you to send a card from hand to send a Horus monster from Deck to GY up to 4 times per turn. Just sending all of the names in a turn gives you a repeatable, recurring Rank 8 package as long as Sarcophagus remains on field. 2 Triple Tactics Thrust and 1 Triple Tactics Talent. 3 Forbidden Droplet. 1 Rank-Up-Magic Cipher Ascension which is a fun little thing you can do. This ranks up Galaxy-Eyes Cipher Dragon into Neo Galaxy-Eyes Cipher Dragon to steal up to 3 monsters instead of 1. 3 Forbidden Chalice and 3 Infinite Impermanence because we are going all into this going second thing. 

For the Extra Deck: 1 Divine Arsenal AA-ZEUS - Sky Thunder, 3 Galaxy-Eyes Cipher X Dragon because it recycles and/or summons back your Dragon Xyz Monsters and you can overlay into it using a monster you stole off of a Cipher Dragon because they are treated as Galaxy-Eyes Cipher Dragon when you do. 1 Galaxy-Eyes Cipher Blade Dragon which is targeted destruction. 1 Galaxy-Eyes Full armor Photon Dragon which is also targeted destruction. 3 Galaxy-Eyes Cipher Dragon as it is your main Rank 8 monster you are going into. 1 Number 90: Galaxy-Eyes Photon Lord as a monster negate to go into going first. 1 Hieratic Sun Dragon Overlord of Heliopolis which tributes monsters from hand and/or field to destroy cards. If you have an insufficient number of Ciphers in hand, but have all of the Horus monsters in GY already, your hand is just fodder for Heliopolis to destroy cards. 1 Number 38: Hope Harbinger Dragon Titanic Galaxy which is a Spell Negate going first. 1 Dingirsu, the Orcust of the Evening Star for removal and protection. 1 Divine Dragon Knight Felgrand for protection and/or a negate. 

Side Deck isn't much. Some Levle 8 Kaijus, 1 Kurikara Divincarnate, 2 Lightning Storm, 1 Harpie's Feather Duster, 3 Forbidden Lance for going first or second for extra protection against Spell/Trap-based removal, the second Triple Tactics Talent, and 3 Solemn Strike for going first.

deck_excerpt: The Melffy of the Forest are going to beat you to Death.
deck_description: The Melffy of the Forest are going to beat you to Death.

The general idea of the deck is to get Lava Golem up and then crash into it with Swordswoman, perferably with equip items that nerf her and buff the Golem, though this can hypothetically be done with any high-ATK monster. With the massive amount of damage + Golem's auto-1000, a optimal field can be extremely dangerous. 

Freed/Tomato/Spy act as your monster searchers, allowing you to get though the deck faster as well as stalling Golem if needed. Freed is also suprisingly quite good standalone given his spell immunity and draw effect, making him a issue that typically involves a waste of removal from the opponent. You don't really need to be too worried about general offence given Golem is universal field removal, though the side does consider that as I'll explain.

Kotetsu lets you get into your equips faster; Snatch Steal and Burial included alongside some beefy equips. 3x Trunade removes the issue of pesky traps alongside freeing the field if equips clog things up. 

Traps are mostly general defence with a couple of extra burn stables thrown in in case of needing that little bit extra damage required if needed. 

Game 2 changes things up by going into Panda Burn: almost always throws the opponent for a loop given the general long-game nature of the Golem strat, but it's a perfect fit for here so it doesn't harm the deck much. Wok helps for burn mirror and Kycoo/Big Bang/Nobleman help for Chaos variations.

deck_excerpt: Dark Magician Dinomorphia Psychic End Punisher
deck_description: This is my Dinomorphia DM Deck.

There's a couple of Ancient Gear builds already that are great, but I figured this version is pretty good as well.

Beast is unironically one of the most underrated cards around. Complete shutdown of backrow if it attacks, negates anything that is destroyed: not just flip effects, but anything that pops in the graveyard, so recruiters also get the boot as well. Combined with Cost Down making it a level 4, it is easily splashable and shuts down a lot of conventional plays. Your opponent has to either waste non-battle removal on it or try to play over with monsters. Golem is impossible to get out normally but with Cost it becomes a single tribute, which is amazing given how much damage it can do with just a single reliable attack on a unsuspecting token or facedown play. Jinzo is a solid play as well. 

To aid with this I threw in the regular Monarch Soul Control engine just in case Cost isn't available + removal alongside some basic Earth recruiters that can either be removal-bait, used for field control or just there to hold the fort. Gigantes is a great combo given it's essentially a free summon so it can be used to swarm the field for big damage or splashed into a tribute. Sangan/Serpent are there for easy discard/consistency fodder alongside Exiled/Lady alongside Reinforcement for more Gigantes fodder + removal if required.

Book of Moon is there just mostly for tech purposes and we have 1 Limiter to beef up any Golem + Jinzo for a big charge. 

Because of the need to protect monsters I didn't really bother with traps bar three Decree to shutdown backrow disruption. 

Side deck is pretty generalised. Threw in a standard Chaos build just to have more stuff for Cost to burn though, Wombat + Wok for burn, Trunade for safe charges against more proactive fields and Stein in case of needing big monsters on the fly. Meta combos well with your Golems if you want more flexiablity and Forbidden is mostly to counter ReasoningGate plays if required given their speed can be a issue for the deck (alongside Golems not being able to be special summoned).

Goblin Attack Force is a pretty recent (ish) tech in some beatdown decks here and there across the years. No one has really gone overboard and went into the terrible concept of a proper Goblin deck, but it actually turned out pretty decent. The Deck generally tries to control the field with big ATK values and useful backrow. 

Goblin/Toon Goblin Attack Force are the core of the deck. Huge stats, basically are a wall to get past. The great thing about Goblins is that they have amazing consistency and search power, with both reinforcement and Toon Table being able to get them out. If you just run with a single 3x Table into Goblin, that's already a 36 card deck essentially. Gorilla is a solid beatdown alternative alongside stables like Gigantes and Exiled. Panda is obviously great, no need to detail further.

Usual basic spell set, including Trunade and Nobleman to establish control quickly. If you play a Goblin turn 1 the opponent generally always goes for a facedown play, so this is a easy set-up. 

Traps focus around the main weakness of the deck: Goblins not being able to attack more than once without a cooldown. Skill Drain removes that issue and cripples the opponent alongside Final Attack, turning any monster play by the opponent into a dangerous investment and outright nearly destroying Scapegoat plays by itself. Deck generally doesn't have many issues with Goat Control given what's on board here. Solemn + Comp are useful for getting rid of problematic cards, Ring is especially useful with such beefy targets to boot.

Side is...mostly just the basic plays against Warrior/Chaos/Burn. Trio + Final Attack or Panda can be a useful alternative way to stack up damage. Kaiser is fairly underrated and keeps more swarm-heavy builds under check immediately, can bait out removals because of how annoying it can be.

deck_excerpt: 10 Winstreak into Master Rank 2, 5 Win Streak into Master Rank 1
deck_description: My complete guide to sprights - https://youtu.be/XeqlXBeF9GA

I randomly made this terrible concept up one night while drunk don't judge me lol

The main issue with Exodia in Goat Format is that it is 

A. Too slow to work properly (unless you build your entire deck around a OTK that falls apart if you go second)

B. Loses to any aggressive build that attacks the hand 

ExodiaGate fixes those two by....completely confusing the fuck out of the opposite player with a ReasoningGate build. Because of the meta of this, your opponent will almost always call a high number to counter the impending Crane/Dark Magician/beefy monster, but instead you are likely to draw a Exodia piece instead. The point of the deck is that this is great, because that means a free tribute or being able to snatch it up when it is in the grave with your numerous recovery tools.

Jinzo and Horus are also used to confuse the opponent further when they either call low or a higher number, not to mention Horus LV8 is a amazing boss monster that shuts down half of the important cards in the set. Emissary is here to draw out the pieces individually if required. 

Dark Factory + Backup and Reincarnation give you your pieces back alongside the usual set you'd see from a deck like this.

Traps are either for stalling or removal. Three Solemn counters any attempt to stop you getting the pieces and/or making important plays. 

Side Deck is VERY important here because once your opponent understands the mindgame they will be inevitably trying to stop you with hand removal + ReasoningGate tech. This is also great, because we will be instead be playing Chaos Control, blindsiding them again with a classic smokescreen. I also threw in some typical counters to builds alongside Magician and Crane if you want to play more conventionally. If done properly, this deck does, occasionally, win some matches.

deck_description: hehe doodoodoo
Suship
Just have fun!

This is a pretty simple build: it's all focused around normal monsters with high statlines running over everything. Backrow helps with controlling the field and keeping threats in check.

Heart is insanely good for consistency; it makes you able to draw into all of your plays so much quicker, especially with two. Alongside Trinity and the rest of the stables we have 3x Kaiser. I debate having 2 instead, but Kaiser is just so good that it's not even funny. As soon as this is on the field Scapegoat is useless, any deck that spams monsters is useless, Chaos is shut down for the most part, etc. It's so oppressive and it forces your opponent to either waste removal or try to play around it with big monsters, both playing to the style this deck works at. 

Order to Charge doesn't seem great, but having a Quick Play instant monster removal is amazing, actually. If you run into a battle trap you can chain this and destroy something anyway, wasting the trap in the process, anything that targets like soul exchange or brain control for Monarchs is also countered as long as you have a opposing monster to handle. You always have a way to get rid of stuff or make sure it can't go off proper, especially alongside three Solemn and three Saku. Your opponent will be playing Nobleman and that's a instant waste given this deck should never be setting anything apart from backrow. 

Sides are mostly either Chaos counters or more removal options. I included Non-Spellcasting as it's actually pretty nutty for support, giving you full-on immunity to all spell cards: not targeting, not destroying, full on immunity. This makes Soul Control Monarchs automatically just suck ass as all of their stealing tech is disabled, Moon is disabled, Snatch is disabled, hell any attempt to use spells on your monsters will simply not work. 

Obviously this isn't meta in the slightest, but you'd be surprised how much trouble this deck can give to some of the better stuff out there.
P.U.N.K.

Tear is strong, but the Ishizu cards are boring and everyone runs them. I say who cares about those. I love Orcust so I wanted to shove these 2 decks I like into this, (admittedly not as strong as Ishizu Tear), deck. I have tons of fun with this deck, and vastly prefer is over any other Tear variant. 

This deck is capable of consistently ending on Galatea with Crescendo Set, Redoer, and Rulkallos. Being able to pitch any Orcust card in hand with Scheiren allows you to be able to set up your grave for Orcust plays, as well as unbrick your hand for when World Wand decides to show up. I run Armageddon Knight in this deck over the 2nd copy of Girsu as he is capable of starting both Tear plays and Orcust plays depending on what you already have on board/in grave. With Poly you are capable of fusing any Tear name with any Orcust name to create Mudragon, triggering the Tear cards effects as well as gaining targetting protection/going straight into Dragostapelia

.Abyss Dweller is a card that honestly rarely comes up. It is sort of hard to get 2 level 4's on field before dark locking yourself with the Orcust effects, so you may cut it if you want. Due to Babel's effect of constaly recycling itself, milling it is not an issue, as well as replacing it on field for Planet. I;P also may be changed out for Dharc, I simply like being able to go into Unicorn on my opponents turn.

Bystials/Evenly Matched/Imperm ratios can all be changed around depending on preference.

deck_excerpt: use these powerful level 3 monsters to summon themselves and synchro into even more powerul cards!
deck_description: mmm mimimick

I recall someone I played once using something similar to this and it was so cool that I wanted to replicate it as best as possible despite seeing 10 cards of it pretty much.

Anyway, Creation Control is all about spamming the field with monsters and then using your monster advantage to harrass your opponent, namely with Horn of Heaven which is a free Solemn for monsters only...but still feels really busted given that fact. Agent of Creation can spam out her Shine Balls that can either be used for cost, then Chaos fodder, or used for a tribute and then as Chaos fodder. Airnight and Jinzo are here to control the field respectfully with the conventional recruiters alongside Faith and Serpent to regain advantage over and over.

Brain Jacker is....kinda funky. I was thinking better of it but given this deck is all about advantage via monsters, a cheaper snatch steal does the gimmick good. 

Stray Lambs! These generally aren't used because of their limitations, but for this deck it's fantastic. We can use these for tributes or for Horn of Heaven, even just to sit on to work on other things while the opponent works around our field presence. Conventional traps plus some battle protection, simple. 

Side deck can be used to move to Monarchs if you don't feel comfortable with the bigger monsters used alongside faster Chaos plays, some additional tribute tech or simply controlling the backrow/hand more.

Super Heavy Samurai is easy to climb into using tri-edge or charge warrior, it allows you to have a follow up something this deck lacks horribly at the moment. 

Malong can increase its level using it and a level four can out psychic end punisher
Concept for Tears, Side is just other cards you can put in

This deck is best done on the first turn, and usually allows you to set up Crystal Clear Wing and Crystal Wing Synchro Dragon on turn 1, depending on the starter hand. Though even if you go second, this deck has good recovery options.

Crystal Clear Wing Synchro Dragon is the must-have card. The effect of raising the attack above the 3000 threshold AND making it unaffected by monster effects after that is a god-send, not to mention the once-per-turn spell/trap negate and on-death searching effect. Better still, you can pull this off easily with Red-Eyed Dice and a non-tuner Speedroid monster. Other Synchros, such as Baronne, are alternatives when CCW isn't an option.

This deck can definitely be tweaked for better performance (and no I don't mean adding handtraps like Ash Blossom and Maxx "C"), and while I'm not sure if it's exactly a meta-deck, it can definitely go toe-to-toe with archetypes like Tearlaments and Swordsoul.

deck_name: Superheavy Samurai Adamancipator post 2023 June Banlist
deck_excerpt: adamancipator superheavy samurai 2023 june post banlist
deck_description: Here is my new version of SHS Adamancipator with as little bricks as possible and an impressive consistency. I think we should minimize bricks as long as we don't get another Tuner or Block Dragon back, so that's why the main goal is to focus on having Raptite thanks to SHS without normal summoning and with scales set up.
For fun

This is a mostly exact copy of Luke Boncic's version of Darkstrike, which I wanted to showcase here for archive purposes. As you can see, the gameplan is pretty simple: lots of stat-heavy monsters, dump them away with removal then rush in with Strike Ninja for big aggressive plays. 

Despite me being worried that this would brick given the amount of "can't be Normal Summoned" cards here it suprisingly has been pretty robust in playtesting, only having the occasional slightly bad draw. Trunade and other powerful backrow options keep the backrow in check to protect yourself while aiding that eventual OTK strat down the line. The deck isn't really built to grind, it's built to just last long enough to make a competent charge.

Side-deck is mostly counters to warriors alongside Cold Wave and Fragrance to stop spell-heavy/similarly aggressive decks. Return is useful as a less impressive Fusion but can definitely aid in a clinch, especially given it unlike Fusion banishes everything back again so you don't have to worry about rebuilding your field. 

The Magician cards are there to run though the deck alongside a potential 500+ boost to all DARK monsters, which in the long run can actually be a substantual play given the strength of your big Ninja plays.

deck_excerpt: Heroic Challenger, Heroic Champion, Warrior, XYZ, Going Second, OTK
deck_description:
HEROIC CHALLENGER DECK

This Deck uses the Heroic archetype as the main engine, one of my favourites ever from the Yu-Gi-Oh! Zexal anime. It's a pretty cheap Deck to buy (if you don't consider some of the staples) and it's pretty simple and straightforward to learn. It's suitable for new players as it also teaches you the basics of going second: You break the board and eliminate the dangerous threats on the field? You win! You don't? You lose.

 

MVP of the Deck

 

 

STRATEGY

The Deck's strategy, as I already said, is pretty straightforward: You want to go second and OTK (One Turn Kill) your opponent with Heroic Champion - Claivesolish and Heroic Chance while eliminating the threats that prevent you to do so, using Kaijus and other going second staples. I don't run cards like Dark Ruler No More and Evenly Matched because you have to give up the OTK opportunity to use them. If you still want to play them you're free to do so, as it can be an actual win condition to draw either of them against certain Decks. The Deck is also provided with some "plan B"s to use when you think you can't OTK, when you have to go first or in some matchups.

 

 

MAIN DECK TECHS

- Nibiru, the Primal Being : At two copies in the main Deck because it can be a brick, but I added another copy of it in the side Deck. It's a free win if your opponent reaches at least 5 summons and they can't recover after you use it. I reccomend you to place it in attack position, as Heroic Champion - Claivesolish can still attack over it and OTK the opponent if you have Heroic Chance .

- Gameciel, the Sea Turtle Kaiju : A generic monster removal that bypasses almost all immunities. The Heroic archetype makes most use of this card as, like Nibiru, it's also an OTK enabler because you can attack over it.

- Dinowrestler Pankratops : Because why not? A Quick Effect removal that bypasses on-field targeting and can destroy any card on their field. There's a reason why this card is limited to 1 copy, you know?

- War Rock Gactos : It's a free warrior-type body that specials summon from the hand whenever you normal summon any level 4 Heroic Challenger monster. It's a way better option than Blue Mountain Butterspy and Kagetokage because he can be also normal summoned by himself and it's better than Goblindbergh because Gactos' effect triggers in the hand: if it gets negated at least you normal summoned a Heroic monster, while if you use Goblindbergh you have to burn your normal summon and it can be negated with cards like Infinite Impermanence .

- ZS - Ascended Sage : Another free warrior-type body that special summons himself and can also be normal summoned from the hand. It can be an anti-synergy if you have both him and Heroic Challenger - Assault Halberd in your hand because they both have to be special summoned as the first monsters on your field. Note that Assault Halberd can also be used as a discard fodder for Heroic Challenger - Thousand Blades . It's better than Photon Thrasher , but the latter can still be played to attack over a funny Inspector Boarder .

- Lightning Storm : Self-explicative. Also can be used as backrow removal. Note that you can't use Heroic Chance if you want to attack directly.

- Harpie's Feather Duster : Compensates the lack of backrow removal in the staples. It could have been another copy of Lightning Storm instead but Konami limited it to two.

- Forbidden Droplet : It bypasses targeting and the opponent's monsters can't respond to it if you sent at least one monster to the graveyard, which you'll probably do because the Deck is mostly composed of monsters. You can revive any level 4 warrior monster you send to the GY with this effect with Heroic Champion - Jarngreipr and Heroic Call .

 

 

EXTRA DECK TECHS

- Number 41: Bagooska the Terribly Tired Tapir : This Deck doesn't really have a consistent going first, so Bagooska is a good choice if you're bricky or you think your opponent doesn't have the out.

- ZS - Utopic Sage : You can combo quite nicely, summon ZS - Ascended Sage from the Deck, make another XYZ monster then into Number F0: Utopic Draco Future . 

- Gagagaga Magician : For the same reason of Utopic Sage but if you already have a non-number XYZ monster in your graveyard.

- Castel, the Skyblaster Musketeer : I usually summon it after Utopic Sage, use its effect and then make F0.

- Knightmare Cerberus : It's a good out to Bagooska if your opponent summons it.

- Tornado Dragon : It's just versatile to have a Mystical Space Typhoon always available in your Extra Deck. You could also go for Knightmare Phoenix .

 

 

SIDE DECK TECHS

- Droll & Lock Bird : It's overall a good card in the current meta, you can main Deck it instead of Ash Blossom & Joyous Spring if you want. It's most effective in some matchups.

- Abyss Dweller : Good card against Tearlaments or other Decks that play a lot with GY effects.

- Knightmare Unicorn : If you want to continue the Link combo after Knightmare Cerberus or Phoenix. You could also play Accesscode Talker or any other Link-4 as a combo closer.

- Twin Twisters : If you're against a backrow heavy Deck. You could also play Cosmic Cyclone for a banish, but note that you can't use it if you cut your LP to 500 due to Claivesolish's effect. But I guess you'll use Cosmic Cyclone before even attemtping to OTK so actually either is good.

- Solemn Judgment : Increases power in your going first. The LP cost doesn't weight as much since it'll always be half your current ones, so it's good synergy with Claivesolish.

- Royal Decree : Ever met "That Guy" at locals that sets 5 cards and passes? Obviously you want to go first instead of them. The main Deck also doesn't play any Trap cards so it's completely splashable.

 

 

OTHER NOTES

- Heroic Challenger - Clasp Sword doesn't really fit the Deck. As for now, this build of the Heroic Challenger Deck is focused on raw card advantage and if you have one copy of it you'll either draw into it and bricking, or banishing it with Pot of Desires . It's not an essential part of the combo either, but it could be useful in other builds.

- Isolde, Two Tales of the Noble Knights is a generally good card but it doesn't fit this build either.

- You could also splash in the Number 39: Utopia Double OTK engine, but note that Double or Nothing! is a brick if you get it in the hand. On the other hand, you could also go for Ultimate Leo Utopia Ray and equip ZW - Pegasus Twin Saber to get access to two negates for one XYZ, but it doubles the amount of bricks.

deck_excerpt: Nitro Unit looks like a original Xbox ngl
deck_description:
This deck started off as a goofy attempt to make a "bomb" themed casual Goat deck, but I actually think it worked out pretty well for that dumb purpose. 

The deck runs around Nitro Unit, a equip card that is essentially a opponent-only Ring of Destruction if you can ping it off via battle. We work machines for this purpose, namely aggressive stat-heavy ones that can be brought out relatively easy, but is also assisted with some monster stealing. Moon techs with Fusilier to get it to full stats, Fate/Kote help with consistency and regaining useful cards. Stein is here for quick and easy access to big monsters and Roulette Barrel can basically be sat on if required. 

Burrower combos with Nitro to add even more damage to the mix with its underrated level-based burn effect. Combined with 3x Limiter alongside possible equips and clearing the field, this can potentially stack damage up massively. 

Traps are also explosive-themed with Widespread Ruin and Ring being able to handle huge threats by themselves. Pineapple is certainly....weird for tech, but it worked here given it hard-counters a Scapegoat field or any monster-heavy lineup with only a single summon. 

I was prepared to work the side deck as usual until I noticed that nearly all of the big plays here are Dark monsters, so...I just side-decked a mini-Ninja Return package to capitalise on that alongside some general cost-cards to work towards that specific goal. It's a pretty effective smokescreen that typically allows you to slip in faster plays on a opponent expecting your usual stuff.
Just a cool hero deck integrated with dark Armed dragon for armed Neos !

Blue-Eyes may be just a nostalgia bait archetype, but it can be fairly splashable, and it doesn't deter Branded from its usual playstyle, aside from sometimes using the Normal Summon on Stone.

Drawing Shrine allows you to send the Normal Blue-Eyes, as well as a Dragon of your choice. If you need Albaz in Grave, you can do that, or send Jet or Stone for more material.

Exosisters is a powerful Anti-Meta deck that performs well in most metas. With the wide variety of decks topping the big events, a deck that can run Dimension Shifter along with a plethora of staple handtraps and board breakers can go a long way.

deck_excerpt: An Apple a Day Keeps the Meta at Bay
deck_description:
This deck is a lot of fun. Fairly consistent thanks to Prosperity and the Triple Tactics cards, and easy access to the Normal Blue-Eyes courtesy of Dictator and Vision, which makes Apple Dragon live. Ringowurm is a crazy card, which allows all sorts of Synchro shenanigans. In this deck specifically, it lets you make a bunch of powerful Level 10 Synchro Monsters.

Ringowurm can Special Summon itself from your hand if you control a non-Effect monster, like the original Blue-Eyes, which you can use to go into a Level 10 Synchro, if you started this combo with "Dictator of D.", I would recommend going into "Bystial Dis Pater", then use the GY effect of "Ringowurm, the Dragon Guarding the Hundred Apples" to Special Summon a Token, which can be treated as a Tuner. Then use the Token and Dictator to go into Stardust Charge Warrior" to draw a card, and use the effect of Dis Pater to Special Summon a banished Light or Dark monster, in this case Ringowurm, then use Ringowurm and Charge Warrior to go into "Accel Synchro Stardust Dragon", and use its effect to Special Summon Ringowurm from the GY, and go into another Level 10 Synchro.

deck_excerpt: I'm Gonna Banish a Light and a Dark
deck_description:
The Bystials are series of Dragon monsters that have excellent hand effects. Lubellion searches another Bystial, and the Level 6 Bystials can banish a LIGHT or DARK monster in either player's GY at Spell Speed 1, however, if your opponent controls a monster, it becomes Spell Speed 2 (Quick Effect). These supercharged D.D. Crows are extremely powerful hand traps, as well as formidable bodies on board.

Funny thing is, when you mix a Level 6 DARK Bystial with a Level 4 LIGHT Dogmatika Ecclesia, you get a full power Chaos Angel. One of the most powerful cards recently released, this Synchro Monster doesn't need a Tuner, and can instead treat a Light or Dark monster as one. This monster gains very stong effects based on the Attributes of monsters used as Synchro Material, Light monsters allow your Synchro Monsters to be unaffected by your opponent's activated monster effects, and Dark monsters make it so that all monsters you control are unable to be destroyed by battle.

With the powerful utility and disruption that the Dogmatika cards and Ultimate Slayer provide, and the crazy amount of interaction and power the Bystials bring to the table, this deck can be a force to be reckoned with.

The Charmers are a fan favourite archetype of cute girls (and a sad boy), that originated in early ygo as FLIP monsters that can take control of a monster your opponent control with their same original Attribute. Over time they have gotten more support that has made them usable, but not viable. The Charmers' Familiars recieved upgrades as well, becoming excellent extenders while you control a Spellcaster monster. One stellar piece they recieved was Eda the Sun Magician, which Special Summons a Spellcaster with 1500 DEF, such as a Charmer, from your Deck in face-down Defense Position. It can also flip up a face-down Spellcaster you control during your opponent's turn at Quick Effect speed.

Combine all this with the powerful Dogmatika Engine, which provides further extension, disruption, and utility, which makes this deck much more competitive, but nowhere near tiered status.

If you want to play the Shaddoll Engine, you can easily exchange a few cards out for it, and you'd probably want to add another Maximus too.

Come forth and enter the mysterious Dream Mirror. Which Twisted Realm will you see today? The Realm of Joy or the Realm of Terror? Today we take a closer look at a very fun and unique Archetype, Dream Mirror. Let's go into the Details: 

 

Joy and Terror Combined

The overall Goal of this Deck is to have both of your Field Spells Dream Mirror of Joy and Dream Mirror of Terror active. To achieve that you need to use the Trap Card Dream Mirror Hypnagogia which will place one Field Spell to your Side and the other to the opponents side, from your Hand or Deck. 

Like that most of your Dream Mirror Monsters can as a Quick effect during the Main or Battle Phase tribute themselves to Special summon their LIGHT or DARK Counterpart from the Deck. If you have Dream Mirror Recap active they will be shuffled into the Deck instead thus creating a perfect Ressource Loop. 

So the overall Goal is to find Dream Mirror Hypnagogia as fast as possible and soon after that get Dream Mirror Recap into play too. With quite a bit of setup your Deck is now able to unleash it's almighty Power!

 

Neiroy the Disciple enters the Dreamworld

Both Neiroy, the Dream Mirror Disciple and Neiroy, the Dream Mirror Traitor don't follow the usual rules Maindeck Dream Mirror Monsters have and they serve as your Main Starters. They both are L3 and have 1000/1000 Statlines.

Neiroy, the Dream Mirror Disciple can be Special Summoned from the Hand if you control a Dream Mirror Monster and can then Change his Attribute to DARK (More on that importance later). If he's Special Summoned through a Dream Mirror Monster effect he also triggers a Mandatory effect. If Dream Mirror of Joy is active you can return a Spell/Trap from the opponent to the Hand and if Dream Mirror of Terror is active you Draw 1 Card and then shuffle 1 Card from your Hand back into the Deck. The Bounce effect is sometimes interesting to get your own Field Spell back to your Hand if it's on the opponents side and the other effect is obviously nice to get a better Hand. 

Neiroy, the Dream Mirror Traitor is THE Starter of the Century and fixes the whole Archetype. If he's Normal or Special summoned he can search Neiroy, the Dream Mirror Disciple from the Deck to your Hand and then Change his Attribute to DARK. He can also Tribute a Dream Mirror Monster and Special Summon any other Dream Mirror Monster with a different level then the tributed Monster from the Deck in defense Position AND add the Field Spell which is mentioned on that Monster to your Hand. He's always very welcome to be in your opening Hand to get your Deck up to speed by summoning Ikelos, the Dream Mirror Sprite which searches for any other Dream Mirror Card on summon. If you fail to find him in your Starting Hand you can also use Dream Mirror Phantasms to search for him. Always think of Neiroy, the Dream Mirror Traitor when you want to get things started.

 

Ikelos, Phantasos and Morpheus twisted Shape

Now with our Starter Neiroy out of the way we can take a look at the other Dream Mirror friends in our Maindeck. All of them can tribute themselves as a Quick effect during the Main or Battle Phase and summon their LIGHT/DARK Counterpart from the Deck. The LIGHT Monsters need Dream Mirror of Terror and the DARK Monsters need Dream Mirror of Joy active to be able to use this effect. The LIGHT Monsters have higher DEF and the DARK Monsters have higher ATK. All of them trigger a optional effect if they are Special Summoned through an Dream Mirror Monster effect. 

Ikelos, the Dream Mirror Sprite: L1 with 0/500 Statline. Searches for any Dream Mirror Card you like except herself from your Deck. She's kinda good since you can search your whole Deck with her. It's always good to summon her as quick as possible and pair her with Dream Mirror Recap to keep the advantage Train running smoothly. You get to search during your turn and your opponents turn so you can imagine how quickly this will get out of Hand.

Ikelos, the Dream Mirror Mara: L1 with 500/0 Statline. She Special summons any Dream Mirror Monster from your Hand except herself. She's super useful to get your tribute Monster Morpheus out of your Hand or to trigger any Dream Mirror Monster effect. Since Ikelos, the Dream Mirror Sprite can search any Dream Mirror Card there's potential interruption possible with Morpheus, the Dream Mirror Black Knight.

Phantasos, the Dream Mirror Friend: L4 with 900/1900 Statline. Special summons a L8 or lower Dream Mirror Monster from your GY in defense position. This is nice to get a Morpheus back into play easily or trigger any other Dream Mirror Monster effect. It is very unfortunate that you can't revive your L10 Boss Oneiros with this card which decreases it's usefulness drastically but having a quick effect reborn ready = more interruption when combined with Morpheus, the Dream Mirror Black Knight and we take as much of that as we can get. 

Phantasos, the Dream Mirror Foe: L4 with 1900/900 Statline. Can attack directly during the Turn he's Special summoned. Combining him with one or more Dream Mirror Phantasms can lead to a 2400/2900/3400 direct attacking threat but that's about all he can do. Both Forms of Phantasos are okayish to use and Phantasos, the Dream Mirror Foe is overall the weakest of them all. 

Morpheus, the Dream Mirror White Knight: L8 with 1000/2800 Statline. Can't be destroyed by Battle or Card effects during the turn he's Special summoned. Combining him with Dream Mirror of Joy is very useful to protect your Monsters with a lower level from Attacks and targeting effects while Morpheus itself is also protected from his own effect. He really helps out a lot to stay alive more times then you would think. 

Morpheus, the Dream Mirror Black Knight: L8 with 2800/1000 Statline. Can target and destroy 1 Card on the Field. He's a very nice interruption and a great OTK Tool. Since you can switch between both Forms of Morpheus during the Battle Phase he can deal massive Damage. Since he can destroy your own cards too there's an argument to destroy your own Dream Mirror Fantasy to get the GY protection effect available if you fail to meet the activation Condition of this card. 

Now before we move on we have to take a closer look at Dream Mirror Recap. It's a permanent Trap which will shuffle Dream Mirror Monsters into the Deck if they are tributed to activate their own effect. Thanks to this card you can loop Ikelos, Phantasos and Morpheus as many times as you like. If you don't have this card active you run out of targets for their Quick effects very quickly. 

The little problem is that your Fusion Bossmonster Oneiros, the Dream Mirror Tormentor will be shuffled into the Extra Deck too while this card is active which you don't want to happen BUT thankfully they thought about that part too. As a quick effect anytime you can send Dream Mirror Recap to the GY to place a Dream Mirror of Joy or Dream Mirror of Terror which is in the GY or Banished into your Field Zone face up. You can then Special summon a Monster from your Hand which mentions the Field Spell in it's text. Dream Mirror Recap is the only in archetype card who gets your Field Spells back from the GY so you often wanna use that effect to get your Field Spells back like that. 

 

Oneiros the God of Dreams

Obviously your Boss Monster has 2 Forms too which are both L10 with a 3000/3000 Statline. Both Forms are treated as LIGHT and DARK Attribute while on the Field and have to be summoned with a LIGHT and DARK Dream Mirror Monster. 

Oneiros, the Dream Mirror Tormentor can as a quick effect negate a Monster effect if Dream Mirror of Terror is active. If Dream Mirror of Joy is active he can tribute himself as a quick effect to summon his Counterpart Oneiros, the Dream Mirror Erlking from the Extra Deck in Defense Position. This is not treated as being properly Fusion Summoned. If you have a set Dream Mirror Oneiromancy in the backrow you are ready to negate everything the opponent might throw at you. 

Oneiros, the Dream Mirror Erlking can target and destroy any Card on the field if another Monster you control is Tributed. If he's destroyed through Battle or an opponents Card effect you can summon any other Dream Mirror Monster from your GY. His destruction effect triggers no matter how your Monster is tributed which is a very good thing. 

Both Forms of Oneiros form a little Loop if performed in correct order. Summon Oneiros, the Dream Mirror Tormentor first and tribute him with his Quick effect if he's in danger to summon Oneiros, the Dream Mirror Erlking from your Extra Deck. If this Oneiros, the Dream Mirror Erlking is destroyed he can bring back Oneiros, the Dream Mirror Tormentor who then can tribute himself again to get another Oneiros, the Dream Mirror Erlking from the Extra Deck. This "Loop" is obviously limited to the 3 Erlking's you have access too but it's nice to have. 

 

Manipulating the Mirrors

I guess it's about time to take a closer look at the pretty strong Spell & Trap Lineup we have access to. Dream Mirror Hypnagogia and Dream Mirror Recap are already out of the way and we know how important those two are but what about the rest? 

Dream Mirror of Joy and Dream Mirror of Terror can both banish themselves during either players End Phase and activate their Counterpart from the Hand or Deck. It's useful to use this effect not only to thin out your Deck but to get Dream Mirror Fantasy online too (We talk about this card very soon). 

Dream Mirror of Joy has an additional effect if you Control a LIGHT Dream Mirror Monster. Your opponent can only target your Monster with the highest Level for attacks and card effects. If you have your L10 Oneiros active he will protect all other Dream Mirror Monsters. Since he's treated as LIGHT and DARK he alway fulfills the Condition for both of your Field Spells. 

Dream Mirror of Terror will inflict 300 Burn damage to the opponent whenever he Special summons a Monster if you control a DARK Dream Mirror Monster. Since your L3 Neiroy's can change their Attribute they are not only useful to easily Fusion Summon Oneiros but also good to get your Field Spells effects active. In general I like to have Dream Mirror of Joy active on my side since the protection he creates is kinda good to have. 

Having 300 Burn Damage is useful in some specific matchups so think about it against Synchro Spam or Divine Beast Decks. 

Dream Mirror Phantasms is a permanent spell that can search any Dream Mirror Monster from your Deck on activation. If "Joy" is active your Monsters gain 500 ATK/DEF, if "Terror" is active opponents Monsters loose 500 ATK/DEF. This card is a searcher which also creates a huge Gap in Stat advantage and even increases the ATK of non Dream Mirror Monsters. A must play for sure. 

Dream Mirror of Chaos is a quick play which fusion summons Oneiros by using Monsters from the field as Material. If "Joy" is active you can use your Hand too, if "Terror" is active you can banish Monsters from your GY too. This card is obviously your Oneiros access and very easy to get with Ikelos, the Dream Mirror Sprite whenever you need it. 

Dream Mirror Fantasy is a Normal Trap I mentioned a few times already since it's kinda good. If you control a Dream Mirror Monster you shuffle both "Joy" and "Terror" from your banished Zone back into the Deck to banish 1 card on the field. This effect does NOT target. You can banish this card from the GY if Dream Mirror Cards would be destroyed to prevent that. It can protect both Monsters and Backrow. This card is easily online within one turn since both "Joy" and "Terror" can banish themselves during the End Phase. 

Dream Mirror Oneiromancy: A Counter Trap which negates and destroys a Spell/Trap if "Joy" is active and negates and destroys a Monster that is Special summoned if "Terror" is active. Having a slightly weaker Solemn Judgment without cost and only condition is absolute gold. 

 

The Extra Dreams 

The Extra Deck is there to close some holes within this Strategy and make the whole Archetype well rounded. 

Leviair the Sea Dragon is here to bring back banished Dream Mirror Monsters which fell victim to Dream Mirror of Chaos and be able to use them again. 

Number 49: Fortune Tune is a little tower who can recover a few LP every turn but more importantly shuffle both Neiroy, the Dream Mirror Disciple and Neiroy, the Dream Mirror Traitor back into your Deck to be able to use them again. 

Use Gravity Controller to easily trigger this recycling effect. Gravity Controller itself can return to the Extra Deck if he Battles a Monster in the Extra Monster Zone which forms a very nice little Loop with Number 49: Fortune Tune who also returns to the Extra Deck through his own effect.

Knightmare Gryphon is here to recycle your Spell & Trap lineup, especially Dream Mirror of Chaos and Dream Mirror Oneiromancy most of the time. Since he's a Link-4 he has a pretty hefty cost investment but he also prevents the activation of Special Summoned Monsters effects which are not linked. 

Proxy F Magician is able to fusion summon with Monsters on the field and can special summon Neiroy, the Dream Mirror Traitor from your Hand which is also nice to have access to. 

Barricadeborg Blocker recycles your Field Spells and Dream Mirror Phantasms and protects them against destruction. He's especially nice since Dream Mirror Phantasms makes him more formidable in terms of Statline.

 

Oneiros has a Pipedream

Dream Mirror is not without flaws. Without Neiroy, the Dream Mirror Traitor you don't get up to speed very fast and he falls to a single Ash Blossom & Joyous Spring which is bad. On the other Hand Dream Mirror Hypnagogia is immune to Ash Blossom & Joyous Spring which is a pluspoint. 

But there's another problem in form of ressources. You need Dream Mirror Recap active to be able to run this deck properly after turn 3 or more. Otherwise you won't have enough targets in your Maindeck left to play the game. 

Being reliant on 2 active Field Spells comes with another downside. The opponent might find it easy to remove the Field Spell on his side by activating his own Field Spell on top of it. Be sure to know what he's playing and activate Dream Mirror Hypnagogia in response to his Field Spell activation to avoid disaster. 

Overall this Deck is not as easy to play as it might seem at first sight. 

 

Final Fantasy 

Dream Mirror is a Deck which relies heavily on it's Spell & Trap lineup and can generate massive advantage while interrupting the opponent with powerful Quick effects. A Dream Mirror Hypnagogia & Dream Mirror Recap setup can deal with almost everything and makes you feel like playing a top Meta Deck. 

If you like a unique Playstyle like the one Dream Mirror has and you got some Experience with Yugioh as a whole feel free to give this Deck a try, it's a very fun Deck. 

 

Final Rating: 

OTK Potential

Defensive Tools

Control Options

Removal Options

Recovery/Recycling

Card Advantage

Overall Rating:   34/42

 

 

Special Sleeping Instructions

More modern Decks don't have many unknown rulings but Dream Mirror is strange and special, that's why this section is a little bigger: 

Oneiros, the Dream Mirror Tormentor: 1. His negate doesn't destroy the Monster. 2. Summoning Oneiros, the Dream Mirror Erlking with his effect does not count as being properly Fusion summoned. 3. This card returns to the Extra Deck if Dream Mirror Recap is active when he activates his second effect. 

Morpheus, the Dream Mirror White Knight: His protection effect has to be activated after he's successfully special summoned. 

Neiroy, the Dream Mirror Disciple: 1. Special summoning him from the Hand is an effect which activates in your Hand. 2. His 2nd effect is mandatory. It's optional to return a Spell/Trap but you always draw a card. 

Neiroy, the Dream Mirror Traitor: If you can't add "Joy" or "Terror" to your Hand his effect can't be activated. 

Dream Mirror of Joy & Dream Mirror of Terror: Activating "Joy" or "Terror" from your Deck is an effect which Ash Blossom & Joyous Spring can't negate. 

Dream Mirror Hypnagogia: This cards effect can also not be negated from Ash Blossom & Joyous Spring.

Dream Mirror Fantasy: 1. This card can prevent the destruction of as many Dream Mirror Cards as you like by banishing itself. 2. This card does not target.

Dream Mirror Recap: Monsters shuffled into the Deck do not touch the GY at any point.

deck_excerpt: Fan Favourite Archetype Devolves into Shifter Turbo
deck_description:
Crystal Beasts are a popular anime archetype that recieved an astounding series of support last year with their structure deck, which helped fix a lot of problems they had before, and are coming up on another powerful piece of support very soon, "Golden Rule". This card allows you to set 2 Crystal Beasts from your Deck as face-up Continuous Spells, then Special Summon 1 Crystal Beast monster from your hand with a different name from the cards you placed. Notice how the 2 you set from the Deck can be the same name. So what you can do is set 2 Sapphire Pegasus from your Deck, and Special Summon Ruby Carbuncle from hand, and Summon the 2 Pegasus from your Spell & Trap Zone to set other Crystal Beasts from your Deck.

This archetype has become easily able to make Rank 4s, most popularly "Time Thief Redoer" and "Lightning Chidori", but due to the Crystal Beast monsters staying the Spell & Trap Zone instead of the GY, the deck is easily able to utilize the infamous Dimension Shifter and Dimensional Fissure. Overall, a rogue deck that can stand up to the current meta, but not dominate it.

deck_excerpt: Gravekeepers CAN be good after all!
deck_description:
This is a replica of puy's World Championship Qualifier build that topped and won the whole event in question, stuck on here for archive purposes.

From the sea of Chaos/Warrior/Panda, this stuck out particularly well for me with its focus on trying to redeem Gravekeepers. While the architype is surely quite well known in Goat Format, it's had almost zero major success as a competently strong deck (other than some relatively minor early victories) despite being a direct counter to Chaos builds; you usually only see Necrovalley used in some side-decks if need be as a tech at best. You see Spy a lot as well however as either a wall and/or in slower Chaos variations.

This attempts to reform them by pairing them up with Anti-Meta/Toolbox Warrior for adjustable plays alongside aggressive backrow removal and 3x Dustshoot to fully control the field and hand. As you can tell it's mostly based around handling the Chaos meta, which it seems to be fairly successful at. Side-deck functions with even more tech to throw in including more backrow removal, Monarch plays and even King Tiger to disable Panda Burn strats. It's a pretty simple but extremely effective deck at doing what it does.

Category: Tournament Meta Deck

Tournament Meta Decks are current-level Meta Decks that are capable of going up against the best of the best. These are curated lists that cannot be uploaded by regular users.

Creator: Ricardo Ruiz

Tournament: Central America WCQ - June 9th 2023

Placement: Top 32

Honestly, this is one of the cooler builds I thought up.

While there is a version that uses the stronger version of Jackal in a convoluted loop, no one uses the weaker but still pretty impressive Jackal Knight, which is a shame because he's a solid feature. His stats are decent for the time, he's splashable in beast decks, and his effect is crippling for many decks as he can snatch up their monsters when they are destroyed, meaning Chaos builds lose their typically splashable fodder for their bigger plays, most conventional meta builds can suffer if their combo pieces are missing, and any general flip monster can be stolen and then used by us via Book of Moon to turn their effects against them. It's a really great effect, especially when considering almost every major deck uses the Graveyard for multiple plays.

To help with the current meta of heavy backrow, we use Decree to disable general traps alongside Warwolf/Breaker and Jinzo. Equip cards like United or Baou either make our Jackal more beefy or bypass dangerous flip effects. Removal like Smashing/Vortex/Nobleman provide great coverage for threats that our high-stat beasts might have issues with.

Battle Ox gives our Jackal plays more oomf with additional piercing damage to boot, and Nimble is useful for baiting out removal or to establish field presence. Wild Nature is generally not played in Beastdown/beatdown decks due to most staple monsters having low DEF: a extra 600 or so isn't going to help much. Jackal has 1600, which combined with his already decent stats makes him a 3000+ wrecking ball that can run over practially everything. We can also use Moon to bypass the destruction effect if need be. My Body as a Shield helps with field nukes and/or attempts to clean the field nicely.

Finally we have conventional cards like D.D. Assailant and Reaper; mostly here just to stall potential plays out if required but can be used aggressively as well. The side deck is focused around specific counters (Asura/Panda/Controller for Goat Control, Wombat/Wok for burn, etc) additional tech like Manticore as a alternative boss monster or Trunade to further wipe out backrow troubles. Easy done.

....ok, so this isn't obviously going to be that good, especially with no Trinity. Unlike in Edison a Monster Mash deck is significantly harder to do just due to the insanely good spells and traps you are inhertently missing out in. The point of Monster Mash is that you ONLY play monsters, so obviously Chaos is the best archetype to go though. This is my most conservative attempt at making it at least semi-playable, playing it safe if you will.

One great thing about this deck is the sheer amount of plays here: you have tons of draw power, big monster potential, tons of recruiters, etc etc. Monster Mash means you will always draw a hand of good to great monsters while your opponent will draw maybe a few with spells and traps.

So.....how do we deal with that? Mirage Dragon helps a ton, as does the usual destruction you'd expect from a Chaos deck. You have so much to use here that backrow will usually not be enough to hold back all of it, especially combined with endless recruiter spam + eventual Chaos staples getting rid of cards, controlling the field, etc. Consistency is easy with the deck....well about as much without any spells, anyway. Everything draws or establishes advantage in different manners. Even silly stuff like the one Stein can go into shutdown or aid with aggressive pushes well. Maruading Captain helps cheat out out plays. Zombie engine is still one of the best plays even with no spells or recovery so it was a no brainer to stick on as well.

Jars are AMAZING in this deck. Unlike in conventional decks where this would hurt if you were saving up a certain spell or trap when it pops, it means nothing to you here, just a reason to fill up the Grave with Chaos fodder and stuff you don't need. Cyber Jar gives you a entire field to play around with while your opponent will at best get 2/3. Protector + Jars is a cool combo as well if you can pull it off.

Flip effects keep your opponent on your toes and will probably waste Noblemen given the sheer volume of recruiter fodder mixed in. 

Side deck is mostly if you need to push more aggressively. Theban is weird, but having a 3000 beatstick is worth it for the quality this deck has. Magician combo is more consistency and you can work Creator tech if you need to recycle monsters + get more LIGHT monsters for Chaos. I'll be tinkering around with Mash more with variations (Megarock maybe???) which may or may not be better. It's a step to something, at least.

deck_name: Top Deck / Frog Monarch | Dandan Equivalent
deck_description:
Overview

Please ignore the vanillas - just there due to YGOPRODECK limitations - please view the actual deck down the bottom.

I thought the whole Dandan format for MTG was really neat, so I gave a go at doing something similar for YGO.

The game is meant to be played with one deck and one graveyard, shared between both players.

Could be a good bit of fun, maybe even skillfull. I encourage you all to play around with card choices / ratios / rules and let me know what you think / develop it further yourselves if you so desire.

I have looked into Diamond Dude as another really interesting card for the format - just requires some more normal spells to be used more consistently, it certainly benefits from stacking. Duality looked neat, but it was basically free card draw, although at the cost of using Treeborn which is neat. Ancient Telescope could also be a neat card - but rules about public information would have to be refined to ensure that this format's whole thing of best possible play with maximum information is maintained.

This format cannot really be played via any simulators, automated at least. Would recommend that if you do play - do so IRL (Dueling Book would be a real hassle for this), and make sure to take a look at my ratios at the bottom / mess around with the deck / rules for yourself.

Card Choice Explanations

  • Raiza the Storm Monarch | Raiza is meant to be both a removal option, and the only real means of damage in the format. Raiza is your main tribute / body outlet with the Treeborn frog in circulation. Raiza allows you to stack the deck in your favour / your opponents [opposite of favour], just like other cards in the format, but also allows for removal of monsters such as Ghost Belle or a Treeborn Frog on the field via battle, either removing them from the game, setting up plays with Treeborn, or putting something into the GY for Cyber Valley to recycle. It takes four hits from Raiza to close out the game, 8000 > 5600 > 3200 > 800 > 0, with ample opportunities for counter-play, either with another Raiza, or Back to Square One / Phoenix Wing Wind Blast.
  • Treeborn Frog | Essential card for this format. With one GY, this card is basically exchanged each turn - meaning if you tribute it off on your side for a Raiza, suddenly your opponent has both free defense, and tribute fodder that next turn. Removal of TF from the GY means both players suddenly lose a resource, emphasising smart timing and careful planning / strategy. TF has multiple options of removal from the GY as discussed later on - all which play into this strategic resource loop between players. Treeborn's 100 ATK / DEF means it cannot get over itself, a set D.D Crow, or a Ghost Belle (in which case you would take damage).
  • Ghost Belle & Haunted Mansion | One of the two hand traps in this format, Ghost Belle is a means to stop a Treeborn from going off, negate a D.D. Crow or Called By The Grave use, or rendering Cyber Valley a trade for normal summon Treeborn. Ghost Belle's 1800 DEF makes it the only real defensive body of the format that ALSO deals damage, pushing your opponent over that 800LP margin and opening them up for game in only three hits with Raiza. Ghost Belle can in turn be negated by Called By The Grave.
  • D.D. Crow | Crow is basically Ghost Belle but it can be used in a more interesting scenario - banishing a TF after you have just used it, taking it out of the game for your opponent. Crow can thus also stop a TF, or even mess up a Cyber Valley. Crow, as a handtrap, can thus also lose to Clled By.
  • Cyber Valley | Cyber Valley is one of the most premium resources here, offering real versatility in use. It can be a way to delay the game from a loss, a way to draw into whatever you just stacked, or a way to recycle cards your opponent or yourself have used to either give them a poor draw, or give you something quite useful later down the track. Valley is the only card draw in this format, and thus costs between itself as a body, or another monster, for you to gain that card draw - requiring some degree of pre-planning to use it.
  • Back to Square One / Phoenix Wing Wind Blast | A normal spell and a trap, respectively, which both allow for a discard and a stack of the deck. This either means removal in the case of Wind Blast, or removal / stacking of any monster via Square. Wind Blast has the trade-off of having to wait a turn, but allows for greater versatility in the form of removing your opponent's spells / traps in addition to monsters, although losing the ability to stack your cards onto the deck. Thus, Wind Blast's only out other than Raiza, is itself, turning it into a card with a lot of weight on its shoulders and a degree of risk. Both of these cards, requiring a discard, can thus also put Treeborn Frog into rotation. Wind Blast can thus ensure you get its first revival - sending TF on your opponent's turn, awaiting your standby phase. Back to Square One requires you have some kind of negation such as Ghost Belle to ensure that your opponent cannot make use of it during their standby phase after you sent it.
  • Spellbook Organization / Fruits of Kozaky's Studies | Basically the same card, but required. Both of these cards allow for either counterplay to deck stacking, either giving you a draw you stacked further down, bricking your opponent, preventing your opponent from getting something they stacked, or preventing your opponent from bricking you. Nothing much else of note, they do not achieve card advantage, but they do allow for more stacking strategy.
  • Called By The Grave | This is your out to Cyber Valley, Treeborn Frog, Raiza, and Ghost Belle all in one. It does thus come at the cost of stopping you from using those cards that turn, the hand traps in particular, but it allows you to either insulate your plays, stop your opponent from interrupting your plays, preventing a Treeborn Frog from going off, or acting as basically a free negate. Called By's banish also means that anything banished, either a Treeborn Frog or anything Cyber Valley may want to stack, are no longer in the game - gone, banished, exiled, zero'd, thus also requiring smart use, or you may be putting yourself at risk. Called By in of itself loses to Ghost Belle.

Correct Ratios (due to YGOPRODECK limitations)

Due to YGOPRODECK's limitations, the ratios I have built the deck with are not displayed. Please ignore the random vanilla monsters, just there to satisfy YGOPRODECK's 40-card minimum. The correct deck ratios are as follows:

  • 6x Raiza
  • 6x Treeborn
  • 3x Belle
  • 3x D.D. Crow
  • 2x Cyber Valley
  • 4x Back to Square One
  • 4x Phoenix Wing Wind Blast
  • 4x Spellbook Organization
  • 4x Fruits of Kozaky's Studies
  • 4x Called By The Grave

deck_excerpt: 3x Cybernetic Successor, based on a guide by Fliboce from Out Of Games.
deck_description:
Taken from: https://outof.games/yu-gi-oh/guides/200-introduction-to-cybernetic-successor-yu-gi-oh-master-duel-structure-deck/

Visit the site for more information.

Bare Essential Starting Hand

Cyberdark Claw + Any Spell/Trap to discard + Any "Cyber" Monster to discard + Any Cyberdark Monster to Fuse

  1. Activate Cyberdark Claw to add Cybernetic Horizon.
  2. Activate Cybernetic Horizon by dumping any 2 "Cyber" Monsters from Deck and Hand to GY, including one Cyberdark. Search Cyber Dragon Core and send Cyber End Dragon to the GY at resolution.
  3. Normal Summon Cyber Dragon Core, enabling you to add Cyberdark Realm to hand.
  4. When activating Realm, Cyberdark Cannon will be the next Monster to search.
  5. Now activate Cannon to replace it with Cyberdark Chimera, which lets you Fusion Summon by banishing materials from the GY.
  6. Thanks to Cyberdark Realm we have a second Normal Summon for Cyberdark Chimera.
  7. Chimera now uses its effect to discard the Spell/Trap we started out with, which gets us to Power Bond (Power Bond must be in the Deck for this to work).
  8. A total of 3 Cyberdark Monsters are now in the GY, Chimera is one on the field, and one was in the starting hand. This means Power Bond can use all 5 to bring out Cyberdarkness Dragon.
  9. The effect on Summon will let us equip Cyber End Dragon to it and voilà, the unaffected by activated effects 5,000 ATK Monster hits the field.

"Ideal" Starting Hand

Cyber Emergency + Cyberdark Cannon + Any Spell/Trap to discard

  1. Emergency adds Core.
  2. Core adds Realm.
  3. Realm adds Claw.
  4. Claw adds Horizon.
  5. Cannon adds Chimera.
  6. Horizon is used by discarding Chimera from hand and Core from the Deck.
  7. Another Chimera will be added, and Cyber End Dragon hits the GY.
  8. Chimera triggers in the GY, allowing a fourth Cyberdark Monster to be sent from the Deck to the GY.

From there onward it's the same routine as above. In this variation, four Cyberdarks are in the GY, since Chimera was added twice, allowing its effect to send another. When you start out with more combo pieces than needed, consider if you can afford to search Cyberdark Invasion for added disruption.

One last idea to close the combo section out on: It's not always correct to go all in. A potential plan B could involve passing just with Cyberdarkness Dragon. The possibility to negate any effect up to the amount of equipments it has, is worth looking into. Even for something as simple as an activated Maxx "C", ending on a single negate might prove more detrimental than granting the opponent another draw.

Is a deck of insects

Fluffals, Edge Imps, and Frightfurs are a very interesting hybrid of archetypes which all support each other. "Frightfur Fusion" and "Frightfur Patchwork" are both searchable via "Edge Imp Chain", and Patchwork can in turn search an Edge Imp, like Scythe, and a Poly, "Frightfur Cruel Whale" is able to be summoned and disrupt on your opponent's turn from "Edge Imp Scythe", and all of the Fusions can easily OTK on the follow-up.

Cross-Sheep is an excellent card in this deck, as the Fluffals have a lot of good effects on the field and when used as fusion material, so you can fuse with them, then summon them back, not only giving more fusion or link material on the field, but giving you access to their effects again."Toy Vendor" is the same roulette wheel as always, and "Foolish Burial Goods" can send it, or "Frightfur Repair", which can also be sent off of Cruel Whale's effect. "Royal Penguins Garden" searches "Fluffal Penguin", the best one, which can Special Summon a Fluffal from hand while on field, and draw 2, discard 1 when used as fusion material.

The Generaider Bosses are high level monsters with powerful effects that center around their archetypal Field Spell, "Generaider Boss Stage". If a card is added from your opponent's deck to their hand, it allows you to Special Summon a Boss from your Deck, and if you Special Summon a Generaider monster during your opponent's turn, you can summon a bunch of tokens, which you can use to activate the Bosses' strong effects. Overall, this deck's very unique playstyle has coined it many fans, and with its new support, it firmly cements itself as a rogue strategy.

deck_excerpt: He Taught the Fish to Synchro Summon
deck_description:
In a deck centered around banishing cards, of course "Dimension Shifter" would make an appearance. These fish Special Summon themselves during the next turn after they are banished, or in Zep's case, if they are banished at all, and can Synchro Summon during your opponents turn. Their boss monster, "Ghoti of the Deep Beyond", has a Zeroboros-like board wipe effect on Synchro Summon (if it was during your opponent's turn) to banish everything on the field, but summons itself back next turn if it was banished from the field.

The Diva Package allows this deck to easily make a (mostly) untargetable "Swordsoul SupremeSovreign - Chengying", a monster which buffs itself and debuffs your opponent's monsters for each banished card, has a powerful effect when a card is banished, and also isn't able to be destroyed by card effects. The line to it is: Normal Summon "Deep Sea Diva", Special Summon "Guitar Gurnards Duonigis" from your deck and activate its 1st effect, modify Diva's level with Gurnards' 2nd effect, Synchro Summon "Deep Sea Prima Donna", add one of your opponent's banished cards to their hand and Special Summon another Gurnards from your Deck, then Synchro Summon a Level 10, like Chengying. You also have a couple of Gurnards in the GY to use their 3rd effect, which banishes themself from the GY, to buff a WATER monster you control for each banished monster, which can trigger Chengying's effect to non-target banish 1 card from your opponent's field and 1 from their GY.

deck_excerpt: It's gettin', it's gettin', it's gettin' kinda hectic.
deck_description:
Aside from not having handtraps, because they're filler and I hate them, I'm calling this deck meta. Engage and Multirole are fresh off the limited list, so yeah. This deck's gonna make a huge comeback, all due to the fact that it's getting new cards and an alt-art printing in Monstrous Revenge. Thanks, capitalism! Imagine the emotional damage this deck would do with Triple Tactics Thrust. There's plenty of flexy space for handtraps with some easy choices to replace, but I don't like being that meta, so you can figure it out on your own.

Camellia isn't out in the TCG yet, so sub her with a second Zeke. I maxed on Roze because Azalea, the new link that is out, requires 2 light/dark monsters to summon. I prefer her removal to Zeke's because she can target and destroy any card on summon and has non-targeting battle phase destruction. It seems to me that with the new main deck monsters, none of which are light/dark, you can either use their effects or quick-play spells on your opponent's turn, but not both until the monsters are gone. Flexibility, I guess, though I wish they'd written a way around it for the monsters since using them could technically slow the deck down. It's worth noting that even if you give control of Ciela to your opponent, her GY effect will activate for you. Akash gives battle protection and is a decent body to camp on the board. Himmel's the only new one I would say is a requirement because of that negate. It feels weird that there are no new spell cards, but after Linkage, I guess they don't need to do any more.

deck_excerpt: Not to be confused with Canap
deck_description:
The four sons of Horus descend upon Yu-Gi-Oh! This new strategy focus around Pharaonic Sarcophagus being on the field so your Horus monsters can come back from the GY onto the field, fitting considering their imagery being used for Canopic Jars which houses organs of the deceased, these cards will make your opponent think twice before hitting you with a Kaiju.

All Horus monsters share the following effects:

"If you control "Pharaonic Sarcophagus", you can Special Summon this card (from your GY). You can only Special Summon "X, X of Horus" once per turn this way." And "If another card(s) you control leaves the field by an opponent's card effect while you control this monster: Apply effect"

  • Imsety, Glory of Horus is the most important Horus monster, discarding itself and another monster to add Pharaonic Sarcophagus and drawing 1, not only does this set-up the GY with your Horus cards, Vanguard of the Underground Emperor, Gizmek Orochi, the Serpentron Sky Slasher or search a Kaiju with Interrupted Kaiju Slumber's GY effect. When another card leaves the field Imsy sends a card from the field to the GY.
  • Hapy, Vanguard of Horus unique effect recycles 2 cards from the GY or banished zone from either player back into their hand, which is great to retrieve handtraps, staples or other monsters like Deep Sea Diva or Coach King Giantrainer to keep drawing. Do not let him be hit by D.D. Crow. 
  • Duamutef, Blessing of Horus unique effect draws 1 for each card up to the number of differently named monsters on your board, which comes handy considering you want to draw as many 8s to discard/summon to your board for the OTK.
  • Qebehsenuef, Aegis of Horus is the weakest of them in my opinion since you wont be keeping any of the Horus cards half the time, but he offers protection against targeting which the continuous spell does not cover, and for some reason prevents battles? Which the continuous already does...
  • Pharaonic Sarcophagus is insane, protects Horus cards from being destroyed by stuff that doesnt target like Lightning Storm or Raigeki. It can also foolish any Horus monster for a discard up to 4 times per turn, which is funny cause people will still try to Ash it, and if a Horus battles once per turn you get to send whatever it battled with, which is annoying for decks that rely on big battle damage like Scareclaw or Crusadia.
  • Dogoran, the Mad Flame Kaiju, Gadarla, the Mystery Dust Kaiju, Gameciel, the Sea Turtle Kaiju and Interrupted Kaiju Slumber are all free removal which also gives you a big body, level 8 monster, which you can Change of Heart or Triple Tactics Talent back to your field. Other than that its discard fodder.   
  • Danger! Bigfoot! and Danger! Thunderbird! can discard themselves to remove backrow, monsters or put themselves in the board. Same goes for Vanguard of the Underground Emperor, Yakusa, Lord of the Eight Thunders and Gizmek Orochi, the Serpentron Sky Slasher which also recurs from the GY, do note that you may banish your one ofs, use him when you are certain you can push for game.
  • Deep Sea Diva summons another of herself, and with 2 8s and both of them you get Baronne de Fleur and Swordsoul Supreme Sovereign - Chengying that are good going first or second, Ruddy Rose Dragon can also help against Decks that need the GY, she and Orochi can also trigger Chengying.
  • Number 97: Draglubion and Number 100: Numeron Dragon are your go to cards to delete your opponent from the face of the Earth.
  • Number 90: Galaxy-Eyes Photon Lord negates spells, Number 90: Galaxy-Eyes Photon Lord monsters, and Number 23: Lancelot, Dark Knight of the Underworld isn't picky he will just negate the first thing he sees.
  • Coach King Giantrainer draws 3 for free, but will stop you from battling, so watch out for that.
  • The Zombie Vampire mills from both players and can revive one of the milled monsters, giving you extra bodies for the push.
  • Dingirsu, the Orcust of the Evening Star sends a card from the opponent's field and protects your monsters from destruction.
  • Number F0: Utopic Future and Number F0: Utopic Draco Future can be made to negate and run over stuff.
  • Divine Arsenal AA-ZEUS - Sky Thunder for the mass board wipe and possible attaching of a Horus to put in the GY and Superdreadnought Rail Cannon Gustav Max which paired with Coach's burn can push for game, you will be making him with your 10's.
  • Number 1: Infection Buzz King, Number 84: Pain Gainer, Number 77: The Seven Sins can replace the Gustav and F0s, first removes a target from the opponent's Extra Deck and pops a card while the other 2 makes Zeus bigger.

Tournament: Central America WCQ - June 9th 2023

Another casual deck to play with. Here is how to OTK:

- Draw with Treasure Panda and Saryuja until you get combo pieces.

- Combo-I: Either reduce your health by half via Cybernetic Fusion Support or increase your opponent's health via Upstart Goblin. Difference must be 3000 to execute the combo.

- Combo-II: Special Summon another level 4 monster alongside Treasure Panda via Saryuja.

- Combo-III: XYZ summon Number 39: Utopia >>> Number S39: Utopia Prime.

- Combo-IV: Give your opponent a minion to activate Utopia Prime's ability via Shien's Spy. Then, trigger Utopia Prime to reduce your health.

- Combo-V: A Feather of Phoenix >>> Put Spell/Monster card on top of deck >>> Set Fuhma Shuriken >>> Reversal Quiz >>> Choose correct answer! >>> KO!!!

 

Here are some budget tips if you want to save SR or UR:

- "Into the Void" can be unlocked through "The Infinite Void" Secret Pack to save 90 SR!

- "Formula Synchron" isn't really needed, if you are low on SR. Though it can be unlocked by opening "Stardust Ties" Secret Pack, Saryuja and other Link monsters can pick targets to refill GY for "Pot of Avarice" more than enough. 90 SR saved!

- "Pot of Avarice" and "Number 39: Utopia" can be collected by purchasing "Re-Contact Universe" deck. 90 SR + 30 UR saved and you can try a new deck!

- "Wonder Wand" and "Spellbook of Knowledge" can be collected by purchasing "Spellbook of Prophecy" deck. 120 SR saved and you can try a new deck!

- "Link Spider", "Link Bound" and LAN are given for free, if you've picked "Link Generation". Thus, 90 SR is saved!

- "Reversal Quiz" and "Number S39: Utopia Prime" can be found from "Legacy Pack". Hope you were lucky to get these for free to save 60 SR.

- "Moray of Avarice" can be unlocked through timed selection pack called "The Synchronized Cosmoc". As of this writing, if you are willing to spend gems to save 30 UR, this is your chance.

- "Moray of Greed" can be a good and cheap alternative for drawing cards. 2xExodia+5x1*-Water or 3xExodia+4x1*-Water are perfect formulae for this card without making Wand and Spellbook cards redundant.

 

So, in total, you can save up to 540 SR and 60 UR, if you are willing to spend some gems. Other SR and UR cards I didn't mention are essential.

 

That's all for this deck. Thanks for reading, feel free to ask anything. Have fun in Master Duel!
