Enjoy. Don't actually buy this deck, just play it on a limited format on a website like https://duelingbook.com for cheap decks without broken cards.

Regarding adds if you have a good hand, always have a Souleating Oviraptor before any Normal Summon. If you have one, add Miscellaneousaurus . If you have one, add Doodle Beast - Stego 

Most basic 1 card combo:

Activate Lost World if able, and at the end of the combo if everything worked Lost World will protect opponent's token from Souleating Oviraptor 's effect to destroy any Level 4 or lower Dinosaur monster on the field ( including your opponent's ) and by protecting the token, Lost World will send Petiteranodon which will Special Summon Dinowrestler Pankratops from Deck.

The combo starts with Souleating Oviraptor or any spell that adds Souleating Oviraptor to hand.

 

Normal Summon Souleating Oviraptor, effect.

Add Miscellaneousaurus to hand, activate Miscellaneousaurus 

Miscellaneousaurus effect in GY banish itself, Special Summon Animadorned Archosaur 

Animadorned Archosaur  destroys any baby dinosaur in hand but if nothing was found, destroys Souleating Oviraptor and adds Double Evolution Pill 

You will now commit to a summon of a non-Dinosaur monster. If you have Doodle Beast - Stego in your hand, Special Summon it using its effect in a zone that Baba Barber can point to.

Doodle Beast - Stego 's effect to add Doodlebook - Uh uh uh! and discard Doodlebook - Uh uh uh! 

Link Summon Relinquished Anima using Animadorned Archosaur. If your opponent placed their monsters in an awkward spot, then Link Summon Baba Barber using Relinquished Anima and Souleating Oviraptor. 

Activate Double Evolution Pill banish Relinquished Anima and Animadorned Archosaur to Special Summon Ultimate Conductor Tyranno from your Deck, ignoring its summoning conditions. If you drew Ultimate Conductor Tyranno , Special Summon Dinowrestler Pankratops instead and use Ultimate Conductor Tyranno 's summoning condition banishing Animadorned Archosaur and Souleating Oviraptor from your GY.

During your opponent's Draw Phase, activate Doodlebook - Uh uh uh! if its in your GY, banishing itself to add Doodle Beast - Tyranno 

Doodle Beast - Tyranno will let you tribute a single Dinosaur monster ( should be Doodle Beast - Stego ) to non-targetting destroy 1 monster on the field and gain ATK equal to half the ATK it had on field ( not original ATK )

Ultimate Conductor Tyranno will let you destroy one of your monsters to flip every monster your opponent controls face-down.

Dinowrestler Pankratops will let you tribute itself to destroy one of your opponent's cards.

Baba Barber is a weak monster that removes itself or Doodle Beast - Stego during the Battle Phase.

There's also the occasional Wollow, Founder of the Drudge Dragons. Don't sleep on him! He's great.

Tournament: Niagara Falls WCQ Regional - June 17th 2023

Time Wizard is a recent tech pick that's been used in quite a few decks so I figured I would try to come up with something worth trying out in regards to that running theme. Pretty standard Chaos build outside of throwing in Nephthys cards to benefit off a wrong toss and Blowback to take advantage of the 2x Second Coin Toss included. 

Time Wizard can be bounced out via Angel recruiters or with the Magician set, making him a suprisingly easy monster to throw on the board, though you can also misdirect by just doing the usual Vindictive play. Cyber Jar is here to cycle though your deck quicker and/or get a big nuke with Wizard's effect.

Backrow selection is a lot of one-offs, mostly because there's not really a need to go overboard with anything with such a strong monster lineup, not to also mention you don't want to potentially lose a ton of advantage if Nephthys is popped.

Side deck is predictively also very varied, focused around countering a wide assortment of decks if required or adding in more consistency to certain playstyles. Fiend Comedian is silly but pulling it off on someone who focuses way too much on the grave (Zombie/Chaos again) can be funny.

deck_description: Auroradon Springans for Master Duel Post Selection Pack: Climax of the Showdown

The ability of the non-Ritual Gishki monsters to search any Gishki card you need is crazy, and most of them are Level 2, so you know what that means... The Sprights are an excellent supporting engine to support any archetype/deck involving Level/Rank/Link 2 monsters, and they excel at their job in this deck. The new boss of the Gishki archetype, "Evigishki Neremanas" is a hell of an upgrade. On Ritual Summon, it reborns a WATER, it can't be destroyed in battle with an Extra Deck monster, and to top it all off, it has a soft once per turn monster negate. While this deck was definitely hurt by the banning of "Spright Elf", I think it can still hold its own and show its mettle in this meta.

deck_description:
Hello, I am fairly new to yugioh.  Started playing with the release of Master Duel, and have been on and off since.  This is my first real attempt to actually build a combo deck myself, and I have no idea if there are more optimized versions of this endboard.  One of the first decks I really fell in love with was @Ignister, so I really leaned into what I knew and went from there.

What I have been looking at as main combo
Achichi NS search Pikari, make Dark Infant to search A.I.land

SS Pikari search A.I. Meet You for Doyon, make Wicckid

SS Doyon add back Pikari, Wicckid banish Infant to search Bururu.  Make Cyberse Witch

SS Bururu mill Gatchiri, Witch banish A.I. Meet You for Sage and Cynet Ritual, then SS Doyon

SS Wind Pegasus with Bururu+Doyon, Bururu reborn Doyon, Cynet Ritual Doyon as material for Sage

Sage effect use Doyon and Wicckid in gy to make Disabwurm in far left column

SS Dark Templar with Witch, Wind Pegasus, Sage in right EMZ

Diasbwurm reborns Pikari and becomes lvl 4, Pikari for Infant in middle zone, Templar triggers, chain Infant to become divine, reborn Pikari, Bururu, Achichi.

Pikari+Disabwurm makes Allembertian,searches Circular.  Infant, Achichi, Bururu, and Templar make a 4 mat Arrival Cyberse

Circular mill a to SS, Allambertian tribute to reborn Nabla.  Circular search Equation.  Circular+Nabla to make Splash Mage.

Splash Mage reborns Gatchiri, Equation reborns a Mathmech, the Mathmech+Splash makes Transcode

Transcode+it's reborn+Gatchiri makes Darkfluid with Synchro, Fusion, XYZ, and Ritual.  Gatchiri makes the Darkfluid unaffected.  If you open Gatchiri, Circular, or one of the 3 reborns then you can also end on Superfactorial for Laplacian

deck_description:
I'm fully on board with saying that this deck is NOT optimal in the slightest but it's fun for big monster stuff so I couldn't really care. 

You play a big stat-heavy monster (mostly the Goblin cards, which are easily searched out) tribute it for Great Maju, run into stuff. Deck runs a mini Soul Control package to help tributes run faster, but is more biased towards Brain Control so you can actually use Maju for plays. Big Bang works well with the deck as you can equip it to basically any big monster for punishing attacks. 

Royal Command is fairly unused in some circles but it's great here as a universal method of dealing with flip plays when running over stuff rather than using purely Nobleman and praying for the best. Most of the deck otherwise is typical staple cards alongside stuff like Trunade and My Body to make plays more accessible. 

Side deck focuses on a wide assortment of plays including Monarchs, more flip counters, Oppression, Judgement, and even a copy of Deck Devastation that goes well with letting Maju do something beyond being big. It doesn't save this deck from being fairly exposed, but hey, that's what a deck like this has to suffer with in order to be workable.
This deck utilizes the Nemeses engine to abuse the effect of Destiny Hero Malicious. The Spell card Bonfire is used to search Nemeses Flag from the deck.

deck_description: Mannadium
Zombie World & Synchro

It would be extremely satisfying to see Watts become a new rogue deck, especially now that they finally have a combo! Wattuna is effectively a 2-card combo. You attack with your other level 4 Watt first, then summon it from hand to attack again, then special summon Wattaurus using Tuna and another one from your hand (this is important), then after Wattaurus attacks, shuffle Tuna from gy and 1 Watt you control (has to be 1 you control) into the deck to special summon any other Watt synchro regardless of level except Taurus. If this goes uninterrupted, you're looking at 4800-5100 damage minimum, depending on what other monsters you summon. And that's before buffs, which cards like Hip Hoshiningen and Galaxy Photon Dragon give to light monsters, like all Watts.

I filled the extra and side decks with other crap to try and turn the game in Watts' favor, because they still need to reach the battle phase before they can lock the opponent. Wattkingdom cancels opponents' summon effects in the same column, and that stacks with each copy and Watt monster on the field. It also finally gives us a way to summon more than one Watt on the first turn without having to wait for that Wattrain in your gy, meaning we can now do extra deck plays. You'll probably want to do that after the battle phase, though. Like summoning Bagooska after smackin' your opponent. Imagine opening a hand with 3 Wattkingdoms and a Watt monster. Your opponent gets to do nothing on summon without that limited Harpie's Feather Duster.

3 popular cards you should absolutely never use with Watts are Evilswarm Exciton Knight, Dark Ruler No More, and Evenly Matched. This deck needs to deal damage in the battle phase, which all 3 of those prevent. I know your opponent can put up big, daunting boards with their meta wombo-combo deck and you wanna get rid of them, but firstly, without Exciton, these monsters can't remove anything permanently, and secondly, you sacrifice your one win condition to clear their field once and then get blasted next turn. So be smart, and don't do that.
Win

Reflected Damage/Goad deck for Domain Format, a casual multiplayer free-for-all format inspired by MTG Commander format.

Using Ha-Re the Sword Mikanko as the Deck Master gives me access to any FIRE, Warrior or Mikanko monsters.

The main goal of this deck is to control the Battle Phases with any Reflecting Damage monsters with protection to battle/effect destruction and a battle interceptor card. After this setup, you can start to burn your opponent's LP attacking his monsters or forcing 'em to attack you.

QUICK NOTE: It's hard to use your Extra Deck cards outside a Rank 3 or a Synchro 4/7, the rest are for Pot of Prosperity.

Key concepts/keywords:

  • Reflecting damage card: Any card that can redirect battle damage to your opponent. For example: Amazoness Swords Woman.
  • Battle interceptor card: Any card that can redirect an attack to certain monster on the field. For example: Ring of Magnetism.
  • Goading card: Any card that forces your opponent's monsters to attack if able. For example: Savage Colosseum.
  • Double Damage card: Any card that doubles the damage you can reflect, whether you double the monster ATK/DEF or the damage itself. For example: Massivemorph or Magical Cylinders.

Key interactions:

  • Board goad + Battle interceptor: Your opponents can only attack you.
  • If both players are going to take damage from a card effect and you control a reflecting damage monster, only your opponent takes the damage. 

Let's break this list apart to help you understand the main role of certain cards:

  • Mikanko cards package: 10 S/T cards that works wonders to reach our endboard.
    • Equip Spells:
      • Mikanko Water Arabesque: With this you only need a battle interceptor to finish your setup. Trade any of your monsters for any non-ritual Mikanko monster from your deck. Awesome card in the early game.
      • Mikanko Fire Dance: Again, you only need a battle interceptor to finish your setup. Get any Mikanko monster from your GY and revive an opponent's monster. If you can, save this card for a recovery if you eat a board wipe.
      • Mikanko Purification Dance: This card is an easy setup with your Deck Master but is most often used to control your opponent's combo or extenders.
      • Mikanko Dance - Mayowashidori: Your ultimate recovery card, also is a great card to control the board with our attacks. Play this when you can protect it if you want to get the most of it.
    • Traps: 
      • Mikanko Promise: Use this card after a board wipe if you still have a Mikanko monster in your deck. Also, you can save it for a Pot of Avarice or Jar of Avarice follow-up.
      • Mikanko Rivalry: Works like a second Armory Call. Also can recover a Equip Spell from your GY.
      • Mikanko Spiriting Away: Works like a second Cross Over for Mikanko monters. Also can recover a banished Mikanko monster.
    • Mikanko Kagura: Non-target destruction equal to the number of equip spells in your GY.
    • The Great Mikanko Ceremony: Special Summon ANY Mikanko monster, pair with Ohime the Manifested Mikanko to recycle any Equip Spell from your GY. Also you can send a Mikanko card from your deck to the GY.
  • Reflecting damage cards: 
    • Monsters: 
      • Ha-Re the Sword Mikanko: Needs to be equipped to be a permanent reflector. Search any Mikanko Equip Spell when becomes equipped. 
      • Ni-Ni the Mirror Mikanko: Needs to be equipped to be a permanent reflector. Also it's a quick Change of Heart on your opponent's turn.
      • Hu-Li the Jewel Mikanko: Needs to be equipped to be a permanent reflector. Search any Mikanko Trap when becomes equipped. Also gives target protection to all Mikanko cards.
      • Ohime the Manifested Mikanko: Permanent reflector. Also it's a quick recycle for any Equip Spell from your GY.
      • Arahime the Manifested Mikanko: Permanent reflector. Also you can bounce any monster on the field during the End Phase.
      • Amazoness Swords Woman: One-time reflector. Give it battle protection if you want to get the most of it.
    • Spells:
      • Dark Sanctuary: It's a 50/50 half reflect. I need to check if it's effect applies to any attack or only when the controller is involved.
      • Fiend's Sanctuary: Special summons a one-time reflector monster.
    • Traps:
      • Dimension Wall: Conditional reflector.
      • Magic Cylinder: Conditional reflector. Old but gold :D
      • Zoma the Spirit: Special summons a "kind-of" one-time reflector monster.
  • Kaiju-like removal package: Get rid of any problematic card(s) on the board and get a big body on your opponent's field for reflecting damage.
    • Dogoran, the Mad Flame Kaiju
    • Lava Golem 
    • Volcanic Queen 
  • Goading cards package: 
    • Continuous effect:
      • Savage Colosseum: Board goad.
      • Yang Zing Unleashed: Board goad.
      • Battlin' Boxer Cheat Commissioner: Board goad.
      • Gravity Warrior: Targeted goad.
    • Conditional effect: 
      • All-Out Attacks: Goad any special summoned monster of the current player's turn.
      • Heavenly Gate of the Mikanko (also a Battle Interceptor card): Continuous Board goad if you control a equipped monster.
    • One-time effect: 
      • Battle Mania: Single board goad.
      • Staunch Defender: Single board goad.
  • Generic equip spells package:
    • Battle protection:
      • Heart of Clear Water 
      • Rocket Pilder 
      • Mist Body 
    • Battle interceptor:
      • Raregold Armor 
      • Ring of Magnetism 
  • Double damage cards package:
    • Smile Action: Pair with a permanent reflecting monster to recover 5 spell cards in your GY and doubles all the reflected damage.
    • Magical Cylinders: Recycle Magic Cylinder and doubles the next damage inflicted by them.
    • Massivemorph: Pair with a permanent reflecting monster to double all reflected damage.
    • Rise to Full Height: Pair with a permanent reflecting monster to double all reflected damage.

Notable Combos:

  • Ni-Ni the Mirror Mikanko + Mikanko Purification Dance: Take control of an opponent's monster, then, if your opponent special summons another one, bounce both cards.
  • To be continued...

Notable techs:

  • Armory Call
  • Cross Over: Get rid of any problematic card on the board and enable your Deck Master reflection.
  • Courageous Crimson Chevalier Bradamante: Faster Armory Call for your Deck Master or Amazoness Swords Woman.
  • Double-Edged Sword: Your opponent could take double damage but I need to check this card interaction with a judge.
  • Defense Zone: Use your monsters to protect your equip spells. Great card on the early game.
  • Final Attack Orders: Force your opponent's monsters to attack position, get the most of it paired with any Continuous Goading card.
  • Metalsilver Armor: Force your opponents to only target the equipped monster.
  • Vylon Matter: Mini Jar of Avarice for Equip Spells.

Cards for further testing:

  • Level Limit - Area B
  • Spirit Barrier and Astral Barrier combo
  • Level 4 Infernobles
  • Stax equip spells like Axe of Fools
  • Gearbreed
  • Elemental HERO Neos Kluger and Neos Wiseman package

This was my take to translate the MTG Goad concept to Yu-Gi-Oh! I hope you like it :D

We play on Discord often. Anyone can come ask questions or learn the format to build a deck. https://discord.gg/jGkRCJkt3d

Also you can check Yugioh Commander! video. https://youtu.be/jva6mdbDlWM

deck_description:
Metagame the graveyard-centric Masterduel meta with Punk Bystial! Spam handtraps like no tomorrow, including the recently released Bystial cards!

On top of PUNK's regular gameplan of drawing multiple cards and summoning Synchro boss monsters, Bystial adds free bodies (more level 6s and 8s to sync with!) on board, more resources in hand (Branded Regained/Magnumhut), additional interruptions (Branded Beast/anti-GY) and a way to counter those pesky Tearlaments that dominate the metagame!

Surprisingly, with the anti-GY powerhouse that Bystial provides combined with the draw power and synchro shenanigans that PUNK enables create a surprisingly competent deck - able to compete with the big meta decks like Branded, Spright and Tearlaments.

 
Want to see the deck in action? Scroll to the very bottom for the Youtube video!

This deck is a variant of my "Pure PUNK" deck guide I made last year, so If you want a complete guide with all the combos, tips and gameplans, visit my Pure PUNK article linked here.

This deck is also a Masterduel variant of the "Punk Bystial" deck guide I made back at January, linked here.

deck_description:
One of my favorite decks in the whole format (though that's my bias to Rock talking) Megarock is all about dumping out your deck to run head on at the opponent and hopefully do huge damage. This is done by stacking the deck full of rock monsters, having them be milled by the Jars/Merchant before then making a Megarock (s) and using the ever broken Dimensional Fusion to take full presence and run things over.

The monster lineup is pretty much ALL of the rock monsters....the good ones, at least. Golem Sentry is a low-key MVP that enables solid stall play while being a effective counter to opposing flip monsters or big beaters, being able to waste Noblemen slots on it while not being too much of a loss to your gameplan overall. Alongside Stone Statue's huge wall-like DEF stats and double damage, this typically gets you that early advantage to work off while setting up your stuff. 

Gigantes and Rock Spirit are also used given we can still use our rock resources to make similarly big monsters to establish aggro presence, not to mention they just get added to the pile as well as a 1/1. Granmarg is objectively the worst Monarch but can be still very useful as our alt-removal tech and primary target for Fusion to bring back given his big stats. Everything else is interchangable: some deck versions use more copies of Maharaghi or Elephant but I just couldn't see much of a use for them that aids the deck much for the big plays.

Spells are the usual lot minus Duo as we need the life points + there's not really a need for it in the deck, especially when most Chaos decks benefit from having stuff in the graveyard anyway. Card Destruction/Trunade allow huge presence regardless that controls the field more reliably. Rivalry especially is quite useful, especially when dealing with stuff like Panda Burn/more varied deck lots. 

Side deck works some typical popular format counters alongside working more of a PACMAN strat with Medusa Worm and co. Big Shield is a good 1 of tech that can fake out a nobleman play and get in extra damage. Sphinx is amazing regardless of the deck, and Lost Guardian is a weird nerfed Gran Maju that could maybe snatch a win or two from a opponent playing sloppy and charging into it.

deck_name: Lady of Lament Stardust Assault Mode
deck_excerpt: Assault Mode Activate is a Normal Trap I guess
deck_description:
Lady of Lament monsters synergize with Normal Trap Cards and Assault Mode Activate is a Normal Trap Card. So if we put two and two together, we get this Lady of Lament Assault Mode Deck, if you can even call it a Deck. 

For the Lady of Lament part of the Deck, we are playing the usual 3 Lilith, Lady of Lament, 3 Alice, Lady of Lament, 1 Sangan, and 2 Tour Guide from the Underworld. For the Assault Mode part of the Deck, 2 Stardust Dragon/Assault Mode, 3 Assault Sniper, 1 Assault Beast, and 3 Psi-Reflector. Stardust Assault Mode is probably the best Assault Mode option aside from Red Dragon Archfiend Assault Mode since its effect is reactive and it floats into something that is also reactive. RDA Assault Mode is probably the next best option due to your Extra Deck options for RDA like Scarlight whose name becomes RDA on field and in GY so RDA Assault Mode can be made with it and float back into it, but the Assault Mode's effect is after it attacked anyways which is slow and not as worth it. Assault Sniper is basically your access to Psi-Reflector not given E-tele and it allows you to just sit on Assault Mode Stardust with a bunch of backrow in the event you don't draw any Lady of Laments. Assault Beast and Psi-Reflector are just the usual Assault Mode package. 

For Spell/Traps: 3 Pot of Prosperity (This isn't necessary, but it is nice if you want to see both halves of your Deck), 3 Ties of the Brethren, 3 Emergency Teleport, 2 Dogmatika Punishment, 1 Trap Trick, 2 Assault Mode Activate, 2 Red Reign, 3 Infinite Impermanence, and 3 Solemn Strike. Assault Mode Activate is very searchable already and having more than 1 in hand and/or on field is not necessary as you will probably be sitting on an Assault Mode already from your 1 Assault Mode Activate you searched. Red Reign is an interesting removal option which banishes all other monsters on the field other than the monster with the highest Level if you control a Level 8 or higher Synchro. This can be a removal option before you go into Stardust Assault Mode as it only banishes other monsters and not backrow, so you still have all of your Traps to support you. 

For the Extra Deck: 1 Garura, Wings of Resonant Life for a draw when sent to the GY, 2 N'tss for a pop when sent to the GY, 2 Stardust Dragon for the Assault Mode stuff and because we can technically make more than 1 throughout the game, 1 Golden Cloud Beast - Malong which is a bounce when sent to the GY, 1 D/D/D Deviser King Deus Machinex and 1 D/D/D Stone King Darius for an Xyz body to make, 1 The Phantom Knights of Break Sword for removal, 1 Number 49: Fortune Tune, 1 Tri-Brigade Arms Bucephalus II for a larger body to send off of Punishment which sends a Beast, Winged Beast or Beast Warrior in return like Garura, 1 Evil Twins Trouble Sunny for an Ultimate Slayer target, 1 Dharc the Dark Charmer, Gloomy, 1 Paleozoic Cambroraster for backrow protection, and 1 Salamangreat Almiraj.

Side Deck isn't much. 1 Evil Twins Ki-sikil & Lil-la to send off of Trouble Sunny, 3 Alpha, the Master of Beasts and 1 Dinowrestler Pankratops for removal, 3 Ultimate Slayer, 1 Destructive Daruma Karma Cannon, 3 Evenly Matched, 2 Starlight Road as we are playing Stardust Dragon, and 1 Transaction Rollback as a cute tech option.

You can play Assault Reboot in this Deck as it is also a Normal Trap, but it requires you to play another brick in another Assault Mode name. The next best 1 you could go into for interruption is T.G. Halberd Cannon/Assault Mode as it negates a Summon and banishes all Special Summoned monsters your opponent controls and it floats into the normal Halberd Cannon which does the same thing. However, Assault Reboot must summon from Deck and it is impossible to hard summon the normal Halberd Cannon. The Assault Mode does float into it from GY ignoring its Summoning conditions which means you can send it from ED with Punishment, but it just isn't worth it.

deck_excerpt: You better run...You better hide...'cause they're coming...TO PLAY.
deck_description:
This is my tried-and-true competitive Melffy deck built from years of testing (and accessible reprints). The greatest strength of Melffies is...their friendship and ability to work together! Because that gives them access to more boss monsters than any other deck I've built! So let's get into it.

You've got the obvious 3-ofs, Puppy, Catty, Pinny, then 1 of the rest because they're all searchable and do things Melffies need. Wally's at 1 because you only need to trigger her once. Rabby, as cute as he is, is sadly unplayable. Fortunately, the devs kept him relevant by featuring his adorable face on Staring Contest, which is a good mulligan card and permanently nerfs the monsters your opponent currently controls. Kalantosa gets kinda bricky if you have too many, but he's not even soft once per turn, so 2 is perfect, especially if you open with one and that 1 Fenny in hand.

There's a small danger package for removal/free summons because Melffies struggle to do all that on your turn. White Steed helps you build Dragite, which tops off this deck's negation alongside Herald of Arc Light, Apollousa, Impermanence, and Melffy of the Forest. Kerass is a ss that helps you xyz or link. Nimble Beaver's your primary ns target. No Rescue Cat because that thing is so handtrap prone that it is dead weight, and unlike Beaver, leaves you with nothing on the board. You also can't xyz or synchro with it. Because Melffies don't deal big damage on their first turn, you're totally safe skipping your battle phase with Evenly Matched before you build a big invincible board to smash 8000-0 next turn. I've done it more than once.

I:P Masquerena is especially great for these little beasties because they summon on opponent's turn, so after you've gone through Kalantosa, link with her. Knightmare Unicorn's your option if you couldn't field anything else. If you get 4 monsters, you can go into Apollousa or Underworld Goddess (with Goddess' effect, they technically use the same amount). Summon whatever's best for what you're facing. Masquerena cannot summon Tri-Brigades, though. That will have to be on your turn, but Shuraig can banish on your opponent's turn when your Melffies summon.

You may have noticed a peculiar pick that isn't any kind of beast in this deck. This is my most recent inclusion. I added Icejade Ran Aegirine because this deck has searchable water monsters, and Ran is a free Gymir summon. Previously, I had to get one of the lvl 8 Dangers or Alpha and make it with Pinny, but now I can just discard Pinny instead. Having Gymir on the field pretty much guarantees my victory. Unless you DRNM her, there's virtually no way around because she can trigger on anything, and if you chain her, she removes that, too. And if your opponent likes to banish, she comes back. Swordsoul Chengying is just an additional target for the Ran playset. The only downside to running her is you have to hard draw her, but even if you open on all 3 copies, that's not a total brick because you can also discard a copy of her for her effect. 1 Gymir is WAY better than 1 anything else.

deck_excerpt: Evil Twin Spright / Germany National Championship Top 32
deck_description:
Category: Tournament Meta Deck

Tournament Meta Decks are current-level Meta Decks that are capable of going up against the best of the best. These are curated lists that cannot be uploaded by regular users.

Creator: Philipp Beck

Tournament: Germany National Championship - June 17th 2023 

Placement: Top 32

Hello there. Another intriguing casual OTK deck to showcase! Let's see how...

 

- Draw a lot of cards with Panda and Saryuja. Then...

 

1) Turn 1: Send Neko+Elephant+Slifer to GY. You can do as mentioned below to achieve this goal:

  • Via Saryuja, summon those 3 minions and send them to GY by Link summoning other monsters. It's easy to achieve if you play "Link Bound" and "Pot of Avarice" when Saryuja is either present onboard or in GY.
  • "One for One" and "Foolish Burial" accomplishes the same thing. Don't forget to target Elephant or Slifer first, then Neko for "One for One" to send those to GY. You will hit two birds with one stone by doing so. In the end, Link summoning any monster will take care of Neko.
  • Another way to send Elephant to GY is playing Saryuja >>> Monk >>> Elephant combo in order. Since "Flying Elephant" is level 4 monster, "Summoner Monk" can search it. Then, you can Link summon to send the Elephant to GY.

2) Set those cards below and end your turn. It doesn't have to be in order:

  • H - Heated Heart
  • Give and Take
  • 2 x Powerful Rebirth

3) On your opponent's turn (Draw Phase), activate those traps and specific targets in order. To activate traps even during Draw Phase of your opponent, change "Activation Confirmation" to "Switch+Hold" and set to "ON" in-game. You can edit to "Switch+Hold" in "Duel" section of settings page:

  • First, activate "Powerful Rebirth" and select "Neko Mane King"
  • Next, activate "Powerful Rebirth" and select "Flying Elephant"
  • Finally, activate "Give and Take" and select "Slifer the Sky Dragon". Target any minion but Link monster you have onboard.

- Chain reactions will lead into skipping your opponent's turn.

4) Buff your Elephant with "H - Heated Heart" and hit your opponent directly with Elephant to win the game.

 

Want to save up SR and UR? Let me show you:

 

- "Into the Void" can be unlocked through "The Infinite Void" Secret Pack to save 90 SR!

- "Slifer the Sky Dragon" can be unlocked through "The Great Olds" Secret Pack to save 30 UR!

- "Formula Synchron" isn't really needed, if you are low on SR. Though it can be unlocked by opening "Stardust Ties" Secret Pack, Saryuja and other Link monsters can pick targets to refill GY for "Pot of Avarice" more than enough. 90 SR saved!

- "Pot of Avarice" can be collected by purchasing "Re-Contact Universe" deck. 90 SR saved and you can try a new deck!

- "Wonder Wand" and "Spellbook of Knowledge" can be collected by purchasing "Spellbook of Prophecy" deck. 120 SR saved and you can try a new deck!

- "Link Spider", "Link Bound" and LAN are given for free, if you've picked "Link Generation". Thus, 90 SR is saved!

- "Moray of Greed" can be a good and cheap alternative for drawing cards. 2xExodia+5x1*-Water or 3xExodia+4x1*-Water are perfect formulae for this card without making Wand and Spellbook cards redundant.

 

So, in total, you can save up to 480 SR and 30 UR, if you are willing to spend some gems. Other SR and UR cards I didn't mention are essential.

 

That's all for this deck. Thanks for reading, feel free to ask anything. Have fun in Master Duel!

deck_excerpt: Clearing clutter better than your mother
deck_description:
Golem Control focuses around using the VERY loosely assoicated Golem cards for control over the field. Lava Golem keeps the field clean and burns, Golem Sentry bounces and acts as a mini-wall, and Dummy Golem is a free Creature Swap if you can pull it off: arguably even better as the "can't change position" restriction on that isn't on here, so you can use flip effects, attack, etc. This specific deck is pretty monster heavy, but the monsters used either boost up the consistency plays or let you get advantage one way or another.

I use cards like Momonga and Jujitsu Master as fake-outs for Nobleman plays, though they are also useful for establishing field presence if needed. Assailent is a must for a deck like this as it can pop + recycle all in a singular play. Gigantes plays off the overwhelming EARTH monsters in here.

Cretin is certainly weird old tech, however I felt like it really fitted here given it could either play into your other flip monsters or loop into itself if you have another in the graveyard. While the opponent also summoning isn't great, it's not a issue for this given there's so many ways of bouncing/tributing/switching threats away. Cretin into a Dummy to catch out someone using the special summon for a big play is always great to pull off and throws them for a loop given the card isn't well used, something the deck relies on to ambush them. 

Guardian Sphinx basically forces non-battle removal if you can get it going so it was also a obvious pick for this, super oppressive. To finish off we have Tribe for clearing the field (given the lack of Rock support in conventional decks we don't have to worry about wiping out cards of our own) and Serpent for cost fodder.

Spells are conventional. Swords is good for stall and Book of Moon is amazing tech for getting another flip effect off, escaping removal like Ring or simply shutting down the opponent. 

We run three Compulsory as it can delay the opponent massively while protecting the weaker monsters. Sunlight is underrated Goat tech that lets you escape a Nobleman or other more restrictive removal options. Threatening Roar is a top tier stall card and used here to keep your plays fresh for the next turn while controlling the pace more.

Side deck is varied, either throwing in more flip support, counters to popular builds or even trying for a Heavy Slump combo because why not, it's funny to do. This deck isn't obviously going to top nationals but it's extremely disruptive and provides a great range of cover for basically any monster thrown at you.

deck_excerpt: burn deck, now with more flips
deck_description:
Ok so this has been attempted a FEW times off and on, but the versions I've seen of this have been either too sacky or just relatively tame. This attempts to fix that with a more proactive build. 

So this is Cannon Soldier burn.....but it's got a Chaos Control build in it for a few reasons. For one, Scapegoat is the MVP of the deck: it's 2000 damage with a single card and monster. You need ways to recycle it, so Magician of Faith is perfect for that role and helps consistency, draw power...basically everything. I use Toon Soldier because you can mill it out with Toon Table to turn this into a 36 card deck if RNG is in your favour. Not really a reason to use the regular one aside from the attacking restriction....who cares about that though?

Second, Chaos Control builds well for keeping the pace of the game in your favour. Tomato/Sangan/Assailent all act as great additions that keep to the theme of making this deck very snappy and searches out your plays wherever far faster. Tsukuyomi is iconic in this kind of deck because it lets you reuse the flip effects, either for additional destruction, burning, or getting your plays back. Black Luster is very useful as a alt-win condition and/or easy removal. Koala is a cool dude and the easiest big damage card in the whole deck pretty much, plus Chaos fodder so no worries either way. 

Third is the meta mind-game that goes into a deck like this. The opponent expects burn....you throw Chaos at them. Vice versa as well. It plays them for a loop and makes side-decking a lot harder given you are trying to counter two popular builds as opposed to one. 

Alongside all of this we use the usual stall cards to keep the opponent's removal busy or do additional damage like with Wave-Motion. Thanks to the power of janky old technicalities Soul Exchange can be used as cost for Cannon Soldier's effect, letting you get essentially a Kaiju-lite removal + burn damage with ease on whatever you want. 

Side deck is a mix of going into actual Goat Control plays to throw the opponent off (not to mention it benefits you anyway given Thousand can stall as well until you get rid of it) going into Panda Burn to do more aggressive plays or simple and reliable counters to popular builds. Dustshoot is good for monster-heavy decks and Desert Sunlight protects your plays from someone throwing more Noblemen at you. Using this right, it's pretty reliable at what it does here.

Basic combo consists of NS Light or Past + Calling summoning the other one. Past eff banish Light -> Light eff summon Water -> Draw 2 -> Stardust Charge. Vision is basicly just 3 extra copies for that 2 card combo as it searches any of the other Fortune Lady cards. Your gameplan after that is to loop your Synchro back into the ED with De-Synchro to draw 2 via Water every time + generic draw spells.

Magical Stone Excav let's you dump the 2nd Water into the GY for Monster Reborn while also giving you a copy of any spell (usually De-Synchro) back. More than 1 felt incredibly bricky though. More than 2 Water also seemed suboptimal due to only ever being able to loop 2 anyway.

IOC + Souls not only works as Fodder for Allure in a pinch, Souls + Past + Water after the first De-Synchro also makes Moonflowerviewing wich is a non OPT draw 1. Add to that how you can use Chicken Game + Vision on field for another Draw 2 that doesn't affect your number of cards in hand for Mallet and it's easy to see why it's a must include.

The must haves for the ED are:

Charge Warrior (Past + Water w/ Past eff)

Moonflowerviewing (Past + Water + Souls)

Crocodragon (Past + Water + Water)

Any Lvl 5 (Past + Water w/ no Past eff)

Anything else is largely optional. Chaos Ruler won me like 2 games where the last Exodia piece was in the bottom 5 cards. Pep won some games solo after Allure banished a Exodia piece and might honestly be the most worth plan b card due to people just not reading it. Formula, Tatsunoko, Pixie & Sigma also all came up once, but thats in like 50-100 games played so def not needed if you aren't trying to win 1% more.

This archaic deck has not recieved support since mid 2016, but is still highly beloved by the playerbase. A unique combination and blending of "Star Wars" and "the Wizard of Oz", this deck has 2 types of cards: the Low Level Psychics, and the High Level Machines. The low level monsters banish themselves from the field to Special Summon a higher level "Kozmo" monster from your hand, and are able to pay LP for varying effects, while the high level monsters banish themselves from the GY to Special Summon a monster from your Deck, and have an On Summon effect with varying differences.

The deck is all about simorgh turboing the dragunity link to send destrudo to the gy and make AFD level 7 plays with kashtira or add more ceilling to the field by scareclaw twinsaw while also maintaning dark simorgh spell/trap negate, if you can't maintain this gameplan you can always fall back on kashtira, scareclaw and/or simorgh link plays. The deck can be all gas if you don't need the handtraps or more control variant, you can also add cards like dragunity Legatus with Divine Lance and Couse to make dragunity synchro plays like Dragunity Knight - Areadbhair. Take notes I leave pot in the side deck cause I wanted to play some boardbreakers/handtraps or going first options, but the pot in the main is probably the best option with evenly so you can break some boards and then follow up with some engine.

The deck plays by itself just do normal Lyrilusc plays and if you need extenders just search Simorgh, Bird of Beginning to double summon another copie to facilitate xyz plays. PS: I don't recommend pot because sometimes it will remove some tool that this deck struggles, like big towers or anything with more than 3100 atack but equalizers are so necessary to the game your only other go second play is zeus and only zeus, so play more handtraps or boardbreakers if you don't need this option. You can also add Harpie Link to instant activate Feather Storm to get some surprises from your opponent.

"Sharks" are series of Xyz focused WATER monsters, primarily Fish or WATER Extenders. Any 2 Level 4's make "Bahamut Shark", which is an easy line into "Number F0: Utopic Draco Future", by using Bahamut's effect to Special Summon "Number 47: Nightmare Shark", and Overlay "Full Armored Black Ray Lancer" onto it, then Xyz Summon "Number F0: Utopic Future", then Overlay Utopic Draco Future on top of it, if you aren't locked into WATERs.

Unfortunately, while the old Sharks only lock you into Xyz, and has level modulation for WATER Xyz, the new "Abyss Shark", the best monster in the archetype, locks you into WATER, and has level modulation for "Number" Xyz, which makes the UDF line a lot more awkward, as "Abyss Shark" requires all monsters you control to be WATER. The best way to skirt around this is to also make "Number 4: Stealth Kragen", which turns everything on the field to WATER Attribute, which is very helpful in locking out your opponent as well if you have "Gozen Match" available.

Sharks with "N.As.H. Knight". The Main Deck Shark support that came out last year are Level 5 monsters that can treat themselves as Level 3 or 4 for an Xyz Summon, but only that of a Number monster, meaning it's either "Number 4: Stealth Kragen" or the "N.As.H Knight" line into "Number C104: Umbra; Horror Masquerade".

C104 is a very powerful monster that was held back before by its difficult summoning conditions, and the difficult summoning conditions of its devolved counterpart, but "N.As.H Knight" and "N.As.Ch. Knight" make this process much easier, as long as you aren't locked into WATERs.

deck_description: Note this deck is not considered meta by the public as of posting.  This is the updated version of a pre-existing decklist I posted before.  Since then Mathmech Circular was limited which gave me room for adjustment.  This is the result.  I have testing the deck a lot and have found a lot of success with it.  In the comments of my previous post I explained how the combos worked.  Go to Transcending the Cyberse and you will be able to find the combos as they are the same.  Except for a little fun I added in the side deck.  TA.I Strike when combined with Donyoribo can inflict heavy damage to your opponent.  If you want to use Fire Phoenix instead of Heatsoul you can as well.  Phoenix when combined with Donyoribo can inflict 4600 damage in one effect.  Use Achichi's graveyard effect with Phoenix to destroy a monster your opponent controls in retaliation to getting attacked.  Water Leviathan can be added in as an extra target for Cyberse Witch to search in case you draw into Sage.  It can bounce any monster on the field with less attack than it.  It can also reduce a monsters attack to zero to return all of your link monsters from your graveyard into your extra deck.  This comes in handy if you need to reset your plays for follow up.  One of my friends hates having to deal with that.  Transcode Talker has been considered for a while now but there wasn't any room for it to be added in.  In case of an extra deck size increase in the future, you can add Transcode Talker, Wind Pegasus, Fire Phoenix, another Dark Templar, and another Splash Mage.  I have a feeling that the extra deck size might become 20 within a year or two.  With that increase, @Ignister will be able to overcome one of their major weak points being follow up.  They can use their entire extra deck in one turn other than Heatsoul which is the Fire target for A.I Meet You which turns Pikari into a one card combo starter as well as making an A.I Meet You in your hand into a smaller combo.  Still very strong though.  I have also considered adding in Prohibition as an extra anti-Nibiru and Droll card.  Declare their names and now they can't be used.  It doesn't work on stuff like Dimension Shifter which can be activated in response to it.  Speaking of which, Dimension Shifter can be added into the extra deck as a Crossout target.  One of my other friends said that it wasn't a good idea but it has won me a few games.  I still hate floodgate hand traps.  One time deals like Ash Blossom and Effect Veiler I am fine with but the floodgates of Droll and Dimension Shifter are annoying to deal with.  Luckily I can use three droll myself.  I am sorry if this was a bit much to take in.  And surprisingly this only lasted a few minutes.  I know I type a lot but this time I know I needed to share this much information.  And with that out of the way...  thank you for paying attention to me.  It means a lot to me.

deck_description: Horrible deck idea, make Ash Blossom & Joyous Spring  as big of a beat stick as possible! Meme deck.

Greetings. Here, I would like to show you how to FTK your opponent with IC1000. Let's get into the action...

 

1) Draw a lot of cards with Panda and Saryuja or Librarian and Formula until you reach the situation illustrated below. Don't forget to send "Neko Mane King" to the GY...

  • You need to have "Overlay Regen" + "Waking the Dragon" + "Powerful Rebirth" in your hand.
  • "Treasure Panda" must be able to Special Summon at least twice, to be exact.
  • "Silent Wobby" must be at the rightmost place while "Yajiro Invader" needs to be at the center. After that, Link Summon "Geonator Transverser" by using two effect monsters on the battlefield, which are Saryuja and Imduk in this case.

 

2) After you've Link Summoned "Geonator Transverser", activate her ability to swap pieces as illustrated below:

  • From here, we will Special summon a lot. Yajiro is trying to catch up whatever we will Special Summon while destroying everything he touches, which is essential for the IC1000 FTK combo.

 

3) Set "Waking the Dragon" to 2nd column...

 

4) ...and Special Summon a monster via "Treasure Panda" to 2nd column. What Yajiro is going to do is to move to 2nd column and destroy everything within his sight.

 

5) Thanks to the interaction between "Waking the Dragon" and "Yajiro Invader", we can Special Summon "Number C1000: Numerounius" on the battlefield. Special Summon this card to the 4th column, while Yajiro is trying to catch up.

  • Meanwhile, attach "Overlay Regen" into the C1000. If C1000 is destroyed with a material attached, this card can Special Summon IC1000 thanks to its effect.

 

6) Special Summon another monster via Panda one more time to the 5th column. There, Yajiro is trying to catch up 5th column while destroying C1000. While at it, set "Powerful Rebirth" card.

 

7) Thanks to the ability of C1000, condition is met. Therefore, we can Special Summon "Number IC1000: Numerounius Numerounia" on the battlefield. Put IC1000 to the 2nd column and watch Yajiro trying to catch up.

  • This is the final setup before ending our turn.

 

8) On your opponent's turn (Draw Phase), activate "Powerful Rebirth". Then, Special Summon "Neko Mane King" to the 4th column and let Yajiro kill Neko. Since your opponent's turn will be skipped thanks to the ability of Neko, IC1000's ability will be activated. It reads "At the end of your opponent's turn, if this card did not battle, you win the Duel." and victory shall be ours!

  • To activate any trap even during Draw Phase of your opponent, change "Activation Confirmation" to "Switch+Hold" and set to "ON" in-game. You can edit to "Switch+Hold" in "Duel" section of settings page.

 

Thanks for reading the guide. I hope you enjoyed reading it as much as I was preparing it extensively. If you want to look for means of saving up some SR and UR points, I got you covered:

- C1000 and IC1000 can be found within "Number Recall" Secret Pack to save 60 UR!

- "Allure of Darkness" can be found within "The Infinite Void" Secret Pack to save 30 SR!

- "Formula Synchron" isn't really needed, if you are low on SR. Though it can be unlocked by opening "Stardust Ties" Secret Pack, Saryuja and other Link monsters can pick targets to refill GY for "Pot of Avarice" more than enough. 90 SR saved!

- "T.G. Hyper Librarian" can be found within "Futuristic Creatures" Secret Pack to save 30 UR. However, you don't need to bother with him at all, if you don't want to spend SR on "Formula Synchron".

- "Neko Mane King" and "Silent Wobby" can be found within "Legacy Pack". Hope you were lucky to have them. Thus, 60 SR saved!

- "Pot of Avarice" can be collected by purchasing "Re-Contact Universe" deck. 90 SR saved and you can try a new deck!

- "Wonder Wand" and "Spellbook of Knowledge" can be collected by purchasing "Spellbook of Prophecy" deck. 120 SR saved and you can try a new deck!

- "Link Spider", "Link Bound" and LAN are given for free, if you've picked "Link Generation". Thus, 90 SR is saved!

 

So, in total, you can save up to 480 SR and 90 UR, if you are willing to spend some gems. Other SR and UR cards I didn't mention are essential.

 

That's all for this one. Let me know if you have any questions and have fun in Master Duel!

deck_name: A Beginner's Guide to Spright Runick Bystial (June 2023)
deck_excerpt: What happens when you mix three competitive advantage engines together? You get an extremely competent meta deck!
deck_description:
What happens when you mix three competitive advantage engines together? You get an extremely competent meta deck that will quickly outpace your opponents! Piloted correctly and skillfully, this deck can eventually reward you Masters 1 rank. 
 
Negate with Spright Red/Carrot, control and break boards with Runick spells, and deal with pesky graveyard with the newly introduced Bystials! In addition to searching from deck, all these archetypes draw cards as well, granting you up to 6+ cards per turn (Draw 3+ with Runick Fountain(s), draw 2 with Ipiria/Capshell in Sprights, and draw 1 with Branded Regained)!

With the Ishizu graveyard shufflers mostly gone and Tearlaments nerfed, Spright along with it's best buddy Runick is once again primed to take the competitive Masterduel meta crown by storm. Add Bystials into the mix, and now you have three advantage engines working flawlessly together to generate so much advantage/control that your opponent has no choice but to lose! 
 
This deck may be straightforward, but it rewards good decision making since boards and gamestates are determined by the pilot's skill and resource management. If you're a player who likes a resource-based control-focused grindgame, Spright Runick Bystial is the strategy for you.
 
Want to see the deck in action? Scroll to the very bottom for the Youtube video!
 
ARCHETYPES AND DECKBUILDING
 
Spright Runick Bystial is composed of the three mentioned archetypes. 

Spright creates solid boards by itself, offering draw power (Ipiria/Capshell), removal (Spright Smashers, Onibimaru Soul Sweeper), negates (Spright Red/Carrot), protection (I:P Masquerena->Avramax) and grindgame recursion (Spright Elf). 
 
Runick offers the main win condition of this deck by banishing your opponent's deck. It also can summon a level 2 to start off your Spright combo in the form of Runick Hugin while simultanously searching for Runick Fountain, allowing you to draw up to three cards. Runick spells also break opponent's boards fairly well when played correctly in tandem with the other archetypes. Runick offers solid defensive options in a pinch, with Hugin protecting against destruction effects while Geri dissuades the opponent from attacking. 
 
Bystial is the newcomer to this strategy, and it serves as a hard counter to popular meta and rogue decks on ladder since they banish crucial light/dark monsters in the GY, such as Tearlaments, Branded, Sky Striker and Eldlich. In these matchups a critical mass of Bystials often is a free win, especially since they generate so much advantage on their own especially with Branded Regained on the field. Bystials also are excellent going-second cards, allowing you to smash boards with their giant 2500ATK bodies before you lock yourself out of the battlephase with Runick cards. 
 
The rest of the cards are the generic must-have staples in Masterduel meta, with Ash Blossom, Maxx "C," and Crossout. Maxx and Ash are at two to prevent opening doubles of the same card. A 40 card deck is used since there are no garnets/bricks in the deck and to maximize consistency. 
 
COMBOS AND GAMEPLAN
 
The strategy of Spright Runick Bystial is to control/banish your opponent's cards until they surrender or deck-out. In certain situations, you can also enter the battle phase and OTK your opponent. The ridiculous resource advantage and control options each archetype gives the duelist should win them the duel in most circumstances. 
 
There is no particular combo line that this strategy uses. Mostly, this deck just summons Hugin to start off with the Runick portion of the deck. The presence Hugin then allows the special summons of Spright monsters so you can full combo. Bystials are not particularly "needed," but if you draw into Lubellion, Magnamhut and Branded Regained, it grants you massive resources, interruptions and free bodies on the field. 
 
The deck's endboard is similar to the usual Spright endboard, consisting of Spright Elf, Spright Red + Spright Carrot, and perhaps an I:P Masquerena/Djinn Buster. The backrow has Runick Fountain and perhaps Branded Regained with a set Spright smashers. That's not all to your "board," since the hand likely contains several Runick quick-plays, Bystials and generic handtraps! The interruptions that your opponent will have to slog through may number 3-7+, which every strategy will have to fear and respect. 
 
Since this is a toolbox control strategy, the use of each card is unique and situational - after Hugin -> Full Spright combo, the duel is usually non-linear. Instead, the game is dependent on the pilot's decision-making, resource advantage skills and knowledge of the specific match-up. If played maximimally, this deck can obliterate opponents going first and second, even through many interruptions. 
 
With the unique control each archetype offers and the draw 3-6+ every turn, your opponent should wither away while you snowball card advantage to victory. 
 
GENERAL TIPS
  • Similarly to Sky Striker, this is a toolbox control resource deck. It has a high skill ceiling since it factors in a player's decision making, resource management and match-up knowledge. Practice makes perfect with the deck!
  • Keep in mind that Spright Starter and Gigantic Spright lock you into only level/rank/link-2s! Don't lock yourself out of Bystials/Extra deck monsters at the wrong time!
  • Bystials are excellent when breaking boards, beating down small monsters and baiting interruption. Ishizu GY shufflers are particularly eager to use their effects when your Bystial summons from hand, so when they're used up you can safely use Spright Elf/Runick Fountain later on. 
  • This deck can generate so many bodies on board that it can easily OTK your opponent. If you feel your opponent cannot withstand your attack and they're out of resources, try to intentionally hold back from using Runick cards so you can enter the battle phase to finish them off!
  • When facing a multi-negate/interruption board, bait out cards until you can activate your strongest starter. The cards that absolutely must resolve if you want to win the duel is Runick Fountain's draw 3, or Spright Blue/Starter for the full combo. If you resolve either of these, you can usually slog through an opponent's board, no matter how hard they try. 
  • Remember, if Spright Elf is on the Extra Monster Zone, you cannot summon the defensive Runick fusions Hugin and Geri! Keep that in mind when facing certain match-ups (especially blind-second strategies), or if you feel a certain fieldwipe or attack is coming your way. 
  • In my opinion, this deck has no major choke points. If your Spright Starter or Runick Hugin get negated for example, you can pivot into the other archetypes and advance your gamestate!
  • Hugin's search effect for Runick Fountain isn't once per turn. If you can spare the cards, you can still search for Runick Fountain a second time! This makes Hugin ideal "Ash bait." 
  • If your opponent Maxx "C,"'s you, stop summoning and don't take the maxx c challenge! It's not worth giving your opponent more resources when you're righting a resource war.
 

Want to see the deck in action? Scroll to the very bottom for the Youtube video!

CONCLUDING REMARKS
I dunno about you guys, but drawing 5+ cards per turn is sooooo satisfying! Ending on a multiple negate board with 6 cards in hand makes you feel like the RICHEST, most ballin' duelist ever! The toolbox control gameplay is extremely fun and rewarding as well, since every game feels like winning a hard-fought battle utilizing a mastermind's tactician's decision making combined with a strategist's logistical mastery. 
 
The Runick archetype is thematically really cool, since it feels like the POV art of each Runick card feels like I'm fighting on the Yugioh battlefield and slaying monsters like the Doomslayer or Skyrim Dragonborn with my adventure party (yeah I know I'm such a nerd lmao). It is perfect for those of us who like to self-insert themselves into our duels with an over-active imagination and bring out the "RP" in Role-Playing Games! 
 
There is a reason why Spright variants are the most dominant deck on ladder right now, it outclasses Branded and Tearlaments because of it's sheer resource advantage and control capabilities. Able to go first and second while fitting soooo many generic staples in the deck and simultaneously hosting 3 archetypes seamlessly awards the strategy with so much versatility and power for every match-up. I dare say it's the perfect deck to climb ladder in Masterduel with! I'll see you guys at Masters 1 - I look forward to the mirror match.  

GLHF Duelists!

The build is actually really consistent. At worst case scenaro you draw more of the Spright side and go through a mini Spright combo line with the endboard being Gigantic Spright (1 material still), Djinn Buster, Spright Carrot or Red (or Smashers if you get it with Jet), and Sprind. At best your end board is the same but with Gigantic "Champion" Sargas and Therion "King" Regulus added which makes a really strong board. Zombie Domain deck

Based somewhat on the 2021 Phillip Harald version but with some modifications; his version didn't play any Vampire Lord, for example, which for me I didn't quite want to follow. Drain Zombie is all about abusing the incredible power of the Zombie engine in Goat alongside Skill Drain to disable everything else, giving you barely any issues as you play floaters and other monsters that bypass the typically devastating impact of the card, making for a impressively restrictive deck that tends to be a fantastic counter to many of the most popular decks used. For that reason almost every monster here does one or the other pretty much, even Sangan and Newdoria are used for that same reason. 

Spells are conventional. Creature Swap is used to run into your own floaters, Book of Life is just Zombie 101 and Smashing is top-tier removal for big plays that are hard to run over.

Traps focus mostly on either keeping the field controlled or using stuff like Dustshoot to get a good idea of what's being played against you alongside taking away potential big plays against what the deck tries to do.

Side deck plays Golem for easy removal (and a great target for running into your cards/Creature Swap) Jinzo/Spell Canceller to handle decks that opt hard into either/or. Zombra is handy for a deck like this given the downsides are practially removed in favour of a very big beater. The rest are more or less generic side-counters to popular plays. Overall the deck is pretty aggressive, and I really dug it when I was trying it out.

deck_description: WOOOOO MIC

Obviously it isn't, but this is about the best usage for the deck. The one that was used for the 2021 Championship was omega bricky and just didn't really have much of a chance against actual aggressive and/or control-based builds. The solution? Make it less about combos and more about flexibility. 

Emissary is a VERY good card in Goat Format, arguably underrated in some circles. It beats over most regular cards, searches on leaving the field, and is easily splashable in any deck that uses Normal monsters, AKA this one. Dragon Zombie is here for more beaters and Shine Balls are around for easy fodder for Smackdown to trigger alongside the usual Angel strat. The deck more or less relies on floating into everything while getting your Mokey on the field and angry for that big boost in ATK.

Spells aid by either stalling or teching around bigger targets, using Creature Swap to get rid of bounceable/weak monsters for better ones or Limit to benefit the usage of mostly sub level 4-monsters.

Traps aren't much to talk about. Skill Drain is a must in Emissary builds and it doesn't hurt the Mokey Mokey strat one bit. Human-Wave also helps if you have sacky plays that you want to run though.

Side-deck plays more into Chaos, conventional counters like Asura for Control or Hysteric to counter Ojama strats. Mobius is a useful tribute if required. Dancing Fairy is a weird one but if you can stall with her for a few turns she's pretty worth it just to handle Burn stuff. 

Siding into Goat Control is pretty easy given your Mokey Mokey's can also be played into Restrict, so it's not a issue throwing that in to blindside them. Combine that with a big aggro change into Decree and it turns into a drastically different deck altogether.

This deck performed beautifully.  4-0 through four rounds of swiss to take first place undefeated.  Performed beautifully against Traptrix, Branded, Flunder and Labrynth.

This deck was built to counter most decks, can go first or second.  Initially, was thinking of going extra deck plays with Kashtira, but put them in the side.  Extra deck ultimately is just Extrav fodder-- you absolutely don't need it.

Mikanko rivalry is clutch to put another card back on your mikanko to keep them from being destroyed by card effects and battle or equipping an enemy monster with Arabesque or Double-edged sword for OTK.  Arabesque is also just insane advantage.

Mikanko Kagura, the ritual spell, is perhaps the most useless card on the list and could be swapped for a second Great Mikanko Ceremony, which does a lot more for you with its banish effect to send a mikanko card to grave.  Also, don't sleep on the mikanko rivalry graveyard effect to banish itself and add an equip spell from grave to hand.

Ohime can win games by herself, as her quick effect allows her to grab an equip spell out of the grave to equip to a monster on the field.  If you have two mikanko names on board with equip spells, you can kaiju your opponent, swing twice and then use Ohime's quick effect in battle to equip a reflection rondo in grave to equip to the kaiju to snatch-steal and swing for game.

Going second, side in Lightning Storm, Interrupted Kaiju slumber, extra mikanko names if you need them.  Hidden Armory never came up, kashtira never came up, all could be replaced with better sides, maybe evenly matched or droll and lock bird.  Diviner is great for sending Herald to search Ohime which starts your plays, but going first it's nicer to set up floodgates.  3 Ohime and 3 Preperation of rites gets you where you need to be going incredibly consistently, prep is also good ash bait.  Lightning storm was clutch versus Lab.  Main deck feather duster was godlike for it too.

Anti banish can be incredible versus flunder and branded, TCBOO completely shuts down flunder plays.  Hu-Li when equipped with an equip spell makes ALL your mikanko cards untargetable for card effects, including the equip spells which shuts down a ton of labrynth plays.

This deck can go first or second and can content with meta decks.

Seal away evil with the power of the mikankos and have fun.

After only having played Master Duel my entire life i went to locals for the first time this week. First time around i played a relativly standard Branded CyDra MD style list, always going blind 2nd. However, while catching people off guard with the PB OTK won me 2 out of 3 game 1s - game 2 they just forced me first and without Verte drawing into your CyDra engine is completely worthless. Game 3 they'd play fully prepared for going first as they know i had no option but to blind 2nd making games incredibly difficult without the factor of suprise.

Going back to the drawing board after this experience i decided i'll try a complete smokescreen approach to combat this weakness in a Bo3 environment.

For context in my first locals i went 1-3:
Match 1 - D.Link (OXX) - PB OTK game 1, forced first game 2, fully prepared for blind 2nd game 3
Match 2 - Agents (OXX) - PB OTK game 1, forced first game 2, close lose in time by 500 LP
Match 3 - Scrap Dinos (XX) - Couldn't quite OTK game 1 (missplayed too), completely pop off game 2
Match 4 (Bye)

The 2nd time around with this deck i was able to go 3-1:
Match 1 - Runick Fur Hire (OXO) - (Megafleet helped me close out the first game a turn earlier but it was mostly Dragoon + Masq who did all the heavy lifting, didn't actually side in the CyDra cards game 2 & 3 as i think running over combo Runick variants is incredibly difficult.)
Match 2 - Ishizu Tearlament (XOO) - (Game 2 was just Branded but i was able to steal game 3 with a cheeky Twin Dragon OTK)
Match 3 - Floowandereeze (XX) - (Match was over in 5 minutes as my best play both games was Edge Imp Chain pass due to complete bricks, would've sided the CyDras here if i had won a game though)
Match 4 - LiveTwin Runick Spright (OXO) - (Same story as Match 1 were it was really just Dragoon doing the heavy lifting)

So due to 2 Runick matches and one quick 0-2 the funny part of the deck didn't actually come up too often, but it DID at least have some positive impact and was incredibly hilarious in the moments it did make an appearance.

For the main deck itself -
Magnamut - Would play it but sadly the seller i bought it from cancelled them on me last second so i had to make due (same thing for Fusion Deployment)
1-off targets for Crossout - Trying to maximize the impact the card has, as i am still not familiar with the meta game of the TCG there is def room for improvement here. Specifically the 1 Evenly & Droll seemed very good though.
50 cards - This can definitely be improved but as siding in itself is something completely new to me playing more cards and giving myself more leeway seemed like a reasonable thing to do even if the end result looks very ugly. Trimming it down to 40-45 is most definitely something i would work on if i am able to return to real life yugioh in the future.
Missing Branded/Despia cards - obv playing standard is better than whatever this is, but due to the side being funny smokescreen you kinda run out of space for non-engine. In practice this leads to games like i had vs Floo were you just draw going 2nd cards you main instead of your missing ways to get to your Branded lines buuut funny. 

In the ED i wasn't playing Dragostapelia due to not seeing a single Fusion deck my first time there and while Garura & Mud do take care of the same things Starving Venom does the simple fact it can run over cards they can't would've come up if i had played it in my original list. Alba-Lenatus is kind of similiar were i wish i had taken it over Fortress due to seeing 0 Machine decks but multiple Dragon decks. Rindbrumm i also figured could come up vs Floo etc, in the end it didn't help at all but i think it was a solid idea.

In conclusion to make this potentially a lot less silly - You'd probably only want to smokescreen the part of CyDra i was main decking (OG+Herz+Megafleet+Rampage+Twin) in a normal Branded list w/o 50 card main deck running going 2nd cards. This would give you the normal meta strenght of Branded while not clogging your side for the funny too much. And i think as a going 2nd engine that part actually is solid, def not the BEST option but something spicy to bring to locals for a laugh for sure.

This is a graveyard focused deck, but it a way that wants you to keep monsters OUT of your GY, and as much, "Dimension Shifter" is a useful addition. Their archetypal Field Spell shuffles all Madolche monsters in your GY into your deck, and gives all your Madolche monsters on the field a 500 ATK/DEF boost, and Continuous Spells that give you an extra Normal Summon of a Madolche, or more advantage if your monsters are shuffled into your deck, as well as handy effect negation of any of your opponent's face-up cards with their Normal Trap. Madolche has been one of the most resilient decks in yugioh's history, as it has been a competitive non-meta decks since "Madolche Anjelly" was released in 2014, which is impressive enough on its own.

deck_excerpt: nine out of ten flip monsters HATE him for this one weird trick
deck_description:
Wanghu is already pretty popular as a Warrior subtype more focused around King Tiger Wanghu, a card so weirdly written that even today it's found places as a strange niche tech option against some combo-heavy decks. This version focuses more around balancing a Warrior toolbox while trying to establish a actual identity for Wanghu as a main deck slot without it seeming too forced.

The monsters were easy; you play stat-heavy stuff that punishes the heavy usage of flip monsters in basically every deck worth mentioning. That means Blade Knight and the usual Warrior staples. Ninja works well for handling walls and having pretty great stats. It also works with getting Wanghu on the field via Art of Transformation. It's not perfect, but it can fly though the deck faster and even bypass some destruction attempts. Freed seems a bit weird but given how much LIGHT stuff you are using here he can be incredibly useful for alt-removal alongside being another good beater.

Spells are the usual Trinity, but 3x Smashing Ground means we can right away establish presence while getting rid of big threats. Nobleman, Reinforcement, you know the deal. 

Traps are a ;ittle bit more out there. Light of Intervention + Wanghu is a classic Lock strat, forcing the opponent to either waste their sub-1400 ATK monsters or hold on to them and clog the hand more. Getting this off on a unsuspecting Goat/Chaos Control deck can be crippling given half of their consistency comes from flip monsters and/or floating into things. Transformation seems a bit dodgy but I think it really clicked with the deck and allowed it a ton more flexiablity despite the limitations of the card. It can be easily sided out anyway so I wasn't that bothered.

Everything else is just the usual, focusing on removal of backrow and monsters when needed to keep the game firmly under your pace.

Side deck throws in Chaos given the relatively easy synergy between what's being used here. Mobius is a handy backrow killer with solid stats. Some extra traps to focus more on hard negations, pretty basic but strudy cover.

deck_excerpt: Pendulums to provide the swarming and consistency your equip deck needs!
deck_description:
Igknights provide extremely consistent access to the starters and boss monsters Infernoble Knights need, as well as aiding with swarming. They also enable you the search off of Isolde, since she doesn't negate the pendulum effect of the monster searched. Isolde's summon from deck is a pretty brutal choke point, but I think this is probably the best version of Infernoble Knights.

 

The goal of this deck is to draw at least 2 Igknights to search Sublimation Knight, which equips Squeaknight from deck to make Isolde. Isolde searches another Igknight, which can use its pendulum effect to search IPG later. Use Isolde to summon Ogier from deck, who dumps Turpin to grave. If possible, use Durendal to acquire Ignis Phoenix, scale up and pendulum summon as many monsters as possible. From there it's up to you.

 

Depending on your hand, you can use Turpin to help you make Angelica, searching Horn of Olifant, or go into Ignister Prominence, or straight into Baronne or Charles. From there, you can use any monster + Isolde to make Spright Sprind, which dumps Ringowurm from deck. Ringowurm banishes itself to summon a token, allowing you to make any of your synchros, depending on what's still on board. If you have Charles, you can add Divine Sword Phoenix Blade back to hand and equip it to Charles. This lets you activate Turpin's other effect, summoning himself from grave. Overlay him and any level 4 for the Battlin' Boxer Xyz, which searches the Counter Trap and turns Spright Sprind online. Link off the Charles for Charlemagne, giving you a S/T negate. If you have both the Battlin' Boxer counter trap, use his effect to destroy the equipped Charles (unless you control the field spell and can summon Charles out). You need the zones. Use Ogier's effect to equip him from grave.

At any point in this combo, you can use a second wave of Igknights to search IPG. If you managed to get Ignis Phoenix, this summons an additional tuner from deck (of any level, since it can be any Igknight) and extends your combo dramatically. Summon IPG by banishing anything. Set Horn of Olifant and the Battlin' Boxer Counter Trap, then during End Phase equip anything from grave and Oliver from deck. This gives you a Charlemagne that's untargetable and indestructible (at 3.8k if you equip Phoenix Blade from grave and don't have the field spell) and ends you on a S/T negate in Charlemange, a monster negate in IPG, a monster negate in the counter trap, a pop in Horn of Olifant, a bounce in Spright Sprind, and anything else you managed to get from your synchros (could be Baronne, could be Muddy Mudragon into Mirrorjade, could be Omega). If you happened to draw Morgan that's an extra omni right there too.

Morgan is to try and provide some protection for Isolde because that's a pretty bad choke point, but if you don't draw the equip to facilitate that, it's still pretty good later because Charlemagne will equip a Noble Arms from grave, turning her online.

 

The side deck is full of other options I was considering. The Mikanko cards make a pretty good engine with Renaud, allowing you to cut down on the number of equip spells you're running, since you can send just Water Arabesque to summon him. He adds back Water Arabesque, which you equip to summon Ha Re from deck. Search Fire Dance. Summon Renaud back from hand, synchro for Cupid Pitch. Cupid Pitch become level 5, use Fire Dance to summon back Ha Re, synchro for Scarlight and search Performapal Handstandcoon because why not. Pend summon your previously destroyed Igknights, use one + Isolde to dump Ringowurm, Ringowurm banish to summon a token. Token + Scarlight for Dis Pater. Dis Pater summon back Ringowurm. Ringo + Igknight for whatever synchro is applicable (Muddy Mudragon is probably the best in this case. Since you don't have Turpin in grave, you only have access to the Xyz if you were lucky, so Spright Sprind isn't online, meaning you can use Muddy Mudragon + Sprind for Mirrorjade and lose nothing).

Additional Ringowurms in the main deck probably wouldn't be bad because it's a free tuner SS, but I don't think I can justify it because it's pretty important to open 2 Igknights with this strategy.

It's too bad the Battlin' Boxer counter trap doesn't negate S/T, so it doesn't protect you from Dark Ruler, but having 2 disruptions + a boss monster that's untargetable & indestructable through Dark Ruler is still pretty good.

Great idea by JayDub, go check out his channel:

https://www.youtube.com/@JayDubDaGadget

All gas combo deck that combines some of the best aspects of zombies, horus, and a little bit of Ishizu to create extremely difficult to break boards with the floodgate benefits of zombie world.

You always want to go first.

Here's how the deck functions:

1. Use Imsemity, Magical Contract Door into Imsemity, Trade-In, or any other draw to get Pharonic Sacophagus.

2. Use Pharonic Sarcophagus to dump your zombies with useful graveyard effects to also dump your other Horus monsters into the graveyard.

3. Use three of your Horus monsters to go into Coach King Giant Trainer.

4. Refill your hand then use your dumped Mezuki to res one level 8 and use the final Horus monster to go into The Zombie Vampire.

5. Link both The Zombie Vampire and Giantrainer into Vampire Sucker.

6. After these 3 steps you should have a sizeable number of zombies in your graveyard, use their discard and ressurection effects to go into Barone, Link Vampire Sucker into Apollousa, Synchro Borrelsword dragon, using whatever remaining resources to either Ressurect Hapy or go into additional Synchro's. At the start of your opponents standby phase Use Doomking's effect to ressurect.

7. You should now have a 3 uses of Appollousa, Barone, Borrelsword, Doomking, and at least Hapy for 6 negates on the board.

Some tips for the deck Include:

As long as Sarcophagus remains on the field you have access to 4 level 8 summons every turn. Your negates should be used to protect it.

Barone's negate should be used on the first non-monster board wipe effect instead of Borreload, as on the following turn Barone can float into one of your level 2 tuners which can then synchro 1 of your 4 horus ressurects per turn to infinitely refresh Barone on the field.

Foolish Burial should be used on your Ishizu cards that excavate 5 as your likely to hit multiple useful zombies.

Hapy is generally the Horus monster you want to end on your board as it's effect can add both zombie world and sarcophagus back to your hand should your opponent manage to destroy them.

This deck has an absolutely insane grind game, the longer the game goes on the more likely you are going to win, so try and stall.

The horus monsters cannot be ressurected by your mezuki's unless zombie world is up, so try and get a necroworld banshee into the graveyard sooner rather than later.
